-19/|archive-date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ScotlandCumulativeCasesByRegion23April2020.svg|alt=|frameless|1170x1170px]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n** [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in England]]\n*** [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in London]]\n** [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland]]\n** [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Scotland|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|Scotland]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Scotland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Scotland\n| image           = File:Kilmarnock during lockdown, 2020.jpg\n| caption         = John Finnie Street in [[Kilmarnock]], during lockdown measures, showing a busy shopping street empty\n| map1            = <!-- Please do not add maps showing spread of the virus without gaining consensus on talk page-->|legend1\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Scotland]]\n| first_case      = [[NHS Tayside|Tayside]]\n| arrival_date    = 1 March 2020 <br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=01|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = Northern [[Italy]] ([[Local transmission|local]])<ref name=first>[https://scottishfinancialreview.com/2020/03/01/coronavirus-first-case-is-confirmed-in-scotland/ Coronavirus: first case is confirmed in Scotland] 1 March 2020 ''scottishfinancialreview.com'', accessed 8 April 2020</ref><br>[[Wuhan]], China (global)\n| confirmed_cases = 9,038 total cases with a positive test (as of 22 April 2020)<ref name=ArcGISUK>{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/ |title=Total UK cases COVID-19 Cases Update |website=coronavirus.data.gov.uk |access-date=17 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"cis\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus in Scotland |url=https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/ |website=gov.scot |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330164929/https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/ |archive-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| hospitalized_cases    = 1,776 patients currently in hospital with either confirmed or suspected Covid-19 symptoms including those in ICU (as of 22 April 2020)\n| suspected_cases = \n| critical_cases    = 155 patients currently in [[intensive care unit|ICU]]s (as of 22 April 2020), includes:\n* 147 tested positive cases\n* 8 suspected cases\n| recovery_cases  = 1,813 hospital patients who have tested positive have been discharged since 5 March 2020 (as of 22 April 2020)\n| deaths          = 1,062 total confirmed-only cases as of 22 April 2020</small><ref name=ArcGISUK/><ref name=\"cis\"/> <br><br> 1,616 total including all confirmed and suspected Covid-19 cases recorded on death certificate (as of 19 April 2020), by setting:\n* 910 in hospitals (as of 19 April 2020) \n* 537 in care homes (as of 19 April 2020) \n* 168 in personal homes (as of 19 April 2020) \n* 1 in other (including prisons) (as of 19 April 2020)\n| territories     = [[Health Protection Scotland]] (HPS) and [[National Records of Scotland]] (NRS) data includes the [[NHS Scotland]] [[NHS Scotland#Health boards|regional health boards]] where the deaths were registered\n| website         = [https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/ Coronavirus in Scotland]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]] was first confirmed to have spread to [[Scotland]] on 1 March 2020 with the [[COVID-19 testing|positive COVID-19 test]] of a male Tayside resident who recently travelled to and from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|northern Italy]]. <ref name=first/>\nScottish coronavirus cases are also included in the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]].\n\nAs of 22 April 2020<ref>https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-daily-data-for-scotland/</ref>, a total of 43,309 people in Scotland have been tested for COVID-19. \n9,038 tests were confirmed positive. \n34,271 tests were confirmed negative. \n1,062 patients who tested positive have died.\n\nAs of 21 April 2020, 495 (or 46% of all) [[Care home|adult care homes]] in Scotland had reported at least one notification for suspected COVID-19 to the [[Care Inspectorate (Scotland)|Care Inspectorate]]. \n308 of these adult care homes have reported more than one case of suspected COVID-19.\n384 (35%) adult care homes have a current outbreak of suspected COVID-19. This is a care home where at least one care home resident has exhibited symptoms during the last 14 days.\nThere have been 2,085 cumulative cases of suspected COVID-19 in care homes. This is an increase of 212 suspected cases on the previous day.\nA total of 7,210 staff, or around 4.3% of the [[NHS Scotland]] workforce, are reporting as absent due to a range of COVID-19 related reasons.\n599 people are in [[inpatient care|delayed discharge]] in [[Scottish hospitals]]. This is 1,013 less than the baseline period (04/03 weekly return).\nOn 18 April 2020, the [[Scottish Ambulance Service]] (SAS) have made 404 attendances for suspected COVID-19, and have taken 250 people to hospital with suspected COVID-19.\n1,813 inpatients have been discharged from hospital since the 5th March, who had been tested positive for COVID-19.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{align|right|{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Scotland medical cases chart}}}}\n\n===January\u2013February 2020===\nIn late January, five people were tested for COVID-19 in Scotland, all returning negative as an incident team was established for the disease.<ref>{{cite news |title=Incident team set up as five tested for coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51223111 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=24 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130180423/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51223111 |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> By 10 February, 57 tests had been conducted (all negatives),<ref>{{cite news |title=More than 50 people tested for coronavirus in Scotland |url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/scotland/more-than-50-people-tested-for-coronavirus-in-scotland/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Evening Express]] |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> a figure which rose to 412 by 25 February.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus preparations stepped up in Scotland |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51638363 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=25 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303035026/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51638363 |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> COVID-19 was made into a \"[[notifiable disease]]\" on 22 February,<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus becomes 'notifiable disease' in Scotland |url=https://www.holyrood.com/news/view,coronavirus-becomes-notifiable-disease-in-scotland_15145.htm |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=[[Holyrood (magazine)|Holyrood]] |date=21 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and a surveillance network involving 41 GP locations was established to submit samples of suspected patients, even if they had no travel history.<ref>{{cite news |title=Surveillance testing system for Covid-19 begins |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51690868 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=1 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301034710/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51690868 |archive-date=1 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\n[[File:Dont panic, but were dooomed! (geograph 6415311).jpg|thumb|left|Goods sold out following [[panic buying]] in a supermarket in [[Morningside, Edinburgh|Morningside]], [[Edinburgh]].]]\nThe first confirmed case of COVID-19 in Scotland was on 1 March, when a resident of [[Tayside]] tested positive for the disease. The person had then recently travelled to Italy. At that time, since the outbreak began in [[Wuhan]], there had been 698 tests resulting negative for the disease.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scotland confirms first case of coronavirus |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/scotland-coronavirus-first-case-a4375406.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=[[Evening Standard]] |date=1 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302160734/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/scotland-coronavirus-first-case-a4375406.html |archive-date=2 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two further cases were confirmed on 4 March, one having travelled from Italy and the other having had contact with a known carrier.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Two more Scotland cases confirmed as UK total hits 90 |url=https://www.cityam.com/coronavirus-three-scotland-cases-confirmed/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=[[City A.M.]] |date=5 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306151730/https://www.cityam.com/coronavirus-three-scotland-cases-confirmed/ |archive-date=6 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Two new coronavirus cases confirmed in Scotland |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/two-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-scotland-lc68rv7rc |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=4 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309102323/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/two-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-scotland-lc68rv7rc |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Three further cases were confirmed on 5 March<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus in Scotland |url=https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/ |website=gov.scot |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305145636/https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/ |archivedate=5 March 2020}}</ref> and by 6 March, the number of confirmed cases had increased to 11.<ref>{{cite news |title=Number of Scottish coronavirus cases rises to 11 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51765401 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=6 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307224841/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51765401 |archive-date=7 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> This had more than doubled to 23 cases by 9 March, out of 2,101 tests conducted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus LIVE: 23 cases confirmed in Scotland |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18291008.coronavirus-live-23-cases-confirmed-scotland/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]] |date=9 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310155827/https://www.thenational.scot/news/18291008.coronavirus-live-23-cases-confirmed-scotland/ |archive-date=10 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the first death from COVID-19 in Scotland was confirmed, of an elderly patient with underlying health conditions. At the time, 85 cases of the disease had been confirmed out of 3,314 tests conducted.<ref>{{cite news |title=First Scottish coronavirus death confirmed |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51874899 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140926/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51874899 |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> By 16 March, 171 cases had been confirmed from 4,895 tests, with positive cases being reported by all health boards of [[NHS Scotland]] except in [[NHS Orkney]] and [[NHS Western Isles]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Number of Scottish coronavirus cases rises to 171 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51912612 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316141140/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51912612 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs of 24 March 16 patients with confirmed cases of COVID-19 have died.<ref name='cis'/> Approximately 0.17% of the population has been tested as of 23 March 2020. However those showing symptoms have been advised to stay at home and are still not being tested.\n\nOn the 25th of March, the First Minister confirmed that the Scottish Government was establishing a COVID-19 Advisory group to would supplement the advice it was receiving from the UK-wide Scientific Advisory Group on Emergencies. It is being chaired by Professor Andrew Morris of Edinburgh University, the Director of Health Research UK, with support from vice chair David Crossman, who is the Dean of Medicine at the University of St Andrews and Chief Scientific Advisor for Health at the Scottish Government <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/first-minister-covid-19-update-2/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) update: First Minister's speech 25 March 2020|date=2020-03-25|work=Scottish Government Statement|access-date=2020-03-28|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nAs of 26 March it was announced that 25 deaths have been reported.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-52036314|title=Six more coronavirus deaths announced in Scotland|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n[[File:Glasgow. West George Street during coronavirus lockdown 1583..JPG|thumb|Glasgow. An empty West George Street during coronavirus lockdown. 8 April 2020.]]\nLate on 5 April 2020, despite initially saying she would stay in office, Scotland's chief medical officer, Dr [[Catherine Calderwood]], resigned after making two trips to her second home, breaking the coronavirus lockdown she and First Minister Sturgeon had encouraged.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-52177171|title=Calderwood resigns over coronavirus lockdown trips|date=2020-04-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2020, the [[Coronavirus (Scotland) Act 2020]] which was introduced as an Emergency Bill in the Scottish Parliament on 31 March 2020 gained Royal Assent, becoming law.\n[[File:Glasgow. Argyle Street during coronavirus lockdown.DSC 1510..JPG|thumb|[[Glasgow]]. [[Argyle Street, Glasgow|Argyle Street]] during coronavirus lockdown, one of the main shopping streets in the city centre. 7 April 2020.]]\n\n==Response plan==\n\n===Scottish government===\n\nThe key Scottish Government officials in Scotland leading the response to the outbreak are:\n\n*[[First Minister of Scotland]]: [[Nicola Sturgeon]]\n*[[Cabinet Secretary for Health]]: [[Jeane Freeman]]\n*[[Minister for Public Health]]: [[Joe FitzPatrick]]\n*[[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer for Scotland]]: Dr [[Gregor Smith]] (Acting)\n*Chief Scientist: Professor David Crossman\n*Chief Nursing Officer Professor: [[Fiona McQueen]]\n*National Clinical Director: Professor [[Jason Leitch]]\n\nDr [[Catherine Calderwood]] was Chief Medical Officer until her resignation from the post on April 5. Calderwood resigned following a photo of her and her family at their holiday home in [[Fife]] breaching the advice she had issued publicly in Scotland via the media in order to prevent the spread of COVID-19. In a briefing, Calderwood acknowledged her mistakes and revealed that she had in fact gone to her holiday home in March. On April 4, Dr Cathrine Calderwood attempted to resign from the post of Chief Medical Officer following the publication of the photos in the media, however First Minister Nicola Sturgeon refused her resignation at this time. After a large media backlash, Sturgeon accepted her resignation on April 5, and replaced Calderwood on an acting basis with the Deputy Chief Medical Officer, Dr Gregor Smith.\n\n===Containment measures===\n\nScottish First Minister [[Nicola Sturgeon]] announced a ban on mass gatherings (500 or more) on 12 March, with the ban starting on 16 March.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news |title=Mass events ban as coronavirus cases spike |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51851341 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313084748/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51851341 |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A number of schools have been closed due to reported symptoms, and would be undergoing deep cleaning.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite news |title=Some schools close for coronavirus deep clean |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51904721 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316141218/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51904721 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Football matches in the [[Scottish Professional Football League]] were cancelled until further notice, alongside a [[Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] game between [[Wales]] and Scotland. [[Radio 1's Big Weekend]], which was due to take place in [[Dundee]] in May 2020 was cancelled in response to the outbreak.<ref name=\"closed\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus in Scotland: Which Scottish events have been cancelled due to COVID-19?\n |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18304715.coronavirus-scotland-scottish-events-cancelled-due-covid-19/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=[[The Herald (Scotland)|The Herald]] |date=14 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On 18 March, it was announced that schools in Scotland would be closed starting on 20 March.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">{{cite news |title=Schools in Scotland and Wales to close from Friday |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51928400 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Advisory group===\nOn March 25, the Scottish Government set up an expert advisory group to help develop and improve its COVID-19 response plan.\n<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.scot/groups/scottish-government-covid-19-advisory-group/ | title=Scottish Government COVID-19 Advisory Group - gov.scot |date=  |website=www.gov.scot |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Public health agency===\nOn 1 April 2020, the Scottish Government launched the new [[Public Health Scotland]] agency.\n\n===Testing capacity===\n{{see|COVID-19 testing}}\n\nNHS Scotland's testing capacity for COVID-19 increased from around 750 a day in early March<ref>{{cite news |last1=McArdle |first1=Helen |title=Helen McArdle: WHO says 'test, test, test' - so has the UK really dropped the ball in the fight against coronavirus? |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/opinion/18351445.helen-mcardle-says-test-test-test---uk-really-dropped-ball-fight-coronavirus/ |work=HeraldScotland |date=2 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> to about 1,900 a day in early April.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nBy March 15, coronavirus testing was extended into Scotland's communities but there would be no routine testing of people with minor symptoms.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51895936 Coronavirus: Scottish Covid-19 testing expanded to communities] 15 March 2020 ''www.bbc.co.uk'', accessed 8 April 2020</ref>\n\nNHS Scotland plans to reach a testing capacity of around 3,500 a day by the end of April.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McArdle |first1=Helen |title=Coronavirus: Scotland on track to hit 3,500-a-day testing goal by end of April - but peak could already be over |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18351470.coronavirus-scotland-track-hit-3-500-a-day-testing-goal-end-april---peak-already/ |work=HeraldScotland |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/52149297 |title = How England has been lagging behind on testing|work = BBC News|date = 8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Glasgow University]] is to launch a major coronavirus testing facility in mid-April, staffed 24/7 by more than 500 volunteers including molecular scientists, technicians and bioinformaticians.\n\n[[Aberdeen University]] has provided three machines to [[NHS Grampian]] to speed up coronavirus testing.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/politics/scottish-politics/2119516/aberdeen-university-provides-three-machines-to-nhs-grampian-to-speed-up-coronavirus-testing/ |title = Aberdeen University provides three machines to NHS Grampian to speed up coronavirus testing}}</ref>\n\nBy 2 April 2020, around 3,500 tests have been conducted on NHS workers and family members in Scotland. It was also reported in that week that around 6pc of Scotland's frontline NHS staff are not currently working, either because they have coronavirus symptoms or live with someone who has.<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{Cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/04/02/coronavirus-mass-testing-distraction-will-not-slow-spread-scotlands/ |title = Coronavirus mass testing a 'distraction' that will not slow spread, Scotland's chief medical officer says|newspaper = The Telegraph|date = 2 April 2020|last1 = Johnson|first1 = Simon}}</ref>\n\nChief Medical Officer for Scotland [[Catherine Calderwood]] described mass testing as a distraction that will not slow down the spread of the virus. She said: \"I have been saying and advising the First Minister and the Cabinet Secretary for several weeks now about the distraction that I think the focus on testing may become. The testing is extremely useful but it is only going to be positive within a short window of perhaps 48 to 72 hours while somebody has symptoms, because there needs to be an amount of virus in that person to be able for that to be detected. But the thought that the testing in some way slows the virus or is a part of our strategy to prevent transmission is a fallacy, I\u2019m afraid. The testing gives us more information but the social distancing and all of these stringent measures are what we actually need to prevent spread and prevent serious illnesses and death.\"<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/coronavirus-row-over-testing-could-distract-from-real-fight-says-calderwood-db8djdlbd | title=Coronavirus: Row over testing could distract from real fight, says Calderwood}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph1\"/>\n\n[[Cam Donaldson]], a health economist and Pro Vice Chancellor Research, Glasgow Caledonian University\nhas written of his scepticism of a \"mass testing\" strategy. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://theconversation.com/coronavirus-as-a-health-economist-im-not-convinced-the-case-for-mass-testing-stacks-up-135257 |title = Coronavirus: As a health economist, I'm not convinced the case for mass testing stacks up}}</ref>\n\nDerek Gatherer a leading Scottish virologist has warned plans to test, trace and isolate everyone infected with the coronavirus after lockdown will not slow its spread.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/coronavirus-in-scotland-doubts-over-test-trace-and-isolate-approach-zcqvxrhh9</ref>\n\nExperts who have advocated a mass or large scale testing approach include [[Harry Burns (doctor)|Harry Burns]] former Scotland Chief Medical Officer<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/coronavirus-in-scotland-test-that-could-end-lockdown-set-to-be-available-within-weeks-says-harry-burns-h0w8ljtbw</ref> and Allan Wilson President of the [[Institute of Biomedical Science]]<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-scotland-52324722/page/6</ref>\n\nA coronavirus testing facility for NHS staff was opened at [[Glasgow Airport]] car park on April 5th.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.stv.tv/west-central/coronavirus-testing-facility-to-open-at-glasgow-airport |title = Coronavirus testing facility to open at Glasgow Airport|date = 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Contact tracing system===\n[[Ciaran Jenkins]] of [[Channel 4 News]] contrasted the differing approaches on [[contact-tracing]] strategy between the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland|Republic of Ireland]] and the  health authorities in the UK including Scotland's.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.channel4.com/news/the-race-to-trace-has-the-uk-abandoned-coronavirus-contact-tracing | title=The race to trace: Has the UK abandoned coronavirus contact tracing?}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/scotland/1239460/contact-tracing-no-longer-taking-place-as-scots-told-social-distancing-could-be-more-important-than-testing-in-coronavirus-fight/ | title=Contact tracing no longer taking place as Scots told social distancing could be more important than testing in coronavirus fight}}</ref>\n\n===Primary care network===\nHealth Secretary Jeane Freeman said in a statement in the Scottish Parliament a network of Covid-19 local assessment centres was to be set up across Scotland with 50 planned in the first wave.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-52022833 |title = Scottish NHS to quadruple intensive care beds|work = BBC News|date = 24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.channel4.com/news/scotlands-nhs-using-unique-system-to-treat-coronavirus-patients | title=Scotland's NHS using unique system to treat coronavirus patients |work = www.channel4.com/news|date = 24 March 2020 |accessdate = 11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.scot/news/new-nhs-24-arrangements-for-coronavirus/ | title=New NHS 24 arrangements for coronavirus - gov.scot |work = www.gov.scot/news|date = 23 March 2020 |accessdate = 11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ardrossanherald.com/news/18327389.coronavirus-community-hubs-open-covid-19-spreads-ayrshire/ |title = Coronavirus community hubs to open as COVID-19 spreads in Ayrshire |work = www.ardrossanherald.com |date = |accessdate = 11 April 2020}}</ref>\nA network of \"humanitarian assistance centres\" is also to be set up, working with GPs and other local partners to arrange delivery of medicine, care services and grocery delivery.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18357909.jeane-freeman-tackle-coronavirus/ |title = Jeane Freeman: This is what we're doing to tackle coronavirus  |work = www.thenational.scot |date = |accessdate = 11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Personal protective equipment===\nOn 2 April, new guidance on appropriate [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) for healthcare hospital, general practice, ambulance and social care workers responding to Covid-19 has been issued by officials.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-52138878 |title = New safety guidance for health and care staff|work = BBC News|date = 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Police===\n[[Scottish Police Federation]] (SPF) claimed new PPE for officers would not provide any \u201cmeaningful protection\u201d, after [[Police Scotland] announced staff would be given surgical face masks to wear when adhering to [[social distancing]] measures was not possible. But the SPF said that its new expert pandemic response panel refused to endorse the type two masks.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/apr/18/coronavirus-live-news-global-deaths-pass-150000-trump-china-china-denies-any-concealment-pence-origins-europe-germany</ref>\n\n===Care homes===\n[[The Guardian]]'s Libby Brooks reported that extra supplies of [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) will be delivered directly to more than 1,000 care homes in Scotland.\n\nBefore the pandemic the care sector usually sourced its own PPE, but as extreme pressure was put on supply chains concerns grew that PPE manufacturers did not have capacity to deliver to Scotland in adequate quantities.\n\nThe Scottish government announced on 17/18 April that the [[NHS National Services Scotland]] would prioritise the delivery of stock directly to care homes where the virus is known to be present, although stock would still be provided to local hubs which supply PPE to other social care workers.\n<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/apr/18/coronavirus-live-news-global-deaths-pass-150000-trump-china-china-denies-any-concealment-pence-origins-europe-germany</ref>\n\nThirteen residents at the Glasgow-based Burlington Care Home have died in one week following a suspected outbreak of coronavirus. The [[Care Inspectorate (Scotland)|Care Inspectorate]] has been made aware of the deaths and are in contact with the care service, as well as the local health and social care partnership.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-52165397 | title=Virus suspected as 13 care home residents die| work=BBC News| date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Hospital capacity===\nScotland has an estimated 3,000 [[hospital bed]]s expected to be available for coronavirus patients in [[List of hospitals in Scotland|hospitals across Scotland]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-52121144|title=Temporary coronavirus hospital 'may not be needed'|date=1 April 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Intensive care unit|ICU]] capacity across Scotland has doubled to 360 beds since the emergency began, 250 of which will be for the exclusive use of coronavirus patients, with that number expected to increase to more than 500 in the first week of April as preparations continue towards eventually quadrupling the number to more than 700 ICU beds.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nThe [[NHS Louisa Jordan]] emergency coronavirus hospital facility at the [[SEC Centre]] will initially have capacity for 300 patients, which could be expanded in the future to more than 1,000.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nScottish hospitals plan to have around 1,000 [[ventilator]]s by the summer for coronavirus patients.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.scotsman.com/health/coronavirus/1000-ventilators-scottish-hospitals-summer-2525533 |title = 1000 ventilators in Scottish hospitals by summer |date=1 April 2020|work=www.scotsman.com |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 24th March, more than 3,000 retired Scottish nurses, doctors and other medical workers have volunteered to return to work as part of efforts to help the NHS cope. As well as using retired workers, all final year nursing and midwifery students will also be given paid work placements on wards during the final six months of their degree programmes.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://inews.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-in-scotland-retired-nhs-staff-volunteer-help-covid-19-outbreak-2516559 | title=3,000 retired NHS staff volunteer to help treat coronavirus patients in Scotland |date=23 March 2020|work=inews.co.uk |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, First Minister Nicola Sturgeon announced the suspension of several non-coronavirus screens (such as diabetic eye screening) to help free up NHS staff and reduce the risk of virus exposure to patients. All elective and non-urgent surgeries had already been cancelled across Scotland to free up hospital beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/coronavirus/18345886.coronavirus-scotland-one-three-intensive-care-patients-struck-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus in Scotland: One in three intensive care patients struck down by Covid-19|website=HeraldScotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> By 1 April 2020, NHS clinical and technical staff have converted over 200 anaesthetic machines into ventilators to increase ICU bed availability to more than 500, tripling the usual capacity.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.scot/news/anaesthetic-machines-boost-ventilator-capacity/ |title = Anaesthetic machines boost ventilator capacity - gov.scot}}</ref>\n\n===Hospital-acquired infection===\nOn the issue of [[hospital-acquired infection]]s, Michael Griffin, president of the [[Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh]] warned coronavirus may be spreading in hospitals at twice the rate of its transmission in communities.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/spread-was-wider-than-predicted-research-suggests-sg5bk289w</ref>. He said \"we have to make our hospital environment is as safe as possible. In the general population, the rate of reproduction of Covid-19 is less than one but in hospitals it is estimated at something like two.\"\n\n===A&E departments===\nThe number of people attending [[Accident and Emergency]] departments in Scotland has fallen by more than 55% compared with 2019. NHS Scotland statistics reveal 11,881 people attended A&E in the second week of April 2020, down from 26,674 patients in 2019 and 25,067 in 2018.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/spread-was-wider-than-predicted-research-suggests-sg5bk289w</ref>\n\n===NHS staffing levels===\nAs of 2 April, more than 14% of NHS Scotland staff are currently off work, according to Scottish government data and about 41% of those absences (equating to 9,719 people) are related to coronavirus. NHS Scotland's total workforce is about 166,000 people.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-52133634 |title = Almost half of NHS staff absences Covid-19 related|work = BBC News|date = 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Clinical research===\n\nOrganisations in Scotland involved in COVID-19 related [[clinical research]] studies<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52111674 | title=Drug treatment for coronavirus starts UK trials| work=BBC News| date=1 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> include the [[Chief Scientist Office]]'s Rapid Research in Covid-19 programme (RARC-19 programme),<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cso.scot.nhs.uk/covid19/ | title=COVID-19 Funding Call \u2013 Chief Scientist Office|date= 30 March 2020 |website=www.cso.scot.nhs.uk |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> [[Health Science Scotland]], NHS Research Scotland,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nhsresearchscotland.org.uk/coronavirus |title = Coronavirus (COVID-19) &#124; NHS Research Scotland &#124; NHS Research Scotland |date= |website=www.nhsresearchscotland.org.uk |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Glasgow University,<ref>[https://www.gla.ac.uk/news/headline_714460_en.html University of Glasgow leads COVID-19 research response in Scotland] ''www.gla.ac.uk'', accessed 9 April 2020</ref> Dundee University,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/dundee-scientists-providing-key-research-in-the-bid-to-assist-global-research-in-tackling-covid-19/ |title = Dundee scientists providing key research in the bid to assist global research in tackling Covid-19|newspaper = Evening Telegraph |date= 29 March 2020 |accessdate= 11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/1237336/coronavirus-flock-of-tayside-sheep-could-defeat-covid-19-in-dundee-university-led-research/ |title = Coronavirus: Flock of Tayside sheep could defeat Covid-19 in Dundee University-led research |website=www.thecourier.co.uk |date= 2 April 2020 |accessdate= 11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/news/18343187.universities-glasgow-dundee-join-fight-coronavirus/ | title=Universities of Glasgow and Dundee join fight against coronavirus pandemic}}</ref> Edinburgh University.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18347084.coronavirus-scotland-researchers-ready-begin-vaccine-clinical-trials/ | title=Coronavirus in Scotland: Researchers explore impact of virus on body}}</ref>\n\n===Public hygiene===\nWorkplace hygiene advice was published on 9 March 2020.<ref>https://www.gov.scot/news/workplace-advice-contained-in-new-coronavirus-guidance/</ref>\n\nGlasgow Taxi Owners' Association urged  taxi drivers to be careful during the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic, after hearing reports of drivers falling ill.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/news/18358651.glasgow-shocked-shocked-several-drivers-very-ill-coronavirus/ |title = Glasgow cabbies express shock as several drivers 'very ill' with coronavirus}}</ref> In addition, the ''Daily Record'' reported comments made by a Scottish nurse who warned drivers to take precautions at petrol stations.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-scotland-nurse-warns-virus-21732044 |title = Scottish nurse warns drivers coronavirus 'may rapidly spread from petrol pumps'|date = 21 March 2020 |accessdate= 14 April 2020 |website=www.dailyrecord.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Volunteer campaign===\n[[File:Glasgow. &quot;Fear and Love&quot;.Graffiti by The Rebel Bear.DSC 1676..JPG|thumb|Glasgow. Graffiti in the time of pandemic COVID-19.]]\n\nA new 'Scotland Cares' campaign was launched on Monday 30 March to encourage people to volunteer during the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic. More than 21,000 people signed up on the first day. By 4 April, the number of registrations to volunteer stood at 50,330. Cabinet Secretary for Social Security and Older People Shirley-Anne Somerville said: \u201cThe response to the Scotland Cares campaign has been outstanding and I want to thank each and every person who has signed up to volunteer during the coronavirus outbreak. Your support at this critical time is invaluable and will make a huge difference over the coming weeks and months.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.scot/news/national-volunteering-plan-for-coronavirus/ |title = National volunteering plan for coronavirus - gov.scot |accessdate= 14 April 2020 |website=www.gov.scot |date=30 Mar 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-scotland-52097216 |title=Coronavirus in Scotland: Virus link to care home deaths |publisher=BBC News |date=2020-04-04 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> \n\nPeople who are healthy and not at risk can volunteer via the [[Ready Scotland]] website.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.readyscotland.org/ | title=Ready Scotland: Preparing for Emergencies |accessdate= 14 April 2020 |website=www.readyscotland.org}}</ref>\n\n===\"At risk\" population===\n\nThose in high risk vulnerable groups can register for deliveries of food and medicine from 3rd April. This includes around 120,000 people in Scotland who are advised to [[Social distancing|shield]]<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51506729 |title = What are the rules on exercise?|work = BBC News|date = 6 April 2020}}</ref> themselves at home (12 weeks of [[Isolation (health care)|self-isolation]]) such as the elderly, those with [[Immunosuppression|suppressed]]/[[Immuno-compromised|compromised]] immune systems and those with underlying health conditions.\n\n===Prisons===\nOn 2 April, BBC Scotland said it found almost a quarter of [[Scottish Prison Service]] staff are absent from work amid the coronavirus outbreak. The SPS said 110 prisoners over 11 sites were [[self-isolating]]. At that time, two had tested positive for Covid-19.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-52133835 |title = Almost a quarter of prison staff absent from work|work = BBC News|date = 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\n\nAs of 19 March 2020, the [[Robert Gordon University]], [[Edinburgh Napier University]], [[University of Dundee]], [[University of Glasgow]], [[University of the West of Scotland]], [[Glasgow Caledonian University]], [[Aberdeen University]], [[Edinburgh University]], [[Heriot-Watt University]], [[University of Stirling]] and [[University of Strathclyde]] had cancelled or suspended face-to-face classes. Scottish political parties ([[Scottish Green Party|Green]], [[Scottish Conservatives|Conservatives]], [[Scottish National Party|SNP]]) also cancelled their spring conferences.<ref name=\"closed\"/>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Kingdom/Scotland medical cases}}\n\n== Graphs ==\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=800\n|colors=#F46D43,#A50026,#C4ADA0,#C4ADB0,#C4ADC0\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x=2 Mar,3 Mar,4 Mar,5 Mar,6 Mar,7 Mar,8 Mar,9 Mar,10 Mar,11 Mar,12 Mar,13 Mar,1