{"title_page": "Ottawa Central Station", "text_new": "{{short description|Main inter-city bus station in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{About|Ottawa's main bus station|Ottawa's main railway station|Ottawa station}}\n{{Infobox station \n| name          = Ottawa Central Station\n| type          = \n| style         = \n| image         = Ottawa Bus Station.JPG\n| image_caption = Bus station while it was operated by Station Centrale\n| address       = 265 Catherine Street<br />[[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]<br />K1R 7S5\n| coordinates   = {{Coord|45|24|31|N|75|41|41|W|type:landmark_region:CA-ON|display=title,inline}}\n| line          = \n| other         = \n| structure     = At-grade\n| bus_stands    = 14 (4 for arrivals)\n| bus_operators = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Greyhound Canada]]\n* [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services|Ontario Northland]]\n* Autobus Gatineau\n* Transcollines \n* [[Thom Transport]]}}\n| connections   = {{rint|ottawa|bus}} [[File:OC Transpo logo.svg|72px|link=OC Transpo]] {{rbox|55||#{{octc|local}}}} [[Bayshore station (Ottawa)|Bayshore]]/[[Ottawa General Hospital|Hospital]] - Elmvale [http://www.octranspo.com/images/files/routes_pdf_future/map_carte_055.pdf]\n| parking       = Paid parking - short and long term\n| bicycle       = Yes\n| opened        = 1972\n| closed        = \n| rebuilt       = \n| electrified   = \n| ADA           = Yes\n| code          = \n| owned         = Crerar Silverside Corporation\n| operator      = {{Plainlist|\n* Ottawa Central Station Inc.\n* Greyhound Canada Transportation ULC\n}}\n| zone          = \n| smartcardname =\n| smartcardstatus = \n| former        = \n| passengers    = \n| pass_year     = \n| pass_percent  = \n| pass_system   = \n| mpassengers   = \n| services      = \n| map_locator   = \n| map_type = Canada Ottawa#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| map_caption = Location in Ottawa##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n| map_dot_label = Ottawa Central Station\n| web           = {{URL|http://www.ottawacentralstation.com/|Ottawa Central Station}}\n}}\n'''Ottawa Central Station''' is the main inter-city [[bus terminus|bus station]] in [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. It is located 1.5 km south of [[downtown Ottawa]] in the [[Centretown]] neighbourhood and serves buses from [[Greyhound Canada]], [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services|Ontario Northland]], Autobus Gatineau and Transcollines. \n\n==Location==\nOttawa Central Station is located at 265 Catherine Street, between Lyon Street and [[Kent Street (Ottawa)|Kent Street]]. Catherine Street lies directly north of [[Ontario Highway 417]] (known locally as the ''Queensway''), which is the main expressway through Ottawa. The station is accessible from highway 417 exits 120 (eastbound) and 119 (westbound). \n\nThe station's main entrance faces south towards Catherine Street and the 417. On the north side of the station building, buses call at 14 outdoor [[bus stand]]s with adjoining indoor waiting areas. The front of the buses are partially covered by a roof overhang.\n\n==Services==\nThe station includes free Wi-Fi, an ATM, vending machines and a [[Mr. Sub]] restaurant featuring Country Style hot beverages and baked goods. Protect Guard Services operates as the station's main security. Ideal Control Systems and [[First Student Canada|First Student]] offices are located on the second level of the terminal.\n\nThe station's operating hours are daily from 5:00 am to 2:30 am. The [[Greyhound Courier Express|parcel department]]'s hours are Monday to Friday 7:00 am to 8:00 pm, Saturday 8:00 am to 5:00 pm and Sunday/holidays 12:00 pm to 5:00 pm.\n\n==Main destinations==\nThe majority of buses serving the station are operated by [[Greyhound Canada]]. Destinations from Ottawa include [[Toronto]] (with connections to the [[United States]]), [[Montreal]] (with connections to the [[United States]] and [[Quebec City]]), [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]] (with connections to [[New York City]] and [[Philadelphia]]), and [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]]. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Bus Carrier\n! Cities Served\n|-\n| [[Greyhound Canada]]\n|[[Montreal]], [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]], [[Cornwall, Ontario|Cornwall]], [[Gatineau]], [[Grand-Remous, Quebec|Grand-Remous]], [[Toronto]], [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]], [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]], [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]], [[Pembroke, Ontario|Pembroke]], [[North Bay, Ontario|North Bay]], [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]]\n|-\n| [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services]]\n|[[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]], [[North Bay, Ontario|North Bay]], [[Pembroke, Ontario|Pembroke]], [[Petawawa]]\n|-\n| Autobus Gatineau\n| [[Gatineau]], [[Kazabazua, Quebec|Kazabazua]], [[Maniwaki]], [[Grand-Remous, Quebec|Grand-Remous]]\n|-\n| Transcollines\n| [[Quyon, Quebec|Quyon]], [[Shawville]], [[Campbell's Bay, Quebec|Campbell's Bay]], [[Fort-Coulonge]]\n|-\n|}\n\n[[File:Ottawa Central Station - 03.jpg|thumb|Ticket Counter at Ottawa Central Station]]\n[[File:Ottawa Central Station - 02.jpg|thumb|Bus Stand at Ottawa Central Station]]\n[[File:Ottawa Central Station - 04.jpg|thumb|Passengers disembarking from a Greyhound Bus. Outdoor Bus Stand Area, Ottawa Central Station]]\n[[File:Mr. Sub - 265 Catherine.jpg|thumb|Mr. Sub at Ottawa Central Station, 2016]]\n\n==Recent History==\n\nOttawa Central Station used to have the same management as [[Montreal]]'s major bus terminal, [[Gare d'autocars de Montr\u00e9al]] before the latter was purchased by the Quebec government.<ref>[https://montrealgazette.com/business/Quebec+move+station+into+Ilot+Voyageur+complex/3846182/story.html# Quebec to move bus station into Ilot Voyageur complex]{{dead link|date=June 2011}}</ref> On February 7, 2011, the terminal operations were sold to Corporate Customer Service Limited,<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/station+owner+applies+rezoning/4423000/story.html# Station Centrale sold to Corporate Customer Service] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314200856/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/business/station+owner+applies+rezoning/4423000/story.html |date=2011-03-14 }}</ref> a sub-contractor of Greyhound Canada. Corporate Customer Service formed a new company, Ottawa Central Station Inc., to manage the terminal. On September 1, 2011, Corporate Customer Service Ltd. handed over the head lease to Greyhound, who in turn negotiated and signed a long-term lease with the property's owner.<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/terminal+receive+facelift/5398253/story.html# Greyhound signs new lease]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Ottawa Central Station Inc. remains as an agency within a Greyhound terminal. The building and the lot is owned by Crerar Silverside Corporation.<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/station+owner+applies+rezoning/4423000/story.html# Station owned by Crerar Silverside Corp.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314200856/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/business/station+owner+applies+rezoning/4423000/story.html |date=2011-03-14 }}</ref> \n\nOn January 21, 2016, [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services]] began operating between Ottawa Central Station and Sudbury to better serve passengers connecting to and from [[Northern Ontario]] communities.<ref name=new-route>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontarionorthland.ca/en/news/new-route-enhances-connection-north-ottawa |title=New Route Enhances Connection from the North to Ottawa |date={{date|2016-01-15}} |work=MEDIA RELEASE |publisher=Ontario Northland |quote=Ontario Northland will be offering service from Sudbury to Ottawa three days per week as of Thursday, January, 21st |accessdate=15 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115233924/http://www.ontarionorthland.ca/en/news/new-route-enhances-connection-north-ottawa |archive-date=2016-01-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn February 29, 2016, Autobus Gatineau, a subsidiary of Autobus Maheux, began operating between Ottawa Central Station and Grand-Remous after Greyhound reduced service to Fridays and Sundays only.<ref>http://www.lapresse.ca/le-droit/actualites/actualites-regionales/201602/26/01-4955165-le-transport-interurbain-sauve-dans-la-vallee-de-la-gatineau.php</ref> Greyhound later discontinued offering this service altogether.\n\nOn December 15, 2008, new security measures by Greyhound came into place. All Greyhound passengers are subject to random screening prior to boarding the bus, which includes the use of wand metal detectors and searching carry-on items. Any passenger refusing to be searched is not permitted to travel.\n==Proposed relocation==\nIn early 2010, Ottawa Mayor Larry O'Brien announced that he was working with Greyhound to move to bus terminal to a new location next to the [[Via Rail]] station on Tremblay Road,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://centretownnewsonline.ca/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1514&Itemid=126# |title=O\u2019Brien pushes to move bus terminal to Via Rail station |publisher=Centretownnewsonline.ca |accessdate=2011-06-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706172444/http://centretownnewsonline.ca/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1514&Itemid=126 |archivedate=2011-07-06 }}</ref> effectively creating a transport hub along with the proposed LRT.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100409081002/http://www.ottawasun.com/comment/columnists/walter_robinson/2010/04/06/13489811.html Transit hub crosses line]</ref> According to O'Brien, talks had been going on for a while and Greyhound seemed warm to the idea, however the Catherine station's owner, Stewart Robertson, was never consulted and only learned through the media about the proposed move.<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/station+move+surprise+owner/2753789/story.html# Bus station move surprise to owner]{{dead link|date=June 2011}}</ref> The move has sparked controversy and mixed opinions with the public and local politicians, stating that the proposed location is inconvenient as it is not central, or more convenient as it is along the [[Ottawa Rapid Transit|Transitway]].<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/station+shift+gets+mixed+reviews/2714639/story.html# Bus station shift gets mixed reviews]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401150529/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/business/station+shift+gets+mixed+reviews/2714639/story.html |date=April 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nRobertson, the station's owner, released renderings of a proposed renovation that would see the inside and outside of the terminal's aesthetics improved as well as the terminal's heating and ventilation system,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://keepitdowntownottawa.com/2010/04/08/bus-terminal-owner-plans-revitalization-of-catherine-street-location/# |title=Bus terminal owner plans revitalization of Catherine Street location |publisher=Keepitdowntownottawa.com |accessdate=2011-06-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713141935/http://keepitdowntownottawa.com/2010/04/08/bus-terminal-owner-plans-revitalization-of-catherine-street-location/ |archivedate=2011-07-13 }}</ref> however these improvements would only come if Greyhound were to sign a long-term agreement with Robertson, which in the end would result in Station Centrale being phased out as the terminal's operators.<ref>{{cite web|author=nurun.com |url=http://www.ottawasun.com/news/ottawa/2010/04/01/13441216.html# |title=Building owner wants to keep Greyhound as tenant |publisher=Ottawasun.com |date=2010-04-01 |accessdate=2011-06-09}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2011, it was revealed that Stewart Robertson had applied for rezoning of the lot to general mixed-use as a contingency plan if Greyhound were to leave.<ref>{{cite web|author=Josh Pringle with Stephanie Kinsella |url=http://www.cfra.com/?cat=1&nid=78398# |title=Robertson applies for rezoning |publisher=Cfra.com |date=2011-03-10 |accessdate=2011-06-09}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2011, Greyhound signed a long-term lease with Crerar Silverside Corporation. As a result, the terminal will not be relocated and extensive renovations are to be done to the station in 2011 and 2012, possibly totalling over one million dollars.<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/terminal+receive+facelift/5398253/story.html# Terminal to get renovations]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n* [[Gare d'autocars de Montr\u00e9al]]\n* [[Greyhound Canada]]\n* [[Voyageur Colonial Bus Lines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.greyhound.ca Greyhound Canada]\n* [http://www.ottawacentralstation.com/ Ottawa Central Station]\n* [https://www.busbud.com/en/central-station/s/1970 Busbud Ottawa Central Station Bus Fare Search]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170919032845/http://investigation-services.ca/ Investigation Services Ltd.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100717015923/http://keepitdowntownottawa.com/ Keep It Downtown, Ottawa]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100417161002/http://www.yowshuttle.com/ YOW Airporter Shuttle]\n\n{{Ottawa}}\n\n[[Category:Bus stations in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Transport in Ottawa|Bus]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ottawa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Main inter-city bus station in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{About|the bus station|the railway station|Ottawa station}}\n{{Infobox station \n| name          = Ottawa Central Station\n| type          = \n| style         = \n| image         = Ottawa Bus Station.JPG\n| image_caption = Bus station while it was operated by Station Centrale\n| address       = 265 Catherine Street<br />[[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]<br />K1R 7S5\n| coordinates   = {{Coord|45|24|31|N|75|41|41|W|type:landmark_region:CA-ON|display=title,inline}}\n| line          = \n| other         = \n| structure     = At-grade\n| bus_stands    = 14 (4 for arrivals)\n| bus_operators = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Greyhound Canada]]\n* [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services|Ontario Northland]]\n* Autobus Gatineau\n* Transcollines \n* [[Thom Transport]]}}\n| connections   = {{rint|ottawa|bus}} [[File:OC Transpo logo.svg|72px|link=OC Transpo]] {{rbox|55||#{{octc|local}}}} [[Bayshore station (Ottawa)|Bayshore]]/[[Ottawa General Hospital|Hospital]] - Elmvale [http://www.octranspo.com/images/files/routes_pdf_future/map_carte_055.pdf]\n| parking       = Paid parking - short and long term\n| bicycle       = Yes\n| opened        = 1972\n| closed        = \n| rebuilt       = \n| electrified   = \n| ADA           = Yes\n| code          = \n| owned         = Crerar Silverside Corporation\n| operator      = {{Plainlist|\n* Ottawa Central Station Inc.\n* Greyhound Canada Transportation ULC\n}}\n| zone          = \n| smartcardname =\n| smartcardstatus = \n| former        = \n| passengers    = \n| pass_year     = \n| pass_percent  = \n| pass_system   = \n| mpassengers   = \n| services      = \n| map_locator   = \n| map_type = Canada Ottawa#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| map_caption = Location in Ottawa##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n| map_dot_label = Ottawa Central Station\n| web           = {{URL|http://www.ottawacentralstation.com/|Ottawa Central Station}}\n}}\n'''Ottawa Central Station''' is the main inter-city [[bus terminus|bus station]] in [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. It is located 1.5 km south of [[downtown Ottawa]] in the [[Centretown]] neighbourhood and serves buses from [[Greyhound Canada]], [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services|Ontario Northland]], Autobus Gatineau and Transcollines. \n\n==Location==\nOttawa Central Station is located at 265 Catherine Street, between Lyon Street and [[Kent Street (Ottawa)|Kent Street]]. Catherine Street lies directly north of [[Ontario Highway 417]] (known locally as the ''Queensway''), which is the main expressway through Ottawa. The station is accessible from highway 417 exits 120 (eastbound) and 119 (westbound). \n\nThe station's main entrance faces south towards Catherine Street and the 417. On the north side of the station building, buses call at 14 outdoor [[bus stand]]s with adjoining indoor waiting areas. The front of the buses are partially covered by a roof overhang.\n\n==Services==\nThe station includes free Wi-Fi, an ATM, vending machines and a [[Mr. Sub]] restaurant featuring Country Style hot beverages and baked goods. Protect Guard Services operates as the station's main security. Ideal Control Systems and [[First Student Canada|First Student]] offices are located on the second level of the terminal.\n\nThe station's operating hours are daily from 5:00 am to 2:30 am. The [[Greyhound Courier Express|parcel department]]'s hours are Monday to Friday 7:00 am to 8:00 pm, Saturday 8:00 am to 5:00 pm and Sunday/holidays 12:00 pm to 5:00 pm.\n\n==Main destinations==\nThe majority of buses serving the station are operated by [[Greyhound Canada]]. Destinations from Ottawa include [[Toronto]] (with connections to the [[United States]]), [[Montreal]] (with connections to the [[United States]] and [[Quebec City]]), [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]] (with connections to [[New York City]] and [[Philadelphia]]), and [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]]. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Bus Carrier\n! Cities Served\n|-\n| [[Greyhound Canada]]\n|[[Montreal]], [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]], [[Cornwall, Ontario|Cornwall]], [[Gatineau]], [[Grand-Remous, Quebec|Grand-Remous]], [[Toronto]], [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]], [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]], [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]], [[Pembroke, Ontario|Pembroke]], [[North Bay, Ontario|North Bay]], [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]]\n|-\n| [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services]]\n|[[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]], [[North Bay, Ontario|North Bay]], [[Pembroke, Ontario|Pembroke]], [[Petawawa]]\n|-\n| Autobus Gatineau\n| [[Gatineau]], [[Kazabazua, Quebec|Kazabazua]], [[Maniwaki]], [[Grand-Remous, Quebec|Grand-Remous]]\n|-\n| Transcollines\n| [[Quyon, Quebec|Quyon]], [[Shawville]], [[Campbell's Bay, Quebec|Campbell's Bay]], [[Fort-Coulonge]]\n|-\n|}\n\n[[File:Ottawa Central Station - 03.jpg|thumb|Ticket Counter at Ottawa Central Station]]\n[[File:Ottawa Central Station - 02.jpg|thumb|Bus Stand at Ottawa Central Station]]\n[[File:Ottawa Central Station - 04.jpg|thumb|Passengers disembarking from a Greyhound Bus. Outdoor Bus Stand Area, Ottawa Central Station]]\n[[File:Mr. Sub - 265 Catherine.jpg|thumb|Mr. Sub at Ottawa Central Station, 2016]]\n\n==Recent History==\n\nOttawa Central Station used to have the same management as [[Montreal]]'s major bus terminal, [[Gare d'autocars de Montr\u00e9al]] before the latter was purchased by the Quebec government.<ref>[https://montrealgazette.com/business/Quebec+move+station+into+Ilot+Voyageur+complex/3846182/story.html# Quebec to move bus station into Ilot Voyageur complex]{{dead link|date=June 2011}}</ref> On February 7, 2011, the terminal operations were sold to Corporate Customer Service Limited,<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/station+owner+applies+rezoning/4423000/story.html# Station Centrale sold to Corporate Customer Service] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314200856/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/business/station+owner+applies+rezoning/4423000/story.html |date=2011-03-14 }}</ref> a sub-contractor of Greyhound Canada. Corporate Customer Service formed a new company, Ottawa Central Station Inc., to manage the terminal. On September 1, 2011, Corporate Customer Service Ltd. handed over the head lease to Greyhound, who in turn negotiated and signed a long-term lease with the property's owner.<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/terminal+receive+facelift/5398253/story.html# Greyhound signs new lease]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Ottawa Central Station Inc. remains as an agency within a Greyhound terminal. The building and the lot is owned by Crerar Silverside Corporation.<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/station+owner+applies+rezoning/4423000/story.html# Station owned by Crerar Silverside Corp.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314200856/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/business/station+owner+applies+rezoning/4423000/story.html |date=2011-03-14 }}</ref> \n\nOn January 21, 2016, [[Ontario Northland Motor Coach Services]] began operating between Ottawa Central Station and Sudbury to better serve passengers connecting to and from [[Northern Ontario]] communities.<ref name=new-route>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontarionorthland.ca/en/news/new-route-enhances-connection-north-ottawa |title=New Route Enhances Connection from the North to Ottawa |date={{date|2016-01-15}} |work=MEDIA RELEASE |publisher=Ontario Northland |quote=Ontario Northland will be offering service from Sudbury to Ottawa three days per week as of Thursday, January, 21st |accessdate=15 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115233924/http://www.ontarionorthland.ca/en/news/new-route-enhances-connection-north-ottawa |archive-date=2016-01-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn February 29, 2016, Autobus Gatineau, a subsidiary of Autobus Maheux, began operating between Ottawa Central Station and Grand-Remous after Greyhound reduced service to Fridays and Sundays only.<ref>http://www.lapresse.ca/le-droit/actualites/actualites-regionales/201602/26/01-4955165-le-transport-interurbain-sauve-dans-la-vallee-de-la-gatineau.php</ref> Greyhound later discontinued offering this service altogether.\n\nOn December 15, 2008, new security measures by Greyhound came into place. All Greyhound passengers are subject to random screening prior to boarding the bus, which includes the use of wand metal detectors and searching carry-on items. Any passenger refusing to be searched is not permitted to travel.\n==Proposed relocation==\nIn early 2010, Ottawa Mayor Larry O'Brien announced that he was working with Greyhound to move to bus terminal to a new location next to the [[Via Rail]] station on Tremblay Road,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://centretownnewsonline.ca/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1514&Itemid=126# |title=O\u2019Brien pushes to move bus terminal to Via Rail station |publisher=Centretownnewsonline.ca |accessdate=2011-06-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706172444/http://centretownnewsonline.ca/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1514&Itemid=126 |archivedate=2011-07-06 }}</ref> effectively creating a transport hub along with the proposed LRT.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100409081002/http://www.ottawasun.com/comment/columnists/walter_robinson/2010/04/06/13489811.html Transit hub crosses line]</ref> According to O'Brien, talks had been going on for a while and Greyhound seemed warm to the idea, however the Catherine station's owner, Stewart Robertson, was never consulted and only learned through the media about the proposed move.<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/station+move+surprise+owner/2753789/story.html# Bus station move surprise to owner]{{dead link|date=June 2011}}</ref> The move has sparked controversy and mixed opinions with the public and local politicians, stating that the proposed location is inconvenient as it is not central, or more convenient as it is along the [[Ottawa Rapid Transit|Transitway]].<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/station+shift+gets+mixed+reviews/2714639/story.html# Bus station shift gets mixed reviews]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401150529/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/business/station+shift+gets+mixed+reviews/2714639/story.html |date=April 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nRobertson, the station's owner, released renderings of a proposed renovation that would see the inside and outside of the terminal's aesthetics improved as well as the terminal's heating and ventilation system,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://keepitdowntownottawa.com/2010/04/08/bus-terminal-owner-plans-revitalization-of-catherine-street-location/# |title=Bus terminal owner plans revitalization of Catherine Street location |publisher=Keepitdowntownottawa.com |accessdate=2011-06-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713141935/http://keepitdowntownottawa.com/2010/04/08/bus-terminal-owner-plans-revitalization-of-catherine-street-location/ |archivedate=2011-07-13 }}</ref> however these improvements would only come if Greyhound were to sign a long-term agreement with Robertson, which in the end would result in Station Centrale being phased out as the terminal's operators.<ref>{{cite web|author=nurun.com |url=http://www.ottawasun.com/news/ottawa/2010/04/01/13441216.html# |title=Building owner wants to keep Greyhound as tenant |publisher=Ottawasun.com |date=2010-04-01 |accessdate=2011-06-09}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2011, it was revealed that Stewart Robertson had applied for rezoning of the lot to general mixed-use as a contingency plan if Greyhound were to leave.<ref>{{cite web|author=Josh Pringle with Stephanie Kinsella |url=http://www.cfra.com/?cat=1&nid=78398# |title=Robertson applies for rezoning |publisher=Cfra.com |date=2011-03-10 |accessdate=2011-06-09}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2011, Greyhound signed a long-term lease with Crerar Silverside Corporation. As a result, the terminal will not be relocated and extensive renovations are to be done to the station in 2011 and 2012, possibly totalling over one million dollars.<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/business/terminal+receive+facelift/5398253/story.html# Terminal to get renovations]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n* [[Gare d'autocars de Montr\u00e9al]]\n* [[Greyhound Canada]]\n* [[Voyageur Colonial Bus Lines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.greyhound.ca Greyhound Canada]\n* [http://www.ottawacentralstation.com/ Ottawa Central Station]\n* [https://www.busbud.com/en/central-station/s/1970 Busbud Ottawa Central Station Bus Fare Search]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170919032845/http://investigation-services.ca/ Investigation Services Ltd.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100717015923/http://keepitdowntownottawa.com/ Keep It Downtown, Ottawa]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100417161002/http://www.yowshuttle.com/ YOW Airporter Shuttle]\n\n{{Ottawa}}\n\n[[Category:Bus stations in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Transport in Ottawa|Bus]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ottawa]]\n", "name_user": "Ottawajin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated about header for style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ottawa_Central_Station"}
{"title_page": "Juanda International Airport", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Juanda International Airport \n| nativename = <small>{{lang|id|Bandar Udara Internasional Juanda}}</small> \n| nativename-a = \n| nativename-r = \n| image =Juandaairportlogo.png\n| image-width = 250\n| image2 = Surabaya Airport.jpg\n| image2-width = 250\n| caption2 = \n| caption  = \n| IATA = SUB\n| ICAO = WARR\n| WMO = 96935\n| type = Public / Military\n| owner = [[Government of Indonesia]]\n| operator = [[Angkasa Pura|PT Angkasa Pura I]]\n| city-served = [[Surabaya]]\n| location = [[Sidoarjo Regency]], [[East Java]], [[Indonesia]]\n| opened = \n* Structure on 1960\n* February 7, 1964 (Domestic Terminal)\n* December 24, 1990 (International Terminal)\n* November 15, 2006 (Terminal 1, Domestic Flights)\n* February 14, 2014 (Terminal 2, Domestic and International Flights)\n| hub =\n* [[Citilink]]\n* [[Garuda Indonesia]]\n* [[Indonesia AirAsia]]\n* [[Lion Air]]\n* [[Wings Air]]\n| timezone = [[Western Indonesian Time|WIB]]\n| utc = [[UTC+07:00]]\n| elevation-f  = 9\n| elevation-m  = 3\n| coordinates  = {{coord|07|22|47|S|112|47|13|E|region:ID-JI|display=it}}\n| website      = [http://www.juanda-airport.com/ juanda-airport.com] \n| image_map           = Java Locator.svg\n| image_map_caption   = [[Java]] region in Indonesia \n| pushpin_map  = Indonesia_Surabaya#Indonesia Java#Indonesia#Southeast Asia \n| pushpin_label = SUB\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in East Java / Indonesia\n| metric-elev  = \n| metric-rwy   = y\n| r1-number    = 10/28\n| r1-length-f  = 9,843\n| r1-length-m  = 3,000x55m\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year    = 2017\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 21,882,335 ({{increase}} 23.9%)\n| stat3-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat3-data = 99,877({{increase}} 10.7%)\n| footnotes    = Source: [[List of the busiest airports in Indonesia]]\n}}\n\n'''Juanda International Airport (JIA)''' ({{lang-id|Bandar Udara Internasional Juanda}}) {{Airport codes|SUB|WARR}}, is an international airport located in [[Sedati]], [[Sidoarjo]]. It is now the [[List of the busiest airports in Indonesia|third busiest airport in Indonesia]] (after [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Soekarno-Hatta]] and [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Ngurah Rai airport]]). This airport is located approximately 12 kilometers (8 miles) from [[Surabaya]] and serves the [[Surabaya metropolitan area]], the metropolitan area of Surabaya plus extended urban area. Juanda International Airport is operated by [[Angkasa Pura|PT Angkasa Pura I]]. The airport takes its name after [[Djuanda Kartawidjaja]], the last [[Prime Minister of Indonesia]] who had suggested development of this airport. In 2013, the airport serves about 400 aircraft per day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://surabaya.tribunnews.com/2014/01/09/soekarwo-bandara-juanda-butuh-double-runway |title=Soekarwo : Bandara Juanda Butuh Double Runway|website=Surabaya.tribunnews.com  |date=9 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, Juanda International Airport is the hub of [[Citilink]], [[Garuda Indonesia]], [[Indonesia AirAsia]], [[Lion Air]] and [[Sriwijaya Air]] along with [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport]]. Juanda International Airport will become one of the main airports in Indonesia for ASEAN [[Open skies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beritatrans.com/2014/09/13/kemenhub-5-bandara-siap-hadapi-asean-open-sky/ |title=Kemenhub; Lima Bandara Disiapkan Untuk Asean Open Sky |website=Beritatrans.com |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Juanda International Airport becomes the world's 10th best in Airport Service Quality by [[Airport Council International]] among 79 airports with passengers capacity between 5-15 million a year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://finance.detik.com/read/2015/04/24/164442/2897525/4/layanan-bandara-ngurah-rai-terbaik-no7-dunia |title=Layanan Bandara Ngurah Rai Terbaik No.7 Dunia |author=Feby Dwi Sutianto |website=Finance.detik.com|date=April 24, 2015}}</ref> In Q1 2015, the airport becomes the world's 7th best in Airport Service Quality by [[Airport Council International|ACI]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beritasatu.com/destinasi/280323-bandara-ngurah-rai-peringkat-ketiga-terbaik-dunia.html |title=Bandara Ngurah Rai Peringkat Ketiga Terbaik Dunia |website=Beritasatu.com|date=June 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nOpened in 1964 as a naval air base of Indonesia. It replaces the previous airport in Morokrembangan, near [[Surabaya|the city center]]. It was originally used as home base for [[Indonesian Navy]]'s fleet of [[Ilyushin Il-28]] and [[Fairey Gannet]]. In its development it was also used for civil aviation. And PT Angkasa Pura I handled the management and operation since January 1985. On December 24, 1990 Juanda Airport was gained international airport status after the opening of the international terminal. Previously, since December 1987, the airport has served flights to [[Singapore]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Taipei]] and [[Manila]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airport-technology.com/projects/juanda-international-airport/ |title=Juanda International Airport, Indonesia|website=Airport-technology.com |accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Development of airport city==\nOn February 25, 2015, Indonesia President [[Joko Widodo]] agreed to develop Juanda Airport City, including an additional two runways and an integrated connection between Gubeng railway station and the airport via an elevated railway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://surabaya.tribunnews.com/2015/02/26/presiden-jokowi-setujui-proyek-juanda-airport-city |title=Presiden Jokowi Setujui Proyek Juanda Airport City|website=Surabaya.tribunnews.com |date=February 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://surabaya.tribunnews.com/2015/02/26/presiden-jokowi-setujui-proyek-juanda-airport-city?page=2 |title=Presiden Jokowi Setujui Proyek Juanda Airport City|website=Surabaya.tribunnews.com  |date=February 26, 2015}}</ref> About 6,000 hectares of land have been prepared for the expansion of the airport - where in 1,500 hectares will be used to construct two additional runways, and Juanda Airport's Terminal 3, while the remaining area will be used to construct the Airport City and the Ultimate Terminal Building.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.tempo.co/read/news/2016/04/24/056765375/Surabaya-to-Reclaim-Northern-Coastline-to-Expand-Juanda-Airport|title=Surabaya to Reclaim Northern Coastline to Expand Juanda Airport|newspaper=Tempo|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><!--Terminal 3 will be predicted to handle 62.5 million passengers per year, with the overload Terminal 1 and 2, total passenger handling capacity will increase to 75 million passengers per year. Besides building Terminal 3, PT Angkasa Pura I will also be adding two new runways. The runways will be around 3850 meters long and 60% of it will be over the sea. If construction began with no delay it is predicted to open in 2019.-->\n\nThe new area for Juanda Airport is estimated to be 1,700 hectares and will be located in the northern part of the airport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2017/09/01/pt-angkasa-pura-i-to-improve-juanda-international-airport.html|title=PT Angkasa Pura I to improve Juanda International Airport|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> Construction of two runways by will require the reclamation of about four kilometers stretch of land along Java's northern coastline. The land acquisition is expected to be completed by 2018. Development consists of three phases;  \n*First phase is the confirmation of the masterplan, land acquisition, reclamation for runway 2 and construction of runway 2.\n*Second phase is the development of Terminal 1, reclamation for runway 3, construction of runway 3 and accessibility from toll roads and terminal.  \n*Third phase will be building an Ultimate Terminal and airport city supporting infrastructure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.tempo.co/read/news/2016/01/06/056733494/Juanda-Airport-to-Build-Terminal-III-New-Runway|title=Juanda Airport to Build Terminal III, New Runway|newspaper=Tempo|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Terminals and runway==\nAt present, Juanda International Airport has 2 terminals.\nA new three-storey terminal building was opened in October 2006, which is now Terminal 1. The building has a capacity of eight million passengers per year and features a {{convert|51500|m2|adj=on}} domestic passenger terminal, a {{convert|20200|m2|adj=on}} international terminal and 11 aerobridges. The terminal used a mix of high hat roofs from Rumah adat [[Sumba]] as well as [[Java-Malay architecture]] themes. Terminal 1 is used for all domestic flights, except Garuda Indonesia and Indonesia AirAsia flights.\n\nTerminal 2 was built by demolishing the old terminal building, which was opened on February 14, 2014. The architecture of T2 is modern with curved features when compared to Terminal 1. Terminal 2 has an area of 49,500 square meters and 8 aerobridges, with a capacity to accommodate 6 million passengers per year. Terminal 2 is used for all international flights, Garuda Indonesia and Indonesia AirAsia domestic and international flights. In addition, Terminal 2 features the Garuda Indonesia Executive Lounge for domestic flights and the Concordia Premier Lounge for international flights.\n\nThe airport has separate {{convert|5300|m2|adj=on}} administration building, including a 15-storey control tower, and a two-storey cargo building with domestic and international cargo sections, capable of handling {{convert|120000|t}} of cargo a year. The apron with an area of {{convert|148000|m2}} can handle 18 aircraft simultaneously, including two wide body, 11 medium and five small aircraft. The airport has a single runway of {{convert|3000|x|55|m|ft|0}}. There are two {{convert|3000|x|30|m|0|adj=on}} parallel taxiways, including five exit taxiways (30&nbsp;m wide) and four connecting taxiways (also 30&nbsp;m). The airport has a parking area of 28,900 m\u00b2 parking area that can accommodate more than 3,000 vehicles.\n\n== Airlines and destinations ==\n<!-- WHEN ADDING A NEW ROUTE, OR ADDING AN END DATE FOR A ROUTE PLEASE ADD A REFERENCE, ALSO ADD THE ROUTE AND LINK ON THE CORRESPONDING AIRPORTS ARTICLE AND THE AIRLINES ARTICLE IF IT IS A NEW DESTINATION, ANYTHING WHICH IS NOT REFERENCED WILL BE REMOVED. ALSO WHEN ADDING A NEW ROUTE, A FIRM DATE IS MANDATORY.-->\n{{Airport-dest-list\n<!-- -->\n<!-- -->|[[AirAsia]]| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]]\n<!-- -->\n<!--+-->|[[Airfast Indonesia]]| [[Harun Thohir Airport|Bawean]], [[Dewandaru Airport|Karimunjawa]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]] \n<!--+-->|[[Batik Air]]|[[Pattimura Airport|Ambon]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]],<ref name=\"lionair.co.id\">{{cite web|url=https://agent.lionair.co.id/LionAirAgentsPortal/Default.aspx|title=Default|website=Agent.lionair.co.id|accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref> [[Jalaluddin Airport|Gorontalo]], [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Halim Perdanakusuma]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]], [[Komodo Airport|Labuan Bajo]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto International Airport|Samarinda]], [[Domine Eduard Osok Airport|Sorong]]\n<!--+-->|[[Cathay Pacific]]|[[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]]\n<!--+-->|[[Citilink]]|[[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]],<ref name=\"citilink.co.id\">https://www.citilink.co.id/rute-baru-atr-sub</ref> [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Halim Perdanakusuma]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]], [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|Jeddah]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indo-aviation.com/2015/02/26/8-maret-citilink-operasikan-rute-penerbangan-surabaya-jeddah/ |title=8 Maret, Citilink Operasikan Rute Penerbangan Surabaya-Jeddah |website=Indo-Aviation.com |accessdate=2016-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220014355/http://indo-aviation.com/2015/02/26/8-maret-citilink-operasikan-rute-penerbangan-surabaya-jeddah/ |archivedate=20 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>[[Notohadinegoro Airport|Jember]],<ref>http://surabaya.tribunnews.com/2019/04/28/gantikan-garuda-indonesia-citilink-terbangi-rute-jember-juanda</ref> [[Kertajati International Airport|Kertajati]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Zainuddin Abdul Madjid International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citilink.co.id/en/special-offer-surabaya-penang|title=Special Offer Surabaya Penang|website=Citilink.co.id|accessdate=23 October 2018}}</ref> [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]],<ref>https://www.citilink.co.id/best-fare/terbang-ke-pontianak</ref> [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto International Airport|Samarinda]], [[Ahmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Adisutjipto International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013Adisucipto]],<ref name=\"Citilink_JOG\">{{cite web |title=Hari Pertama Pengoperasian Penuh YIA Berjalan Lancar |url=https://ap1.co.id/id/information/news/detail/hari-pertama-pengop