hor= |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/29/major-ri-airports-bursting-seams-inaca.html |title=Major RI airports bursting at the seams: Inaca |newspaper=[[The Jakarta Post]] |date=2011-07-29 |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\nThe following are statistics for the airport from 1999 to 2013. In addition to this, it is noted that, in 2006, the domestic sector between Surabaya and Jakarta is the fourth-busiest air route in Asia with over 750 weekly flights.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Total<br>passengers !! Cargo (tons) !! Aircraft<br> movements\n|-\n| 1999 || 2,137,353 || 40,549 || 52,284\n|-\n| 2000 || 2,712,074 || 31,185 || 54,154\n|-\n| 2001 || 3,301,435 || 37,767 || 62,141\n|-\n| 2002 || 4,746,113 || 43,089 || 75,921\n|-\n| 2003 || 6,584,711 || 42,910 || 82,779\n|-\n| 2004 || 8,562,747 || 63,950 || 97,421\n|-\n| 2005 || 8,217,415 || 66,647 || 99,485\n|-\n| 2006 || 8,986,650 || 71,574 || 91.209\n|-\n| 2007 || 8,823,228 || 58,815 || 87,687\n|-\n| 2008 || 9,122,196 || 62,289 || 69,726\n|-\n| 2009 || 10,562,906 || 62,357 || 76,754\n|-\n| 2010 || 12,072,059 || 76,774 || 84,958\n|-\n| 2011 || 13,778,287 || 95,146 || 103,846\n|-\n| 2012 || 16,447,912 || 102,133 || 141,365\n|-\n| 2013 || 17,683,955 || 121,935 || 155,421\n|-\n| 2014 || 18,071,633 || 92,439 || 117,825\n|-\n| 2015 || 18,911,256 || 130,398 || 166,208\n|-\n| 2019 (Estimated) || 23,545,640 || 154,544 || 173,232\n|}\n\nSource : [http://www.angkasapura1.co.id/index.php?modul=keuangan&show=data%20traffic PT (persero) ANGKASA PURA 1] {{in lang|id}}\n\n==Ground transport==\nJuanda Airport is connected to [[Waru-Juanda Toll Road]] to [[Surabaya]], which is about 15 kilometers from the airport. [[Perum DAMRI|DAMRI]] buses are provided by the local government to deliver passengers to Surabaya. Fixed tariff taxis are available to various destinations in Surabaya and surrounding areas including Malang, Blitar, Jember, Tulungagung. Taxi tickets can be purchased at the counter located at the airport exit.\nA monorail will be built and integrated along with the 3 and 4 terminals. The length of the rail is about 20&nbsp;km. The service will have 29 stops that distance between halts 1.5&nbsp;km to 2&nbsp;km.\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n* On 21 February 2007, [[Adam Air Flight 172]] flying from Jakarta to Surabaya with registration PK-KKV (c/n 27284) had a hard landing at this airport, resulting in structural failure of the aircraft.<ref name=\"Flight 172\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/crash-follows-safety-concerns/story-e6freuzi-1111113113161|title=Crash follows safety concerns|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=March 7, 2007|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n* On 13 April 2010, [[Cathay Pacific Flight 780]] from Juanda International Airport to [[Hong Kong International Airport]] landed safely after both engines failed due to contaminated fuel uploaded at the airport. 57 passengers were injured. The two pilots later received the [[Polaris Award]] from the [[International Federation of Air Line Pilots' Associations]] for their heroism and airmanship.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pilots reveal death-defying ordeal as engines failed on approach to Chek Lap Kok |url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/article/1491534/pilots-reveal-death-defying-ordeal-engines-failed-approach |accessdate=21 April 2014|newspaper=South China Morning Post |date=20 April 2014}}</ref>\n* On 1 February 2014, Lion Air Flight 361, a [[Boeing 737-900ER]] (registration PK-LFH) from [[Balikpapan]] [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport]] to Juanda International Airport landed hard and bounced four times on the runway, causing a tail strike and substantial damage to the plane. There were no fatalities, but two passengers were seriously injured and three others had minor injuries.<ref name=JT361>{{cite web|title=Lion Air Flight JT 361|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20140201-0|website=Aviation-safety.net|accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n*On 28 December 2014, [[Indonesia AirAsia Flight 8501]], an Airbus A320-216 registered PK-AXC (MSN 3648) with 155 passengers and 7 crew on board, crashed into the [[Java Sea]] whilst en route from Juanda International Airport to [[Changi International Airport]], Singapore, killing all 162 on board. Regulatory licenses for the Surabaya-Singapore route as well as Medan-Palembang route have been suspended for Indonesia AirAsia since January 2015 due to suspected licensing breaches; the Medan-Palembang route had been resumed, however.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nImage:Juanda4.jpg|Terminal 1 - 2nd Floor\nImage:Cathay juanda.jpg|A [[Cathay Pacific]] [[Airbus A330-300]] at Juanda\nImage:Juanda Airport Apron.jpg|On the [[apron]], [[Saudi Airlines]] [[Boeing 747-300]] refueling and reloading to serve Indonesian [[Hajj]] pilgrims to [[Mecca]].\nImage:Valuair juanda1.jpg|[[Valuair]] [[Airbus A320-200]] arriving from [[Singapore]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Juanda International Airport}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070727132513/http://www.angkasapura1.co.id/eng/location/surabaya.htm PT. Angkasa Pura I: Juanda Airport] {{in lang|en}}\n* [https://www.travelloratour.com/travel-malang-surabaya/ Transport Malang To Surabaya]\n* [http://www.juanda-airport.com/ Juanda International Airport website]\n* {{WAD|WARR}}\n* {{ASN|SUB}}\n\n<!--Navigation box--><br>\n{{Airports in Indonesia}}\n{{Portal|Indonesia|Aviation}}\n\n[[Category:Surabaya]]\n[[Category:Transport in East Java]]\n[[Category:Airports in East Java]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Indonesia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Juanda International Airport \n| nativename = <small>{{lang|id|Bandar Udara Internasional Juanda}}</small> \n| nativename-a = \n| nativename-r = \n| image =Juandaairportlogo.png\n| image-width = 250\n| image2 = Surabaya Airport.jpg\n| image2-width = 250\n| caption2 = \n| caption  = \n| IATA = SUB\n| ICAO = WARR\n| WMO = 96935\n| type = Public / Military\n| owner = [[Government of Indonesia]]\n| operator = [[Angkasa Pura|PT Angkasa Pura I]]\n| city-served = [[Surabaya]]\n| location = [[Sidoarjo Regency]], [[East Java]], [[Indonesia]]\n| opened = \n* Structure on 1960\n* February 7, 1964 (Domestic Terminal)\n* December 24, 1990 (International Terminal)\n* November 15, 2006 (Terminal 1, Domestic Flights)\n* February 14, 2014 (Terminal 2, Domestic and International Flights)\n| hub =\n* [[Citilink]]\n* [[Garuda Indonesia]]\n* [[Indonesia AirAsia]]\n* [[Lion Air]]\n* [[Wings Air]]\n| timezone = [[Western Indonesian Time|WIB]]\n| utc = [[UTC+07:00]]\n| elevation-f  = 9\n| elevation-m  = 3\n| coordinates  = {{coord|07|22|47|S|112|47|13|E|region:ID-JI|display=it}}\n| website      = [http://www.juanda-airport.com/ juanda-airport.com] \n| image_map           = Java Locator.svg\n| image_map_caption   = [[Java]] region in Indonesia \n| pushpin_map  = Indonesia_Surabaya#Indonesia Java#Indonesia#Southeast Asia \n| pushpin_label = SUB\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in East Java / Indonesia\n| metric-elev  = \n| metric-rwy   = y\n| r1-number    = 10/28\n| r1-length-f  = 9,843\n| r1-length-m  = 3,000x55m\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year    = 2017\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 21,882,335 ({{increase}} 23.9%)\n| stat3-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat3-data = 99,877({{increase}} 10.7%)\n| footnotes    = Source: [[List of the busiest airports in Indonesia]]\n}}\n\n'''Juanda International Airport (JIA)''' ({{lang-id|Bandar Udara Internasional Juanda}}) {{Airport codes|SUB|WARR}}, is an international airport located in [[Sedati]], [[Sidoarjo]]. It is now the [[List of the busiest airports in Indonesia|third busiest airport in Indonesia]] (after [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Soekarno-Hatta]] and [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Ngurah Rai airport]]). This airport is located approximately 12 kilometers (8 miles) from [[Surabaya]] and serves the [[Surabaya metropolitan area]], the metropolitan area of Surabaya plus extended urban area. Juanda International Airport is operated by [[Angkasa Pura|PT Angkasa Pura I]]. The airport takes its name after [[Djuanda Kartawidjaja]], the last [[Prime Minister of Indonesia]] who had suggested development of this airport. In 2013, the airport serves about 400 aircraft per day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://surabaya.tribunnews.com/2014/01/09/soekarwo-bandara-juanda-butuh-double-runway |title=Soekarwo : Bandara Juanda Butuh Double Runway|website=Surabaya.tribunnews.com  |date=9 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, Juanda International Airport is the hub of [[Citilink]], [[Garuda Indonesia]], [[Indonesia AirAsia]], [[Lion Air]] and [[Sriwijaya Air]] along with [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport]]. Juanda International Airport will become one of the main airports in Indonesia for ASEAN [[Open skies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beritatrans.com/2014/09/13/kemenhub-5-bandara-siap-hadapi-asean-open-sky/ |title=Kemenhub; Lima Bandara Disiapkan Untuk Asean Open Sky |website=Beritatrans.com |date= |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Juanda International Airport becomes the world's 10th best in Airport Service Quality by [[Airport Council International]] among 79 airports with passengers capacity between 5-15 million a year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://finance.detik.com/read/2015/04/24/164442/2897525/4/layanan-bandara-ngurah-rai-terbaik-no7-dunia |title=Layanan Bandara Ngurah Rai Terbaik No.7 Dunia |author=Feby Dwi Sutianto |website=Finance.detik.com|date=April 24, 2015}}</ref> In Q1 2015, the airport becomes the world's 7th best in Airport Service Quality by [[Airport Council International|ACI]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beritasatu.com/destinasi/280323-bandara-ngurah-rai-peringkat-ketiga-terbaik-dunia.html |title=Bandara Ngurah Rai Peringkat Ketiga Terbaik Dunia |website=Beritasatu.com|date=June 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nOpened in 1964 as a naval air base of Indonesia. It replaces the previous airport in Morokrembangan, near [[Surabaya|the city center]]. It was originally used as home base for [[Indonesian Navy]]'s fleet of [[Ilyushin Il-28]] and [[Fairey Gannet]]. In its development it was also used for civil aviation. And PT Angkasa Pura I handled the management and operation since January 1985. On December 24, 1990 Juanda Airport was gained international airport status after the opening of the international terminal. Previously, since December 1987, the airport has served flights to [[Singapore]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Taipei]] and [[Manila]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airport-technology.com/projects/juanda-international-airport/ |title=Juanda International Airport, Indonesia|website=Airport-technology.com |accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Development of airport city==\nOn February 25, 2015, Indonesia President [[Joko Widodo]] agreed to develop Juanda Airport City, including an additional two runways and an integrated connection between Gubeng railway station and the airport via an elevated railway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://surabaya.tribunnews.com/2015/02/26/presiden-jokowi-setujui-proyek-juanda-airport-city |title=Presiden Jokowi Setujui Proyek Juanda Airport City|website=Surabaya.tribunnews.com |date=February 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://surabaya.tribunnews.com/2015/02/26/presiden-jokowi-setujui-proyek-juanda-airport-city?page=2 |title=Presiden Jokowi Setujui Proyek Juanda Airport City|website=Surabaya.tribunnews.com  |date=February 26, 2015}}</ref> About 6,000 hectares of land have been prepared for the expansion of the airport - where in 1,500 hectares will be used to construct two additional runways, and Juanda Airport's Terminal 3, while the remaining area will be used to construct the Airport City and the Ultimate Terminal Building.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.tempo.co/read/news/2016/04/24/056765375/Surabaya-to-Reclaim-Northern-Coastline-to-Expand-Juanda-Airport|title=Surabaya to Reclaim Northern Coastline to Expand Juanda Airport|newspaper=Tempo|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><!--Terminal 3 will be predicted to handle 62.5 million passengers per year, with the overload Terminal 1 and 2, total passenger handling capacity will increase to 75 million passengers per year. Besides building Terminal 3, PT Angkasa Pura I will also be adding two new runways. The runways will be around 3850 meters long and 60% of it will be over the sea. If construction began with no delay it is predicted to open in 2019.-->\n\nThe new area for Juanda Airport is estimated to be 1,700 hectares and will be located in the northern part of the airport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2017/09/01/pt-angkasa-pura-i-to-improve-juanda-international-airport.html|title=PT Angkasa Pura I to improve Juanda International Airport|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> Construction of two runways by will require the reclamation of about four kilometers stretch of land along Java's northern coastline. The land acquisition is expected to be completed by 2018. Development consists of three phases;  \n*First phase is the confirmation of the masterplan, land acquisition, reclamation for runway 2 and construction of runway 2.\n*Second phase is the development of Terminal 1, reclamation for runway 3, construction of runway 3 and accessibility from toll roads and terminal.  \n*Third phase will be building an Ultimate Terminal and airport city supporting infrastructure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.tempo.co/read/news/2016/01/06/056733494/Juanda-Airport-to-Build-Terminal-III-New-Runway|title=Juanda Airport to Build Terminal III, New Runway|newspaper=Tempo|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Terminals and runway==\nAt present, Juanda International Airport has 2 terminals.\nA new three-storey terminal building was opened in October 2006, which is now Terminal 1. The building has a capacity of eight million passengers per year and features a {{convert|51500|m2|adj=on}} domestic passenger terminal, a {{convert|20200|m2|adj=on}} international terminal and 11 aerobridges. The terminal used a mix of high hat roofs from Rumah adat [[Sumba]] as well as [[Java-Malay architecture]] themes. Terminal 1 is used for all domestic flights, except Garuda Indonesia and Indonesia AirAsia flights.\n\nTerminal 2 was built by demolishing the old terminal building, which was opened on February 14, 2014. The architecture of T2 is modern with curved features when compared to Terminal 1. Terminal 2 has an area of 49,500 square meters and 8 aerobridges, with a capacity to accommodate 6 million passengers per year. Terminal 2 is used for all international flights, Garuda Indonesia and Indonesia AirAsia domestic and international flights. In addition, Terminal 2 features the Garuda Indonesia Executive Lounge for domestic flights and the Concordia Premier Lounge for international flights.\n\nThe airport has separate {{convert|5300|m2|adj=on}} administration building, including a 15-storey control tower, and a two-storey cargo building with domestic and international cargo sections, capable of handling {{convert|120000|t}} of cargo a year. The apron with an area of {{convert|148000|m2}} can handle 18 aircraft simultaneously, including two wide body, 11 medium and five small aircraft. The airport has a single runway of {{convert|3000|x|55|m|ft|0}}. There are two {{convert|3000|x|30|m|0|adj=on}} parallel taxiways, including five exit taxiways (30&nbsp;m wide) and four connecting taxiways (also 30&nbsp;m). The airport has a parking area of 28,900 m\u00b2 parking area that can accommodate more than 3,000 vehicles.\n\n== Airlines and destinations ==\n<!-- WHEN ADDING A NEW ROUTE, OR ADDING AN END DATE FOR A ROUTE PLEASE ADD A REFERENCE, ALSO ADD THE ROUTE AND LINK ON THE CORRESPONDING AIRPORTS ARTICLE AND THE AIRLINES ARTICLE IF IT IS A NEW DESTINATION, ANYTHING WHICH IS NOT REFERENCED WILL BE REMOVED. ALSO WHEN ADDING A NEW ROUTE, A FIRM DATE IS MANDATORY.-->\n{{Airport-dest-list\n<!-- -->\n<!-- -->|[[AirAsia]]| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]]\n<!-- -->\n<!--+-->|[[Airfast Indonesia]]| [[Harun Thohir Airport|Bawean]], [[Dewandaru Airport|Karimunjawa]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]] \n<!--+-->|[[Batik Air]]|[[Pattimura Airport|Ambon]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]],<ref name=\"lionair.co.id\">{{cite web|url=https://agent.lionair.co.id/LionAirAgentsPortal/Default.aspx|title=Default|website=Agent.lionair.co.id|accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref> [[Jalaluddin Airport|Gorontalo]], [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Halim Perdanakusuma]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]], [[Komodo Airport|Labuan Bajo]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto International Airport|Samarinda]], [[Domine Eduard Osok Airport|Sorong]]\n<!--+-->|[[Cathay Pacific]]|[[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]]\n<!--+-->|[[Citilink]]|[[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]],<ref name=\"citilink.co.id\">https://www.citilink.co.id/rute-baru-atr-sub</ref> [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Halim Perdanakusuma]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]], [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|Jeddah]],<ref>{{cite web |url=h