\n<!--+-->|[[Malaysia Airlines]]|[[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n<!-- -->\n<!--+-->|[[NAM Air]]|[[Bersujud Airport|Batulicin]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Gusti Syamsir Alam Airport|Kotabaru]], [[El Tari Airport|Kupang]], [[Zainuddin Abdul Madjid International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Iskandar Airport|Pangkalan Bun]], [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto International Airport|Samarinda]], [[Ahmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]]\n <!-- -->\n<!--+-->|{{nowrap|[[Royal Brunei Airlines]]}}|[[Brunei International Airport|Bandar Seri Begawan]]\n<!--+-->|[[Saudia]]|[[King Abdulaziz International Airport|Jeddah]], [[Prince Mohammad Bin Abdulaziz Airport|Medina]], [[King Khalid International Airport|Riyadh]]\n<!--+-->|[[Scoot]]|[[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n<!--+-->|[[SilkAir]]|[[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|[[Singapore Airlines]]|[[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|[[Sriwijaya Air]]|[[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]],<ref name=\"sriwijayaair.co.id\">{{Cite web |url=https://agent.sriwijayaair.co.id/SJ-Eticket/login.php?action=in |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205143051/http://agent.sriwijayaair.co.id/SJ-Eticket/login.php?action=in |archive-date=5 February 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Kalimarau Airport|Berau]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]],<ref name=\"sriwijayaair.co.id\"/> [[Presidente Nicolau Lobato International Airport|Dili]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[Haluoleo Airport|Kendari]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[H. Asan Airport|Sampit]], [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto International Airport|Samarinda]], [[Domine Eduard Osok Airport|Sorong]], [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]]<br>\n|[[Trigana Air Service]]| [[Iskandar Airport|Pangkalan Bun]]\n<!-- --> \n<!--+-->|[[TransNusa]]|[[Adisutjipto International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013Adisucipto]]<ref name=\"Citilink_JOG\"/>\n<!--+-->|[[Wings Air]]|[[Husein Sastranegara International Airport|Bandung\u2013Husein]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Sultan Muhammad Salahuddin Airport|Bima]], [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[H. Hasan Aroeboesman Airport|Ende]], [[Notohadinegoro Airport|Jember]], [[Komodo Airport|Labuan Bajo]], [[Iskandar Airport|Pangkalan Bun]],<ref name=\"lionair.co.id\"/> [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]]<ref>amp.kompas.com/otomotif/read/2010/03/06/1116392/April.Wings.Air.Buka.Rute.Surabaya-Pontianak</ref>, [[H. Asan Airport|Sampit]], [[Ahmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Sultan Muhammad Kaharuddin III Airport|Sumbawa Besar]], [[Trunojoyo Airport|Sumenep]],<ref name=\"lionair.co.id\"/> [[Adisumarmo International Airport|Surakarta/Solo]], [[Adisutjipto International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013Adisucipto]]\n<!--+-->}}\n\n== Statistics ==\nIn 2010, the airport handled 11 million passengers, although the capacity was 6 million passengers and the [[Air Traffic Controller]] radar system is only able to track 21 aircraft per hour, but at peak hour handled 40 to 45 aircraft landing and taking off.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/29/major-ri-airports-bursting-seams-inaca.html |title=Major RI airports bursting at the seams: Inaca |newspaper=[[The Jakarta Post]] |date=2011-07-29 |accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\nThe following are statistics for the airport from 1999 to 2013. In addition to this, it is noted that, in 2006, the domestic sector between Surabaya and Jakarta is the fourth-busiest air route in Asia with over 750 weekly flights.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Total<br>passengers !! Cargo (tons) !! Aircraft<br> movements\n|-\n| 1999 || 2,137,353 || 40,549 || 52,284\n|-\n| 2000 || 2,712,074 || 31,185 || 54,154\n|-\n| 2001 || 3,301,435 || 37,767 || 62,141\n|-\n| 2002 || 4,746,113 || 43,089 || 75,921\n|-\n| 2003 || 6,584,711 || 42,910 || 82,779\n|-\n| 2004 || 8,562,747 || 63,950 || 97,421\n|-\n| 2005 || 8,217,415 || 66,647 || 99,485\n|-\n| 2006 || 8,986,650 || 71,574 || 91.209\n|-\n| 2007 || 8,823,228 || 58,815 || 87,687\n|-\n| 2008 || 9,122,196 || 62,289 || 69,726\n|-\n| 2009 || 10,562,906 || 62,357 || 76,754\n|-\n| 2010 || 12,072,059 || 76,774 || 84,958\n|-\n| 2011 || 13,778,287 || 95,146 || 103,846\n|-\n| 2012 || 16,447,912 || 102,133 || 141,365\n|-\n| 2013 || 17,683,955 || 121,935 || 155,421\n|-\n| 2014 || 18,071,633 || 92,439 || 117,825\n|-\n| 2015 || 18,911,256 || 130,398 || 166,208\n|-\n| 2019 (Estimated) || 23,545,640 || 154,544 || 173,232\n|}\n\nSource : [http://www.angkasapura1.co.id/index.php?modul=keuangan&show=data%20traffic PT (persero) ANGKASA PURA 1] {{in lang|id}}\n\n==Ground transport==\nJuanda Airport is connected to [[Waru-Juanda Toll Road]] to [[Surabaya]], which is about 15 kilometers from the airport. [[Perum DAMRI|DAMRI]] buses are provided by the local government to deliver passengers to Surabaya. Fixed tariff taxis are available to various destinations in Surabaya and surrounding areas including Malang, Blitar, Jember, Tulungagung. Taxi tickets can be purchased at the counter located at the airport exit.\nA monorail will be built and integrated along with the 3 and 4 terminals. The length of the rail is about 20&nbsp;km. The service will have 29 stops that distance between halts 1.5&nbsp;km to 2&nbsp;km.\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n* On 21 February 2007, [[Adam Air Flight 172]] flying from Jakarta to Surabaya with registration PK-KKV (c/n 27284) had a hard landing at this airport, resulting in structural failure of the aircraft.<ref name=\"Flight 172\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/crash-follows-safety-concerns/story-e6freuzi-1111113113161|title=Crash follows safety concerns|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=March 7, 2007|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n* On 13 April 2010, [[Cathay Pacific Flight 780]] from Juanda International Airport to [[Hong Kong International Airport]] landed safely after both engines failed due to contaminated fuel uploaded at the airport. 57 passengers were injured. The two pilots later received the [[Polaris Award]] from the [[International Federation of Air Line Pilots' Associations]] for their heroism and airmanship.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pilots reveal death-defying ordeal as engines failed on approach to Chek Lap Kok |url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/article/1491534/pilots-reveal-death-defying-ordeal-engines-failed-approach |accessdate=21 April 2014|newspaper=South China Morning Post |date=20 April 2014}}</ref>\n* On 1 February 2014, Lion Air Flight 361, a [[Boeing 737-900ER]] (registration PK-LFH) from [[Balikpapan]] [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport]] to Juanda International Airport landed hard and bounced four times on the runway, causing a tail strike and substantial damage to the plane. There were no fatalities, but two passengers were seriously injured and three others had minor injuries.<ref name=JT361>{{cite web|title=Lion Air Flight JT 361|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20140201-0|website=Aviation-safety.net|accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n*On 28 December 2014, [[Indonesia AirAsia Flight 8501]], an Airbus A320-216 registered PK-AXC (MSN 3648) with 155 passengers and 7 crew on board, crashed into the [[Java Sea]] whilst en route from Juanda International Airport to [[Changi International Airport]], Singapore, killing all 162 on board. Regulatory licenses for the Surabaya-Singapore route as well as Medan-Palembang route have been suspended for Indonesia AirAsia since January 2015 due to suspected licensing breaches; the Medan-Palembang route had been resumed, however.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nImage:Juanda4.jpg|Terminal 1 - 2nd Floor\nImage:Cathay juanda.jpg|A [[Cathay Pacific]] [[Airbus A330-300]] at Juanda\nImage:Juanda Airport Apron.jpg|On the [[apron]], [[Saudi Airlines]] [[Boeing 747-300]] refueling and reloading to serve Indonesian [[Hajj]] pilgrims to [[Mecca]].\nImage:Valuair juanda1.jpg|[[Valuair]] [[Airbus A320-200]] arriving from [[Singapore]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Juanda International Airport}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070727132513/http://www.angkasapura1.co.id/eng/location/surabaya.htm PT. Angkasa Pura I: Juanda Airport] {{in lang|en}}\n* [https://www.travelloratour.com/travel-malang-surabaya/ Transport Malang To Surabaya]\n* [http://www.juanda-airport.com/ Juanda International Airport website]\n* {{WAD|WARR}}\n* {{ASN|SUB}}\n\n<!--Navigation box--><br>\n{{Airports in Indonesia}}\n{{Portal|Indonesia|Aviation}}\n\n[[Category:Surabaya]]\n[[Category:Transport in East Java]]\n[[Category:Airports in East Java]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Indonesia]]\n", "name_user": "Meandkancil2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAirlines and destinations:Add References For Indonesia AirAsia (QZ) Surabaya - Johor Bahru", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juanda_International_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Amrita Sher-Gil", "text_new": "{{short description|Hungarian-Indian painter}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| image = Amrita Sher-Gil 2.jpg\n| caption =\n| alt = Sher-Gil in an ornate gown and jewelry\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{birth date |df=yes|1913|1|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Budapest]], [[Kingdom of Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1941|12|5|1913|1|30}}\n| death_place = [[Lahore]], [[British Raj|British India]] (present-day [[Pakistan]])\n| nationality =Hungarian / Indian\n| movement =\n| awards =\n| patrons =\n| imagesize = \n| field = [[Painting]]\n| training = [[Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re|Grande Chaumiere]]<br>[[\u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]] (1930\u201334)\n| works =\n| url = \n}}\n\n'''Amrita Sher-Gil''' (30 January 1913 \u2013 5 December 1941) was an eminent Hungarian-Indian [[Painting|painter]]. She has been called \"one of the greatest avant-garde women artists of the early 20th century\" and a \"pioneer\" in modern Indian art. Drawn to painting from an early age, Sher-Gil started getting formal lessons in the art, at the age of eight. She first gained recognition at the age of 19, for her [[oil painting]] titled ''Young Girls'' (1932).\n\nSher-Gil traveled throughout her life to various countries including Turkey, France, and India, deriving heavily from precolonial Indian art styles and its current culture. Sher-Gil is considered an important painter of 20th-century India, whose legacy stands on a level with that of the pioneers from the [[Bengali Renaissance|Bengal Renaissance]]. She was also an avid reader and a pianist. Sher-Gil's paintings are among the most expensive by Indian women painters today, although few acknowledged her work when she was alive. Cre4my_L3v roblox\n\n==Early life and education==\n\n[[File:Amrita with Indira 1922.jpg|thumb|150px|left| Amrita with her sister Indira, 1922]]\n\nAmrita Sher-Gil was born on 30 January 1913<ref name=GreatMinds>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000312/spectrum/main2.htm#3 Great Minds], The Tribune, 12 March 2000.</ref> in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Budapest Diary|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267032|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=20 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120529110336/http://outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267032|archive-date=29 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> to Umrao Singh Sher-Gil Majithia, a  [[Jat sikh|sikh]] aristocrat and a scholar in [[Sanskrit]] and [[Persian language|Persian]], and Marie Antoniette Gottesmann, a [[History of the Jews in Hungary|Hungarian-Jewish]] opera singer who came from an affluent bourgeois family.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10087130/The-Indian-Frida-Kahlo.html|title=The Indian Frida Kahlo|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"christies.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.christies.com/features/Amrita-Sher-Gil-6132-1.aspx|title=Revolution personified {{!}} Christie's'|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> Her parents first met in 1912, while Marie Antoinette was visiting Lahore.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> Her mother came to India as a companion of [[Princess Bamba Sutherland]], the granddaughter of [[Ranjit Singh|Maharaja Ranjit Singh]].<ref name=\"spectrum\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090920/spectrum/main3.htm|title=The Princess who died unknown|last=Kang|first=Kanwarjit Singh|date=20 September 2009|work=The Sunday Tribune|accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Singh|first=Khushwant|title=Hamari Amrita|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230674|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=27 March 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206165148/http://outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230674|archive-date=6 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sher-Gil was the elder of two daughters; her younger sister was Indira Sundaram (n\u00e9e Sher-Gil), born in March 1914), mother of the contemporary artist [[Vivan Sundaram]]. She spent most of early childhood in Budapest.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> She was the niece of Indologist [[Ervin Baktay]]. Baktay noticed Sher-Gil's artistic talents during his visit to Shimla in 1926 and was an advocate of Sher-Gil pursuing art.<ref name=\"christies.com\"/> He guided her by critiquing her work and gave her an academic foundation to grow on. When she was a young girl she would paint the servants in her house, and get them to model for her.<ref name=\"The Better India\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thebetterindia.com/44577/googles-doodle-indian-painter-amrita-shergil/|title=Google's Doodle Honours Amrita Sher-Gil. Here Are 5 Things You Should Know about Her|date=30 January 2016|work=The Better India|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The memories of these models would eventually lead to her return to India.<ref>On Amrita Sher-Gil: Claiming a Radiant Legacy By Nilima Sheikh</ref>\n\nHer family faced financial problems in Hungary. In 1921, her family moved to [[Summer Hill, Shimla]], India, and Sher-Gil soon began learning piano and violin.<ref name=\"The Better India\"/> By age nine she, along with her younger sister Indira, was giving concerts and acting in plays at Shimla's [[Gaiety Theater, Shimla|Gaiety Theatre]] at [[Mall Road, Shimla]].<ref name=AmritaSikhHeritage>[http://www.sikh-heritage.co.uk/arts/amritashergil/amritashergill.html Amrita Shergill at sikh-heritage]. Sikh-heritage.co.uk (30 January 1913).</ref> Though she was already painting since the age of five, she formally started learning painting at age eight.<ref name=AmritaSikhHeritage/> Sher-Gil started getting formal lessons in the art by Major Whitmarsh, who was later replaced by Beven Pateman. In Shimla, Sher-Gil lived a relatively privileged lifestyle.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> As a child, she was expelled from her convent school for declaring herself an atheist.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/>\n\nIn 1923, Marie came to know an Italian [[sculptor]], who was living at Shimla at the time. In 1924, when he returned to Italy, she too moved there along with Amrita and got her enrolled at Santa Annunziata, an art school at [[Florence, Italy|Florence]]. Though Amrita didn't stay at this school for long and returned to India in 1924, it was here that she was exposed to works of Italian masters.<ref name=\"AmritaIndia2\">[http://www.iloveindia.com/indian-heroes/amrita-shergill.html Amrita Shergill Biography at]. Iloveindia.com (6 December 1941).</ref>\n\nAt sixteen, Sher-Gil sailed to Europe with her mother to train as a painter at [[Paris]], first at the [[Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re]] under Pierre Vaillent and [[Lucien Simon]] (where she met [[Boris Taslitzky]]) and later at the [[\u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]] (1930\u201334).<ref>[http://www.hausderkunst.de/hdk.de/index.php?StoryID=2613 Archives 'Amrita Shergil' project] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107051420/http://www.hausderkunst.de/hdk.de/index.php?StoryID=2613 |date=7 January 2009 }} www.hausderkunst.de.</ref><ref>[http://www.indianartcircle.com/arteducation/amrita.shtml Amrita Sher-Gil profile at] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015192242/http://www.indianartcircle.com/arteducation/amrita.shtml |date=15 October 2012 }}. Indianartcircle.com.</ref> She drew inspiration from European painters such as [[Paul C\u00e9zanne]] and [[Paul Gauguin]],<ref name=AmritaTate/> while working under the influence of her teacher Lucien Simon and the company of artist friends and lovers like Tazlitsky. While in Paris, she is said to have painted with a conviction and maturity rarely seen in a 16-year old.<ref name=\"christies.com\"/>\n\nIn 1931, Sher-Gil was briefly engaged to Yusuf Ali Khan, but rumors spread that she was also having an affair with her first cousin and later husband Victor Egan.<ref name=\"Singh\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ranisingh/2015/05/01/undiscovered-amrita-sher-gil-self-portrait-and-rare-indian-emerald-bangles-for-auction/#3a29fbb9b4bb|title=Undiscovered Amrita Sher-Gil Self-Portrait And Rare Indian Emerald Bangles Up For Auction|last=Singh|first=Rani|work=Forbes|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> Her letters reveal same-sex affairs.<ref>{{cite web|author=(Some names have been changed to protect their identities) |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1131215/jsp/7days/17682751.jsp |title=A life not so gay |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date= |accessdate=23 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== 1932\u20131936: Early career, European and Western styles ===\n[[File:Amrita Sher-Gil - Young Girls.jpg|thumb|240px|right|''Young Girls'', 1932, oil on canvas, 133\u00d7164 cm, [http://ngmaindia.gov.in/sh-amrita.asp National Gallery of Modern Art, Delhi]]]\n\nSher-Gil's early paintings display a significant influence of the [[Western art history|Western]] modes of painting, more specifically, the post-impressionism style. She practiced a lot in the Bohemian circles of Paris in the early 1930s. Her 1932 [[oil painting]], ''Young Girls'', came as a breakthrough for her; the work won her accolades, including a gold medal and election as an Associate of the Grand Salon in Paris in 1933. She was the youngest ever member,<ref>Anand, ''[[Amrita Sher-Gil#Anand|Armita Sher-Gil]]''</ref><ref name=\"tatew2\">[http://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/exhibition/amrita-sher-gil/amrita-sher-gil-room-1-early-years-paris Works in Focus], [[Tate Modern]], 2007.</ref><ref>[http://en.ce.cn/entertainment/theater/200703/08/t20070308_10626933.shtml Amrita Shergil at tate]. En.ce.cn.</ref> and the only Asian to have received this recognition.<ref name=\"AmritaIndia2\"/> Her work during this time include a number of self-portraits, as well as life in Paris, nude studies, still life studied, and portraits of friends and fellow students.<ref name=\"ngmaindia.gov.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ngmaindia.gov.in/sh-amrita.asp|title=National Gallery of Modern Art, New Delhi|website=www.ngmaindia.gov.in|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> The National Gallery of Modern Art in New Delhi describes her self-portraits she made while in Paris as \"[capturing] the artist in her many moods \u2013 somber, pensive, and joyous \u2013 while revealing a narcissistic streak in her personality.\" <ref name=\"ngmaindia.gov.in\"/>\n[[File:Painting Sleep 1932.jpg|thumb|''Sleep,'' 1932, oil on canvas 112.5 x 79 cm, National Gallery of Modern Art, Delhi]]\nWhen she was in Paris, one of her professors often said that judging by the richness of her colouring Sher-Gil was not in her element in the west, and that her artistic personality would find its true atmosphere in east.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Amrita Sher-Gil: Art & Life: A Reader|last=Dalmia|first=Yashodhara|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-0-19-809886-7|location=New Delhi|page=5}}</ref> In 1933, Sher-Gil \"began to be haunted by an intense longing to return to India [...] feeling in some strange way that there lay my destiny as a painter.\" Sher-Gill returned to India at the end of 1934.<ref name=\"tele\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2007/02/24/baamrita124.xml Laid bare \u2013 the free spirit of Indian art] [[The Daily Telegraph]], 24 February 2007.</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> In May 1935, Sher-Gil met the English journalist [[Malcolm Muggeridge]], then working as Assistant Editor and leader writer for [[The Statesman (India)|''The Calcutta Statesman'']].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bright-Holmes|first=John|title=Like It Was: The Diaries of Malcolm Muggeridge|year=1981|publisher=Collins|location=entry dated 18 January 1951|isbn=978-0-688-00784-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/likeitwas00malc/page/426 426]|url=https://archive.org/details/likeitwas00malc/page/426|access-date=29 August 2011|url-status=dead|url-access=registration}}</ref> Both Muggeridge and Sher-Gil stayed at the family home at [[Summer Hill, Shimla]] and a short intense affair took place during which she painted a casual portrait of her new lover, the painting now with the National Gallery of Modern Art in New Delhi. By September 1935 Amrita saw Muggeridge off as he traveled back to England for new employment.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wolfe|first=Gregory|title=Malcolm Muggeridge: A Biography|year=2003|publisher=Intercollegiate Studies Institute|location=page 136-137|isbn=1932236066|page=136}}</ref> She left herself for travel in 1936 at the behest of an art collector and critic, [[Karl Jamshed Khandalavala|Karl Khandalavala]], who encouraged her to pursue her passion for discovering her Indian roots.<ref name=\"AmritaTate\">[http://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/exhibition/amrita-sher-gil/amrita-sher-gil-room-1-early-years-paris Amrita Sher-Gil Exhibition at tate.org]</ref> In India, she began a quest for the rediscovery of the traditions of Indian art which was to continue till her death. She was greatly impressed and influenced by the [[Mughal painting|Mughal]] and [[Pahari painting|Pahari]] schools of painting and the cave paintings at [[Ajanta Caves|Ajanta]].\n\n[[File:Amrita Sher-Gil - South Indian Villagers Going to Market.jpg|thumb|right|240px|''South Indian Villagers Going to Market'', 1937.]]\n\n=== 1937\u20131941: Later career, influence of Indian art ===\nLater in 1937, she toured [[South India]]<ref name=AmritaTate/> and produced her South Indian trilogy of paintings ''Bride's Toilet'', ''Brahmacharis'', and ''South Indian Villagers Going to Market'' following her visit to the [[Ajanta Caves]], when she made a conscious attempt to return to classical Indian art. These paintings reveal her passionate sense of color and an equally passionate empathy for her Indian subjects, who are often depicted in their poverty and despair.<ref name=AmritaIndiaprofile>[http://www.indiaprofile.com/people/amritashergill.htm Amrita Shergill at]. Indiaprofile.com (6 December 1941).</ref> By now the transformation in her work was complete and she had found her 'artistic mission' which was, according to her, to express the life of Indian people through her canvas.<ref name=GreatMinds/> While in Saraya Sher-Gil wrote to a friend thus: \"I can only paint in India. Europe belongs to Picasso, Matisse, Braque.... India belongs only to me\".<ref name=\"frontline2013\">{{cite journal|title=Amrita's village|journal=Frontline|date=February\u2013March 2013|volume=30|issue=4|url=http://www.frontline.in/stories/20130308300409000.htm|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref> Her stay in India marks the beginning of a new phase in her artistic development, one that was distinct from the European phase of the interwar years when her work showed an engagement with the works of [[Hungarian painters]], especially the [[Nagybanya]] school of painting.<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_15-12-2004_pg3_5 Daily Times, 15 December 2004]. Dailytimes.com.pk (15 December 2004).</ref>\n\nSher-Gil married her Hungarian first cousin, Dr. Victor Egan when she was 25.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> Dr. Egan had helped Sher-Gil obtain abortions on at least two occasions prior to their marriage.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> She moved with him to India to stay at her paternal family's home in Saraya, Sardar nagar, [[Chauri Chaura]] in [[Gorakhpur, Uttar Pradesh|Gorakhpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Thus began her second phase of painting which equals in its impact on Indian art with the likes of [[Rabindranath Tagore]] and [[Jamini Roy]] of the [[Bengal school of art]]. The 'Calcutta Group' of artists, which transformed the Indian art scene, was to start only in 1943, and the '[[Bombay Progressive Artists' Group|Progressive Artist's Group]]', with [[Francis Newton Souza]], Ara, [[Sadanand Bakre|Bakre]], Gade, [[M. F. Husain]] and [[S. H. Raza]] among its founders, lay further ahead in 1948.<ref name=\"AmritaMaps\">[http://www.mapsofindia.com/who-is-who/art-culture/amrita-sher-gill.html Amrita Sher-Gill at]. Mapsofindia.com.</ref><ref>[http://www.contemporaryart-india.com/art%20_movements_in_india.php Contemporary Art Movements in India]. Contemporaryart-india.com.</ref><ref>[http://www.art.in/indian-artists.htm Indian artists]. Art.in.</ref> Amrita's art was strongly influenced by the paintings of the two Tagores, Rabindranath and [[Abanindranath Tagore|Abanindranath]] who were the pioneers of the Bengal School of painting. Her portraits of women resemble works by Rabindranath while the use of '[[chiaroscuro]]' and bright colors reflect the influence of Abanindranath.<ref>{{cite news|title=Art into life|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/nqAAESbsrngHM94BTy0kRI/Art-into-life.html|accessdate=6 February 2013|newspaper=HT Mint|date=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt was during her stay at Saraya that she painted the ''Village Scene'', ''In the Ladies' Enclosure'' and ''Siesta'' all of which portray the leisurely rhythms of life in rural India. ''Siesta'' and ''In the Ladies' Enclosure'' reflect her experimentation with the [[Indian painting|miniature school of painting]] while ''Village Scene'' reflects influences of the [[Pahari painting|Pahari school of painting]].<ref name=\"outlookindia_a\">{{cite news|title=White Shadows|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230586|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=20 March 2006}}</ref> Although acclaimed by art critics Karl Khandalavala in Bombay and Charles Fabri in Lahore as the greatest painter of the century, Amrita's paintings found few buyers. She travelled across India with her paintings but the Nawab [[Salar Jung III|Salar Jung]] of [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]] returned them and the [[Maharaja of Mysore]] chose [[Raja Ravi Varma|Ravi Varma's]] paintings over hers.<ref name=\"outlookindia\">{{cite news|title=Hamari Amrita|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230674|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=27 March 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206165148/http://outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230674|archive-date=6 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlthough from a family that was closely tied to the [[British Raj]], Amrita herself was a [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] sympathiser. She was attracted to the poor, distressed and the deprived and her paintings of Indian villagers and women are a meditative reflection of their condition. She was also attracted by Gandhi's philosophy and lifestyle. [[Jawaharlal Nehru|Nehru]] was charmed by her beauty and talent and when he went to Gorakhpur in October 1940, he visited her at Saraya. Her paintings were at one stage even considered for use in the Congress propaganda for village reconstruction.<ref name=\"frontline2013\"/> However, despite being friends with Nehru, Sher-Gil never drew his portrait, supposedly because the artist thought he was \"too good looking.\"<ref name=\"indiatoday.intoday.in\">{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/education/story/amrita-sher-gil/1/869889.html|title=Why Amrita Sher-Gil refused to draw Nehru's portrait : Art and Culture|website=indiatoday.intoday.in|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> Nehru attended her exhibition held in New Delhi in February 1937.<ref name=\"indiatoday.intoday.in\"/> Sher-Gil exchanged letters with Nehru for a time, but those letters were burned by her parents when she was away getting married in Budapest.<ref name=\"indiatoday.intoday.in\"/>\n\nIn September 1941, Victor and Amrita moved to [[Lahore]], then in [[undivided India]] and a major cultural and artistic centre. She lived and painted at 23 Ganga Ram Mansions, The Mall, Lahore where her studio was on the top floor of the townhouse she inhabited. Amrita was known for her many affairs with both men and women<ref name=tele/> and many of the latter she also painted. Her work ''Two Women'' is thought to be a painting of herself and her lover Marie Louise.<ref>{{cite news|title=Passion And Precedent|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?206737|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=21 December 1998}}</ref> Some of her later works include ''Tahitian'' (1937), ''Red Brick House'' (1938), ''Hill Scene'' (1938), and ''The Bride'' (1940) among others. Her last work was left unfinished by her just prior to her death in December 1941.\n\nIn 1941, at age 28, just days before the opening of her first major solo show in Lahore, she became seriously ill and slipped into a coma.<ref name=\"tele\"/><ref name=\"budapesttimes.hu\">{{cite web|url=http://budapesttimes.hu/2016/01/23/great-success-in-a-short-life/|title=Great success in a short life {{!}} The Budapest Times|website=budapesttimes.hu|language=en-US|access-date=14 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124101915/http://budapesttimes.hu/2016/01/23/great-success-in-a-short-life/|archive-date=24 January 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b072j32f|title=Amrita Sher-Gil: This Is Me, Incarnations: India in 50 Lives \u2013 BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> She later died around midnight on 5 December 1941,<ref>{{cite journal |journal=India International Centre Quarterly |title=Amrita Sher-Gil |first=N Iqbal |last=Singh |volume=2 |issue=3 |date=July 1975 |jstor=23001838 |page=216}}</ref> leaving behind a large volume of work. The reason for her death has never been ascertained. A failed abortion and subsequent [[peritonitis]] have been suggested as possible causes for her death.<ref>Truth, Love and a Little Malice, An Autobiography by [[Khushwant Singh]] Penguin, 2003. {{ISBN|0-14-302957-6}}.</ref> Her mother accused her doctor husband Victor of having murdered her. The day after her death Britain declared war on Hungary and Victor was sent to jail as a national enemy. Amrita was cremated on 7 December 1941 at Lahore.<ref name=\"outlookindia\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Roads in New Delhi 04.jpg|thumb|Road named in Delhi after Shergil]]\nSher-Gil's art has influenced generations of Indian artists from [[S. H. Raza|Sayed Haider Raza]] to [[Arpita Singh]] and her depiction of the plight of women has made her art a beacon for women at large both in India and abroad.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sad In Bright Clothes|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?283591|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=28 January 2013}}</ref> The [[Government of India]] has declared her works as National Art Treasures,<ref name=AmritaMaps/><ref name=\"The Better India\"/>  and most of them are housed in the [[National Gallery of Modern Art]] in [[New Delhi]].<ref>[http://www.culturalindia.net/indian-art/painters/amrita-shergil.html Amrita Sher-Gil at]. Culturalindia.net (30 January 1913).</ref><ref name=\"ngmaindia.gov.in\"/> Some of her paintings also hang at the Lahore Museum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://scroll.in/magazine/827982/when-amrita-sher-gil-vowed-to-seduce-khushwant-singh-to-take-revenge-on-his-wife|title=When Amrita Sher-Gil vowed to seduce Khushwant Singh to take revenge on his wife|last=Dutt|first=Nirupama|work=Scroll.in|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> A postage stamp depicting her painting 'Hill Women' was released in 1978 by [[India Post]], and the Amrita Shergil Marg is a road in [[Lutyens' Delhi]] named after her. Amrita was able to prove to western societies that Indians where able to make fine art.Her work is deemed to be so important to Indian culture that when it is sold in India, the Indian government has stipulated that the art must stay in the country \u2013 fewer than ten of her works have been sold globally.<ref name=\"Singh\"/> In 2006, her painting ''Village Scene'' sold for {{INR}}6.9 crores at an auction in [[New Delhi]] which was at the time the highest amount ever paid for a painting in India.<ref name=\"outlookindia_a\" />\n\nThe Indian cultural center in Budapest is named the Amrita Sher-Gil Cultural Center.<ref name=\"budapesttimes.hu\"/> Contemporary artists in India have recreated and reinterpreted her works.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/two-artists-are-recreating-painter-amrita-sher-gil-s-self-portraits/story-l07Jv15KCyTXABIeUR2DoJ.html|title=Two artists are recreating painter Amrita Sher-Gil's self portraits|date=23 March 2017|work=hindustantimes.com/|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBesides remaining an inspiration to many a contemporary Indian artists, in 1993, she also became the inspiration behind the Urdu play ''[[Tumhari Amrita]]''.<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/mag/2006/08/13/stories/2006081300290200.htm Digital encounters] ''[[The Hindu]]'', 13 August 2006]</ref><ref name=\"The Better India\"/>\n\nUNESCO announced 2013, the 100th anniversary of Sher-Gil's birth, to be the international year of Amrita Sher-Gil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mma.hu/en/web/en/what-s-on/-/event/153538/amrita-sher-gil-in-paris|title=Amrita Sher-Gil in Paris {{!}} Magyar M\u0171v\u00e9szeti Akad\u00e9mia|website=www.mma.hu|language=en-US|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nSher-Gil's work is a key theme in the contemporary Indian novel ''Faking It'' by Amrita Chowdhury.<ref>{{cite book|title=Faking It \u2013 Amrita V Chowdhury|isbn = 9789350094051|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3GyC-0MweoQC|accessdate=5 February 2013|last1 = Chowdhury|first1 = Amrita V.|date = 7 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nAurora Zogoiby, a character in [[Salman Rushdie]]'s 1995 novel ''The Moor's Last Sigh'', was inspired by Sher-Gil.<ref>\"Amrita Sher-Gil: A Self-Portrait in Letters and Writings\", ed. Vivan Sundaram, [[Tulika Books]], 2010</ref>\n\nSher-Gil was sometimes known as India's [[Frida Kahlo]] because of the \"revolutionary\" way she blended Western and traditional art forms.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/><ref name=\"AmritaMaps\" />\n\nIn 2018, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published a belated obituary for her.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/20/obituaries/amrita-shergil-dead.html?smid=tw-nytobits&smtyp=cur |title=Overlooked No More: Amrita Sher-Gil, a Pioneer of Indian Art |work=The New York Times |date= |accessdate=23 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, at a Sotheby's auction in Mumbai, Amrita Shergil's painting \"The Little Girl in Blue\" was auctioned for a record-breaking 18.69 crores. This painting is a portrait of Amrita's cousin Babit, a resident of Shimla and was painted in 1934, when the subject was 8 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/ZcJZwPQCaHJOjXdIqjzAdK/Sothebys-Mumbai-auction-Amrita-SherGils-The-Little-Girl.html|title=Sotheby's Mumbai auction: Amrita Sher-Gil's 'The Little Girl in Blue' fetches record bid of \u20b918.69 crore}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"250px\" heights=\"250px\">\nFile:Amrita Sher-Gil Self-portrait.jpg|Self-portrait, 1930\nFile:Amrita Sher-Gil Self-portrait, untitled.jpg|Self-portrait (untitled), 1931\nFile:Amrita Sger-Gil Klarra Szepessy.jpg|Kl\u00e1ra Szepessy, 1932\nFile:Amrita Sher-Gil Hungarian-gypsy-girl.jpg|Hungarian Gypsy Girl, 1932\nFile:Amrita Sher-Gil Group of Three Girls.jpg|Group of Three Girls, 1935\nFile:Amrita Sger-Gil Bride's Toilet.jpg|Bride's Toilet, 1937\nFile:Village-scene-1938.jpg|Village Scene, 1938\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil'', by Karl J. Khandalavala. New Book Co., 1945\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: Essays'', by [[Vivan Sundaram]], Marg Publications; New Delhi, 1972.\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil'', by Baldoon Dhingra. [[Lalit Kala Akademi]], New Delhi, 1981. {{ISBN|0-86186-644-4}}.\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil and Hungary'', by Gyula Wojtilla . Allied Publishers, 1981.\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: A Biography'' by N. Iqbal Singh, ''Vikas Publishing House Pvt.Ltd., India'', 1984. {{ISBN|0-7069-2474-6}}\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: A personal view'', by Ahmad Salim. Istaarah Publications; 1987.\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil'', by [[Mulk Raj Anand]]. [[National Gallery of Modern Art]]; 1989.\n* ''Amrita Shergil: Amrita Shergil ka Jivan aur Rachana samsar'', by [[Kanhaiyalal Nandan]]. 2000.\n* ''Re-take of Amrita'', by [[Vivan Sundaram]]. 2001, Tulika. {{ISBN|81-85229-49-X}}\n* ''Amrita Sher Gil \u2013 A Painted Life'' by Geeta Doctor, ''Rupa'' 2002, {{ISBN|81-7167-688-X}}\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: A Life'' by Yashodhara Dalmia, 2006. {{ISBN|0-670-05873-4}}\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: An Indian Artist Family of the Twentieth Century'', by [[Vivan Sundaram]], 2007, Schirmer/Mosel. {{ISBN|3-8296-0270-7}}\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: A Self-Portrait in Letters and Writings'' edited by Vivan Sundaram, Tulika Books, 2010.\n* ''Feminine Fables: Imaging the Indian Woman in Painting, Photography and Cinema'', by Geeti Sen, Mapin Publishing, 2002.\n* ''The Art of Amrita Sher-Gil'', Series of the Roerich Centre of Art and Culture. Allahabad Block Works, 1943.\n* ''Sher-Gil, by Amrita Sher-Gil'', [[Lalit Kala Akademi]], 1965.\n* ''India\u2019s 50 Most Illustrious Women'' by Indra Gupta {{ISBN|81-88086-19-3}}\n* ''Famous Indians of the 20th century'' by Vishwamitra Sharma. Pustak Mahal, 2003, {{ISBN|81-223-0829-5}}\n* ''When was Modernism: Essays on Contemporary Cultural Practice in India,'' by Geeta Kapur, 2000.\n*{{cite journal |last=Rahman |first=Maseeh |authorlink= |authormask= |date=6 October 2014 |title=In the shadow of death |department=The Arts |journal=[[India Today]] |volume=39 |issue=40 |pages=68\u201369}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite AV media |people= Anand, Mulk Raj|year= 1989|title= Amrita Sher-Gill|medium= English|place=Jaipur|publisher= National Gallery of Modern Art|ref=Anand}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Amrita Sher-Gil}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://ngmaindia.gov.in/sh-amrita.asp Showcase:Amrita Sher-Gil] at [[National Gallery of Modern Art]]\n*[https://historyoffineartdk.blogspot.com/2019/11/1913-1941.html \u0905\u092e\u0943\u0924\u093e \u0936\u0947\u0930\u0917\u093f\u0932]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sher-Gil, Amrita}}\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Lahore]]\n[[Category:People from Shimla]]\n[[Category:Jewish women painters]]\n[[Category:Indian Sikhs]]\n[[Category:Indian people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Indian women painters]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Indian portrait painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Hungarian painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian painters]]\n[[Category:Bisexual artists]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from Hungary]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from India]]\n[[Category:Painters from Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Women artists from Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Hungarian women painters]]\n[[Category:Indian Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hungarian-Indian painter}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| image = Amrita Sher-Gil 2.jpg\n| caption =\n| alt = Sher-Gil in an ornate gown and jewelry\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{birth date |df=yes|1913|1|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Budapest]], [[Kingdom of Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1941|12|5|1913|1|30}}\n| death_place = [[Lahore]], [[British Raj|British India]] (present-day [[Pakistan]])\n| nationality =Hungarian / Indian\n| movement =\n| awards =\n| patrons =\n| imagesize = \n| field = [[Painting]]\n| training = [[Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re|Grande Chaumiere]]<br>[[\u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]] (1930\u201334)\n| works =\n| url = \n}}\n\n'''Amrita Sher-Gil''' (30 January 1913 \u2013 5 December 1941) was an eminent Hungarian-Indian [[Painting|painter]]. She has been called \"one of the greatest avant-garde women artists of the early 20th century\" and a \"pioneer\" in modern Indian art. Drawn to painting from an early age, Sher-Gil started getting formal lessons in the art, at the age of eight. She first gained recognition at the age of 19, for her [[oil painting]] titled ''Young Girls'' (1932).\n\nSher-Gil traveled throughout her life to various countries including Turkey, France, and India, deriving heavily from precolonial Indian art styles and its current culture. Sher-Gil is considered an important painter of 20th-century India, whose legacy stands on a level with that of the pioneers from the [[Bengali Renaissance|Bengal Renaissance]]. She was also an avid reader and a pianist. Sher-Gil's paintings are among the most expensive by Indian women painters today, although few acknowledged her work when she was alive.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\n[[File:Amrita with Indira 1922.jpg|thumb|150px|left| Amrita with her sister Indira, 1922]]\n\nAmrita Sher-Gil was born on 30 January 1913<ref name=GreatMinds>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000312/spectrum/main2.htm#3 Great Minds], The Tribune, 12 March 2000.</ref> in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Budapest Diary|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267032|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=20 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120529110336/http://outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267032|archive-date=29 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> to Umrao Singh Sher-Gil Majithia, a  [[Jat sikh|sikh]] aristocrat and a scholar in [[Sanskrit]] and [[Persian language|Persian]], and Marie Antoniette Gottesmann, a [[History of the Jews in Hungary|Hungarian-Jewish]] opera singer who came from an affluent bourgeois family.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10087130/The-Indian-Frida-Kahlo.html|title=The Indian Frida Kahlo|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"christies.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.christies.com/features/Amrita-Sher-Gil-6132-1.aspx|title=Revolution personified {{!}} Christie's'|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> Her parents first met in 1912, while Marie Antoinette was visiting Lahore.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> Her mother came to India as a companion of [[Princess Bamba Sutherland]], the granddaughter of [[Ranjit Singh|Maharaja Ranjit Singh]].<ref name=\"spectrum\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090920/spectrum/main3.htm|title=The Princess who died unknown|last=Kang|first=Kanwarjit Singh|date=20 September 2009|work=The Sunday Tribune|accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Singh|first=Khushwant|title=Hamari Amrita|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230674|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=27 March 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206165148/http://outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230674|archive-date=6 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sher-Gil was the elder of two daughters; her younger sister was Indira Sundaram (n\u00e9e Sher-Gil), born in March 1914), mother of the contemporary artist [[Vivan Sundaram]]. She spent most of early childhood in Budapest.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> She was the niece of Indologist [[Ervin Baktay]]. Baktay noticed Sher-Gil's artistic talents during his visit to Shimla in 1926 and was an advocate of Sher-Gil pursuing art.<ref name=\"christies.com\"/> He guided her by critiquing her work and gave her an academic foundation to grow on. When she was a young girl she would paint the servants in her house, and get them to model for her.<ref name=\"The Better India\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thebetterindia.com/44577/googles-doodle-indian-painter-amrita-shergil/|title=Google's Doodle Honours Amrita Sher-Gil. Here Are 5 Things You Should Know about Her|date=30 January 2016|work=The Better India|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The memories of these models would eventually lead to her return to India.<ref>On Amrita Sher-Gil: Claiming a Radiant Legacy By Nilima Sheikh</ref>\n\nHer family faced financial problems in Hungary. In 1921, her family moved to [[Summer Hill, Shimla]], India, and Sher-Gil soon began learning piano and violin.<ref name=\"The Better India\"/> By age nine she, along with her younger sister Indira, was giving concerts and acting in plays at Shimla's [[Gaiety Theater, Shimla|Gaiety Theatre]] at [[Mall Road, Shimla]].<ref name=AmritaSikhHeritage>[http://www.sikh-heritage.co.uk/arts/amritashergil/amritashergill.html Amrita Shergill at sikh-heritage]. Sikh-heritage.co.uk (30 January 1913).</ref> Though she was already painting since the age of five, she formally started learning painting at age eight.<ref name=AmritaSikhHeritage/> Sher-Gil started getting formal lessons in the art by Major Whitmarsh, who was later replaced by Beven Pateman. In Shimla, Sher-Gil lived a relatively privileged lifestyle.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> As a child, she was expelled from her convent school for declaring herself an atheist.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/>\n\nIn 1923, Marie came to know an Italian [[sculptor]], who was living at Shimla at the time. In 1924, when he returned to Italy, she too moved there along with Amrita and got her enrolled at Santa Annunziata, an art school at [[Florence, Italy|Florence]]. Though Amrita didn't stay at this school for long and returned to India in 1924, it was here that she was exposed to works of Italian masters.<ref name=\"AmritaIndia2\">[http://www.iloveindia.com/indian-heroes/amrita-shergill.html Amrita Shergill Biography at]. Iloveindia.com (6 December 1941).</ref>\n\nAt sixteen, Sher-Gil sailed to Europe with her mother to train as a painter at [[Paris]], first at the [[Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re]] under Pierre Vaillent and [[Lucien Simon]] (where she met [[Boris Taslitzky]]) and later at the [[\u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]] (1930\u201334).<ref>[http://www.hausderkunst.de/hdk.de/index.php?StoryID=2613 Archives 'Amrita Shergil' project] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107051420/http://www.hausderkunst.de/hdk.de/index.php?StoryID=2613 |date=7 January 2009 }} www.hausderkunst.de.</ref><ref>[http://www.indianartcircle.com/arteducation/amrita.shtml Amrita Sher-Gil profile at] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015192242/http://www.indianartcircle.com/arteducation/amrita.shtml |date=15 October 2012 }}. Indianartcircle.com.</ref> She drew inspiration from European painters such as [[Paul C\u00e9zanne]] and [[Paul Gauguin]],<ref name=AmritaTate/> while working under the influence of her teacher Lucien Simon and the company of artist friends and lovers like Tazlitsky. While in Paris, she is said to have painted with a conviction and maturity rarely seen in a 16-year old.<ref name=\"christies.com\"/>\n\nIn 1931, Sher-Gil was briefly engaged to Yusuf Ali Khan, but rumors spread that she was also having an affair with her first cousin and later husband Victor Egan.<ref name=\"Singh\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ranisingh/2015/05/01/undiscovered-amrita-sher-gil-self-portrait-and-rare-indian-emerald-bangles-for-auction/#3a29fbb9b4bb|title=Undiscovered Amrita Sher-Gil Self-Portrait And Rare Indian Emerald Bangles Up For Auction|last=Singh|first=Rani|work=Forbes|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> Her letters reveal same-sex affairs.<ref>{{cite web|author=(Some names have been changed to protect their identities) |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1131215/jsp/7days/17682751.jsp |title=A life not so gay |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date= |accessdate=23 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== 1932\u20131936: Early career, European and Western styles ===\n[[File:Amrita Sher-Gil - Young Girls.jpg|thumb|240px|right|''Young Girls'', 1932, oil on canvas, 133\u00d7164 cm, [http://ngmaindia.gov.in/sh-amrita.asp National Gallery of Modern Art, Delhi]]]\n\nSher-Gil's early paintings display a significant influence of the [[Western art history|Western]] modes of painting, more specifically, the post-impressionism style. She practiced a lot in the Bohemian circles of Paris in the early 1930s. Her 1932 [[oil painting]], ''Young Girls'', came as a breakthrough for her; the work won her accolades, including a gold medal and election as an Associate of the Grand Salon in Paris in 1933. She was the youngest ever member,<ref>Anand, ''[[Amrita Sher-Gil#Anand|Armita Sher-Gil]]''</ref><ref name=\"tatew2\">[http://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/exhibition/amrita-sher-gil/amrita-sher-gil-room-1-early-years-paris Works in Focus], [[Tate Modern]], 2007.</ref><ref>[http://en.ce.cn/entertainment/theater/200703/08/t20070308_10626933.shtml Amrita Shergil at tate]. En.ce.cn.</ref> and the only Asian to have received this recognition.<ref name=\"AmritaIndia2\"/> Her work during this time include a number of self-portraits, as well as life in Paris, nude studies, still life studied, and portraits of friends and fellow students.<ref name=\"ngmaindia.gov.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ngmaindia.gov.in/sh-amrita.asp|title=National Gallery of Modern Art, New Delhi|website=www.ngmaindia.gov.in|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> The National Gallery of Modern Art in New Delhi describes her self-portraits she made while in Paris as \"[capturing] the artist in her many moods \u2013 somber, pensive, and joyous \u2013 while revealing a narcissistic streak in her personality.\" <ref name=\"ngmaindia.gov.in\"/>\n[[File:Painting Sleep 1932.jpg|thumb|''Sleep,'' 1932, oil on canvas 112.5 x 79 cm, National Gallery of Modern Art, Delhi]]\nWhen she was in Paris, one of her professors often said that judging by the richness of her colouring Sher-Gil was not in her element in the west, and that her artistic personality would find its true atmosphere in east.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Amrita Sher-Gil: Art & Life: A Reader|last=Dalmia|first=Yashodhara|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-0-19-809886-7|location=New Delhi|page=5}}</ref> In 1933, Sher-Gil \"began to be haunted by an intense longing to return to India [...] feeling in some strange way that there lay my destiny as a painter.\" Sher-Gill returned to India at the end of 1934.<ref name=\"tele\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2007/02/24/baamrita124.xml Laid bare \u2013 the free spirit of Indian art] [[The Daily Telegraph]], 24 February 2007.</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> In May 1935, Sher-Gil met the English journalist [[Malcolm Muggeridge]], then working as Assistant Editor and leader writer for [[The Statesman (India)|''The Calcutta Statesman'']].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bright-Holmes|first=John|title=Like It Was: The Diaries of Malcolm Muggeridge|year=1981|publisher=Collins|location=entry dated 18 January 1951|isbn=978-0-688-00784-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/likeitwas00malc/page/426 426]|url=https://archive.org/details/likeitwas00malc/page/426|access-date=29 August 2011|url-status=dead|url-access=registration}}</ref> Both Muggeridge and Sher-Gil stayed at the family home at [[Summer Hill, Shimla]] and a short intense affair took place during which she painted a casual portrait of her new lover, the painting now with the National Gallery of Modern Art in New Delhi. By September 1935 Amrita saw Muggeridge off as he traveled back to England for new employment.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wolfe|first=Gregory|title=Malcolm Muggeridge: A Biography|year=2003|publisher=Intercollegiate Studies Institute|location=page 136-137|isbn=1932236066|page=136}}</ref> She left herself for travel in 1936 at the behest of an art collector and critic, [[Karl Jamshed Khandalavala|Karl Khandalavala]], who encouraged her to pursue her passion for discovering her Indian roots.<ref name=\"AmritaTate\">[http://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/exhibition/amrita-sher-gil/amrita-sher-gil-room-1-early-years-paris Amrita Sher-Gil Exhibition at tate.org]</ref> In India, she began a quest for the rediscovery of the traditions of Indian art which was to continue till her death. She was greatly impressed and influenced by the [[Mughal painting|Mughal]] and [[Pahari painting|Pahari]] schools of painting and the cave paintings at [[Ajanta Caves|Ajanta]].\n\n[[File:Amrita Sher-Gil - South Indian Villagers Going to Market.jpg|thumb|right|240px|''South Indian Villagers Going to Market'', 1937.]]\n\n=== 1937\u20131941: Later career, influence of Indian art ===\nLater in 1937, she toured [[South India]]<ref name=AmritaTate/> and produced her South Indian trilogy of paintings ''Bride's Toilet'', ''Brahmacharis'', and ''South Indian Villagers Going to Market'' following her visit to the [[Ajanta Caves]], when she made a conscious attempt to return to classical Indian art. These paintings reveal her passionate sense of color and an equally passionate empathy for her Indian subjects, who are often depicted in their poverty and despair.<ref name=AmritaIndiaprofile>[http://www.indiaprofile.com/people/amritashergill.htm Amrita Shergill at]. Indiaprofile.com (6 December 1941).</ref> By now the transformation in her work was complete and she had found her 'artistic mission' which was, according to her, to express the life of Indian people through her canvas.<ref name=GreatMinds/> While in Saraya Sher-Gil wrote to a friend thus: \"I can only paint in India. Europe belongs to Picasso, Matisse, Braque.... India belongs only to me\".<ref name=\"frontline2013\">{{cite journal|title=Amrita's village|journal=Frontline|date=February\u2013March 2013|volume=30|issue=4|url=http://www.frontline.in/stories/20130308300409000.htm|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref> Her stay in India marks the beginning of a new phase in her artistic development, one that was distinct from the European phase of the interwar years when her work showed an engagement with the works of [[Hungarian painters]], especially the [[Nagybanya]] school of painting.<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_15-12-2004_pg3_5 Daily Times, 15 December 2004]. Dailytimes.com.pk (15 December 2004).</ref>\n\nSher-Gil married her Hungarian first cousin, Dr. Victor Egan when she was 25.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> Dr. Egan had helped Sher-Gil obtain abortions on at least two occasions prior to their marriage.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/> She moved with him to India to stay at her paternal family's home in Saraya, Sardar nagar, [[Chauri Chaura]] in [[Gorakhpur, Uttar Pradesh|Gorakhpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Thus began her second phase of painting which equals in its impact on Indian art with the likes of [[Rabindranath Tagore]] and [[Jamini Roy]] of the [[Bengal school of art]]. The 'Calcutta Group' of artists, which transformed the Indian art scene, was to start only in 1943, and the '[[Bombay Progressive Artists' Group|Progressive Artist's Group]]', with [[Francis Newton Souza]], Ara, [[Sadanand Bakre|Bakre]], Gade, [[M. F. Husain]] and [[S. H. Raza]] among its founders, lay further ahead in 1948.<ref name=\"AmritaMaps\">[http://www.mapsofindia.com/who-is-who/art-culture/amrita-sher-gill.html Amrita Sher-Gill at]. Mapsofindia.com.</ref><ref>[http://www.contemporaryart-india.com/art%20_movements_in_india.php Contemporary Art Movements in India]. Contemporaryart-india.com.</ref><ref>[http://www.art.in/indian-artists.htm Indian artists]. Art.in.</ref> Amrita's art was strongly influenced by the paintings of the two Tagores, Rabindranath and [[Abanindranath Tagore|Abanindranath]] who were the pioneers of the Bengal School of painting. Her portraits of women resemble works by Rabindranath while the use of '[[chiaroscuro]]' and bright colors reflect the influence of Abanindranath.<ref>{{cite news|title=Art into life|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/nqAAESbsrngHM94BTy0kRI/Art-into-life.html|accessdate=6 February 2013|newspaper=HT Mint|date=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt was during her stay at Saraya that she painted the ''Village Scene'', ''In the Ladies' Enclosure'' and ''Siesta'' all of which portray the leisurely rhythms of life in rural India. ''Siesta'' and ''In the Ladies' Enclosure'' reflect her experimentation with the [[Indian painting|miniature school of painting]] while ''Village Scene'' reflects influences of the [[Pahari painting|Pahari school of painting]].<ref name=\"outlookindia_a\">{{cite news|title=White Shadows|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230586|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=20 March 2006}}</ref> Although acclaimed by art critics Karl Khandalavala in Bombay and Charles Fabri in Lahore as the greatest painter of the century, Amrita's paintings found few buyers. She travelled across India with her paintings but the Nawab [[Salar Jung III|Salar Jung]] of [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]] returned them and the [[Maharaja of Mysore]] chose [[Raja Ravi Varma|Ravi Varma's]] paintings over hers.<ref name=\"outlookindia\">{{cite news|title=Hamari Amrita|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230674|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=27 March 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206165148/http://outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230674|archive-date=6 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlthough from a family that was closely tied to the [[British Raj]], Amrita herself was a [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] sympathiser. She was attracted to the poor, distressed and the deprived and her paintings of Indian villagers and women are a meditative reflection of their condition. She was also attracted by Gandhi's philosophy and lifestyle. [[Jawaharlal Nehru|Nehru]] was charmed by her beauty and talent and when he went to Gorakhpur in October 1940, he visited her at Saraya. Her paintings were at one stage even considered for use in the Congress propaganda for village reconstruction.<ref name=\"frontline2013\"/> However, despite being friends with Nehru, Sher-Gil never drew his portrait, supposedly because the artist thought he was \"too good looking.\"<ref name=\"indiatoday.intoday.in\">{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/education/story/amrita-sher-gil/1/869889.html|title=Why Amrita Sher-Gil refused to draw Nehru's portrait : Art and Culture|website=indiatoday.intoday.in|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> Nehru attended her exhibition held in New Delhi in February 1937.<ref name=\"indiatoday.intoday.in\"/> Sher-Gil exchanged letters with Nehru for a time, but those letters were burned by her parents when she was away getting married in Budapest.<ref name=\"indiatoday.intoday.in\"/>\n\nIn September 1941, Victor and Amrita moved to [[Lahore]], then in [[undivided India]] and a major cultural and artistic centre. She lived and painted at 23 Ganga Ram Mansions, The Mall, Lahore where her studio was on the top floor of the townhouse she inhabited. Amrita was known for her many affairs with both men and women<ref name=tele/> and many of the latter she also painted. Her work ''Two Women'' is thought to be a painting of herself and her lover Marie Louise.<ref>{{cite news|title=Passion And Precedent|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?206737|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=21 December 1998}}</ref> Some of her later works include ''Tahitian'' (1937), ''Red Brick House'' (1938), ''Hill Scene'' (1938), and ''The Bride'' (1940) among others. Her last work was left unfinished by her just prior to her death in December 1941.\n\nIn 1941, at age 28, just days before the opening of her first major solo show in Lahore, she became seriously ill and slipped into a coma.<ref name=\"tele\"/><ref name=\"budapesttimes.hu\">{{cite web|url=http://budapesttimes.hu/2016/01/23/great-success-in-a-short-life/|title=Great success in a short life {{!}} The Budapest Times|website=budapesttimes.hu|language=en-US|access-date=14 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124101915/http://budapesttimes.hu/2016/01/23/great-success-in-a-short-life/|archive-date=24 January 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b072j32f|title=Amrita Sher-Gil: This Is Me, Incarnations: India in 50 Lives \u2013 BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> She later died around midnight on 5 December 1941,<ref>{{cite journal |journal=India International Centre Quarterly |title=Amrita Sher-Gil |first=N Iqbal |last=Singh |volume=2 |issue=3 |date=July 1975 |jstor=23001838 |page=216}}</ref> leaving behind a large volume of work. The reason for her death has never been ascertained. A failed abortion and subsequent [[peritonitis]] have been suggested as possible causes for her death.<ref>Truth, Love and a Little Malice, An Autobiography by [[Khushwant Singh]] Penguin, 2003. {{ISBN|0-14-302957-6}}.</ref> Her mother accused her doctor husband Victor of having murdered her. The day after her death Britain declared war on Hungary and Victor was sent to jail as a national enemy. Amrita was cremated on 7 December 1941 at Lahore.<ref name=\"outlookindia\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Roads in New Delhi 04.jpg|thumb|Road named in Delhi after Shergil]]\nSher-Gil's art has influenced generations of Indian artists from [[S. H. Raza|Sayed Haider Raza]] to [[Arpita Singh]] and her depiction of the plight of women has made her art a beacon for women at large both in India and abroad.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sad In Bright Clothes|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?283591|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Outlook|date=28 January 2013}}</ref> The [[Government of India]] has declared her works as National Art Treasures,<ref name=AmritaMaps/><ref name=\"The Better India\"/>  and most of them are housed in the [[National Gallery of Modern Art]] in [[New Delhi]].<ref>[http://www.culturalindia.net/indian-art/painters/amrita-shergil.html Amrita Sher-Gil at]. Culturalindia.net (30 January 1913).</ref><ref name=\"ngmaindia.gov.in\"/> Some of her paintings also hang at the Lahore Museum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://scroll.in/magazine/827982/when-amrita-sher-gil-vowed-to-seduce-khushwant-singh-to-take-revenge-on-his-wife|title=When Amrita Sher-Gil vowed to seduce Khushwant Singh to take revenge on his wife|last=Dutt|first=Nirupama|work=Scroll.in|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> A postage stamp depicting her painting 'Hill Women' was released in 1978 by [[India Post]], and the Amrita Shergil Marg is a road in [[Lutyens' Delhi]] named after her. Amrita was able to prove to western societies that Indians where able to make fine art.Her work is deemed to be so important to Indian culture that when it is sold in India, the Indian government has stipulated that the art must stay in the country \u2013 fewer than ten of her works have been sold globally.<ref name=\"Singh\"/> In 2006, her painting ''Village Scene'' sold for {{INR}}6.9 crores at an auction in [[New Delhi]] which was at the time the highest amount ever paid for a painting in India.<ref name=\"outlookindia_a\" />\n\nThe Indian cultural center in Budapest is named the Amrita Sher-Gil Cultural Center.<ref name=\"budapesttimes.hu\"/> Contemporary artists in India have recreated and reinterpreted her works.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/two-artists-are-recreating-painter-amrita-sher-gil-s-self-portraits/story-l07Jv15KCyTXABIeUR2DoJ.html|title=Two artists are recreating painter Amrita Sher-Gil's self portraits|date=23 March 2017|work=hindustantimes.com/|access-date=14 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBesides remaining an inspiration to many a contemporary Indian artists, in 1993, she also became the inspiration behind the Urdu play ''[[Tumhari Amrita]]''.<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/mag/2006/08/13/stories/2006081300290200.htm Digital encounters] ''[[The Hindu]]'', 13 August 2006]</ref><ref name=\"The Better India\"/>\n\nUNESCO announced 2013, the 100th anniversary of Sher-Gil's birth, to be the international year of Amrita Sher-Gil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mma.hu/en/web/en/what-s-on/-/event/153538/amrita-sher-gil-in-paris|title=Amrita Sher-Gil in Paris {{!}} Magyar M\u0171v\u00e9szeti Akad\u00e9mia|website=www.mma.hu|language=en-US|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nSher-Gil's work is a key theme in the contemporary Indian novel ''Faking It'' by Amrita Chowdhury.<ref>{{cite book|title=Faking It \u2013 Amrita V Chowdhury|isbn = 9789350094051|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3GyC-0MweoQC|accessdate=5 February 2013|last1 = Chowdhury|first1 = Amrita V.|date = 7 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nAurora Zogoiby, a character in [[Salman Rushdie]]'s 1995 novel ''The Moor's Last Sigh'', was inspired by Sher-Gil.<ref>\"Amrita Sher-Gil: A Self-Portrait in Letters and Writings\", ed. Vivan Sundaram, [[Tulika Books]], 2010</ref>\n\nSher-Gil was sometimes known as India's [[Frida Kahlo]] because of the \"revolutionary\" way she blended Western and traditional art forms.<ref name=\"The Indian Frida Kahlo\"/><ref name=\"AmritaMaps\" />\n\nIn 2018, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published a belated obituary for her.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/20/obituaries/amrita-shergil-dead.html?smid=tw-nytobits&smtyp=cur |title=Overlooked No More: Amrita Sher-Gil, a Pioneer of Indian Art |work=The New York Times |date= |accessdate=23 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, at a Sotheby's auction in Mumbai, Amrita Shergil's painting \"The Little Girl in Blue\" was auctioned for a record-breaking 18.69 crores. This painting is a portrait of Amrita's cousin Babit, a resident of Shimla and was painted in 1934, when the subject was 8 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/ZcJZwPQCaHJOjXdIqjzAdK/Sothebys-Mumbai-auction-Amrita-SherGils-The-Little-Girl.html|title=Sotheby's Mumbai auction: Amrita Sher-Gil's 'The Little Girl in Blue' fetches record bid of \u20b918.69 crore}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"250px\" heights=\"250px\">\nFile:Amrita Sher-Gil Self-portrait.jpg|Self-portrait, 1930\nFile:Amrita Sher-Gil Self-portrait, untitled.jpg|Self-portrait (untitled), 1931\nFile:Amrita Sger-Gil Klarra Szepessy.jpg|Kl\u00e1ra Szepessy, 1932\nFile:Amrita Sher-Gil Hungarian-gypsy-girl.jpg|Hungarian Gypsy Girl, 1932\nFile:Amrita Sher-Gil Group of Three Girls.jpg|Group of Three Girls, 1935\nFile:Amrita Sger-Gil Bride's Toilet.jpg|Bride's Toilet, 1937\nFile:Village-scene-1938.jpg|Village Scene, 1938\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil'', by Karl J. Khandalavala. New Book Co., 1945\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: Essays'', by [[Vivan Sundaram]], Marg Publications; New Delhi, 1972.\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil'', by Baldoon Dhingra. [[Lalit Kala Akademi]], New Delhi, 1981. {{ISBN|0-86186-644-4}}.\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil and Hungary'', by Gyula Wojtilla . Allied Publishers, 1981.\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: A Biography'' by N. Iqbal Singh, ''Vikas Publishing House Pvt.Ltd., India'', 1984. {{ISBN|0-7069-2474-6}}\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: A personal view'', by Ahmad Salim. Istaarah Publications; 1987.\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil'', by [[Mulk Raj Anand]]. [[National Gallery of Modern Art]]; 1989.\n* ''Amrita Shergil: Amrita Shergil ka Jivan aur Rachana samsar'', by [[Kanhaiyalal Nandan]]. 2000.\n* ''Re-take of Amrita'', by [[Vivan Sundaram]]. 2001, Tulika. {{ISBN|81-85229-49-X}}\n* ''Amrita Sher Gil \u2013 A Painted Life'' by Geeta Doctor, ''Rupa'' 2002, {{ISBN|81-7167-688-X}}\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: A Life'' by Yashodhara Dalmia, 2006. {{ISBN|0-670-05873-4}}\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: An Indian Artist Family of the Twentieth Century'', by [[Vivan Sundaram]], 2007, Schirmer/Mosel. {{ISBN|3-8296-0270-7}}\n* ''Amrita Sher-Gil: A Self-Portrait in Letters and Writings'' edited by Vivan Sundaram, Tulika Books, 2010.\n* ''Feminine Fables: Imaging the Indian Woman in Painting, Photography and Cinema'', by Geeti Sen, Mapin Publishing, 2002.\n* ''The Art of Amrita Sher-Gil'', Series of the Roerich Centre of Art and Culture. Allahabad Block Works, 1943.\n* ''Sher-Gil, by Amrita Sher-Gil'', [[Lalit Kala Akademi]], 1965.\n* ''India\u2019s 50 Most Illustrious Women'' by Indra Gupta {{ISBN|81-88086-19-3}}\n* ''Famous Indians of the 20th century'' by Vishwamitra Sharma. Pustak Mahal, 2003, {{ISBN|81-223-0829-5}}\n* ''When was Modernism: Essays on Contemporary Cultural Practice in India,'' by Geeta Kapur, 2000.\n*{{cite journal |last=Rahman |first=Maseeh |authorlink= |authormask= |date=6 October 2014 |title=In the shadow of death |department=The Arts |journal=[[India Today]] |volume=39 |issue=40 |pages=68\u201369}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite AV media |people= Anand, Mulk Raj|year= 1989|title= Amrita Sher-Gill|medium= English|place=Jaipur|publisher= National Gallery of Modern Art|ref=Anand}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Amrita Sher-Gil}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://ngmaindia.gov.in/sh-amrita.asp Showcase:Amrita Sher-Gil] at [[National Gallery of Modern Art]]\n*[https://historyoffineartdk.blogspot.com/2019/11/1913-1941.html \u0905\u092e\u0943\u0924\u093e \u0936\u0947\u0930\u0917\u093f\u0932]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sher-Gil, Amrita}}\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Lahore]]\n[[Category:People from Shimla]]\n[[Category:Jewish women painters]]\n[[Category:Indian Sikhs]]\n[[Category:Indian people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Indian women painters]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Indian portrait painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Hungarian painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian painters]]\n[[Category:Bisexual artists]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from Hungary]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from India]]\n[[Category:Painters from Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Women artists from Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Hungarian women painters]]\n[[Category:Indian Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n", "name_user": "41.182.51.115", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amrita_Sher-Gil"}
{"title_page": "Simon Yates (cyclist)", "text_new": "{{short description|British road and track racing cyclist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Simon Yates\n| image         = 20140907-SimonYates.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Yates in the [[King of the Mountains]] jersey of the [[2014 Tour of Alberta]]\n| fullname      = Simon Philip Yates\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|08|07}}<ref name=\"eurosport\">{{cite web|title=Simon Yates|url=http://au.eurosport.com/cycling/simon-yates_prs330797/person.shtml|publisher=Eurosport Australia|accessdate=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_place   = [[Bury, Greater Manchester]], England\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        = {{height|m=1.72}}<ref name=\"eurosport\"/>\n| weight        = {{convert|59|kg|lb stlb|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"eurosport\"/>\n| currentteam   = {{ct|OBE}}\n| discipline    = Track and road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = Climber<br />All-rounder (road)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/simon-yatess-scott-addict-186349 |title=Simon Yates's Scott Addict |last1=Bridgewood |first1=Oliver |date=6 August 2015 |website=[[Cycling Weekly]]|access-date=9 September 2015}}</ref><br />Endurance (track)\n| amateuryears1 = 2013\n| amateurteam1  = 100% me<ref>https://www.ukad.org.uk/education/athletes/100percentme/</ref>\n| amateuryears2 = \n| amateurteam2  = \n| proyears1     = 2014\u2013\n| proteam1      = {{ct|OBE|2014}}<ref name=\"Orica\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/yates-brothers-confirm-move-to-orica-greenedge|title=Yates Brothers Confirm Move To Mitchelton-Scott|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=3 October 2013|accessdate=3 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/mitchelton-scott-finalise-25-rider-roster-for-2019/|title=Mitchelton-Scott finalise 25-rider roster for 2019|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|date=15 November 2018|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n| proyears2     = \n| proteam2      = \n| majorwins     = '''[[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]]'''\n:'''[[Tour de France]]'''\n::[[Young rider classification in the Tour de France|Young rider classification]] ([[2017 Tour de France|2017]])\n::2 individual stages ([[2019 Tour de France|2019]])\n:'''[[Giro d'Italia]]'''\n::3 individual stages ([[2018 Giro d'Italia|2018]])\n:'''[[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]'''\n::'''[[General classification in the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|General classification]]''' ([[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2018]])\n::[[Combination classification in the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Combination classification]] ([[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2018]])\n::2 individual stages ([[2016 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2016]], [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2018]])\n'''Other'''\n:[[UCI World Tour]] ([[2018 UCI World Tour|2018]])\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[track cycling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{GBR2}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Track Cycling World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships|2013 Minsk]]|[[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships&nbsp;\u2013 Men's points race|Points race]]}}\n| show-medals   = \n}}\n\n'''Simon Philip Yates''' (born 7 August 1992) is a British [[Road bicycle racing|road]] and [[track cycling|track]] racing cyclist, who currently rides for [[UCI WorldTeam]] {{ct|MTS men}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.greenedgecycling.com/news/wins-from-january-to-october-mitchelton-scott-men-confirm-roster-and-goals-for-2020|title=Wins from January to October: Mitchelton-Scott men confirm roster and goals for 2020|work={{ct|MTS men|2020}}|publisher=New Global Cycling Services|date=11 December 2019|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> His twin brother is [[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]], who is also a cyclist for the same team. He won the gold medal in the [[points race]] at the [[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships \u2013 Men's points race|2013 Track Cycling World Championships]]. Following a [[doping in sport|doping ban]] in 2016, he won the [[young rider classification]] in the [[2017 Tour de France]] and the [[general classification]] in the [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]. Yates has also won multiple stages at each of cycling's three [[Grand Tour (cycling)|grand tours]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\n[[File:Simon Yates.jpg|upright|thumbnail|left|Yates in 2012]]\nThe brothers took up cycling after their father John was injured in a collision with a car while riding. During John's recovery he took the twins to [[Manchester Velodrome]] to track sessions run by his cycling club, Bury Clarion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buryclarion.co.uk/|title=Home - Bury Clarion Cycling Club|work=Bury Clarion Cycling Club}}</ref> to keep in touch with the other members. Both brothers soon started riding on the road for Bury Clarion and on the track for Eastlands Velo.\n\nAt the age of 18, Simon was selected by [[British Cycling]] for its Olympic Academy programme. He was also selected for the England team for the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Delhi]], where his room-mate was [[Chris Froome]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/29391092 |title=Simon and Adam Yates: Bury boys on a twin track to the top |last1=Slater |first1=Matt|date=27 September 2014 |website=[[bbc.co.uk]] |accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe won the gold medal in the [[points race]] at the [[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships|2013 Track World Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bevan|first=Chris|title=Jason Kenny and Simon Yates win World cycling golds for Britain|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/21546329|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=22 February 2013|location=Minsk, Belarus|date=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nSimon made his breakthrough on the road in 2013 riding for the British national team. Along with brother Adam, he competed at the 2013 [[Tour de l'Avenir]] for the Great Britain national team, where Simon won the race's fifth stage, ahead of Adam.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/cycling/news/15264/8895597/simon-yates-and-brother-adam-finish-first-and-second-on-stage-five-of-tour-de-lavenir|title=Simon Yates and brother Adam finish first and second on stage five of Tour de l'Avenir|work=[[Sky Sports]]|publisher=[[BSkyB]]|date=29 August 2013|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> Simon added another stage victory the following day,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/cycling/news/15264/8897673/|title=Simon Yates claims second successive Tour de l'Avenir win with victory on stage six|work=[[Sky Sports]]|publisher=[[BSkyB]]|date=30 August 2013|accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref> and finished the race tenth overall.\n\nHe was then selected as part of the British national team to take part in the [[2013 Tour of Britain|Tour of Britain]]. He competed well throughout the race and on stage six he took his biggest win to that point, on the summit finish at [[Haytor]], sprinting clear of a nine-man group, which included [[Bradley Wiggins]] and [[Nairo Quintana]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour of Britain \u2013 Yates wins stage six, Wiggins maintains overall lead|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/tour-britain-yates-wins-stage-six-wiggins-maintains-134817871--spt.html|publisher=Yahoo Eurosport|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tour of Britain: Simon Yates wins stage six, Bradley Wiggins leads|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/24178704|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref>\nYates finished third overall in the Tour of Britain, and was the best rider in the under-23 classification.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour of Britain 2013, stage eight: Sir Bradley Wiggins triumphs after Mark Cavendish sprints to London victory|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/cycling/10326934/Tour-of-Britain-2013-stage-eight-Sir-Bradley-Wiggins-triumphs-after-Mark-Cavendish-sprints-to-London-victory.html|publisher=Telegraph Online|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Orica\u2013GreenEDGE/Mitchelton SCOTT (2014\u2013present)===\n====2014====\n[[File:Simon Yates-Croix des Moinats (cropped).JPG|upright|thumb|left|Yates at the [[2014 Tour de France]]]]\nYates along with his brother joined the Australian [[UCI World Tour]] team {{ct|OBE|2014}} in 2014.<ref name=\"Orica\"/> He finished 12th Overall in one of his first World Tour races, the [[2014 Tour of the Basque Country|Tour of the Basque Country]]. Yates suffered a broken collarbone on Stage 3 of the [[2014 Tour of Turkey|Tour of Turkey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-crashes-out-of-the-tour-of-turkey|title=Simon Yates crashes out of the Tour of Turkey|author=Cycling News|work=Cyclingnews.com}}</ref> He recovered to take seventh overall and the Young Riders Classification in the [[2014 Tour of Slovenia|Tour of Slovenia]] in June. He was a surprise selection for the {{ct|OBE|2014|nolink=yes}} team for the [[2014 Tour de France]], with only 5 days' notice, and was one of only 4 British riders to take to the Grand Depart startline in [[Leeds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/28111981|title=BBC Sport - Tour de France: Britain's Simon Yates handed unexpected berth|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> Yates featured in two breakaways during his Grand Tour debut, before being withdrawn by his team on the second rest day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/racing/tour-de-france/simon-yates-withdraws-tour-de-france-130712|title=Simon Yates withdraws from Tour de France|date=21 July 2014|work=Cycling Weekly}}</ref>\n\n====2015====\nIn April 2015 Yates finished fifth overall in the [[2015 Tour of the Basque Country|Tour of the Basque Country]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.bt.com/more-sport-hub/more-sport/yates-clinches-fifth-placed-finish-S11363975112013|title=Yates clinches fifth-placed finish|work=BT.com}}</ref> Later that month he rode the [[2015 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandie]] and placed sixth overall. In June 2015 Yates finished fifth overall in the [[2015 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9]] after finishing second behind [[Chris Froome]] on the final stage, a summit finish at [[Modane]]. By doing so Yates also won the White Jersey as best young rider.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/33127651|title=Criterium du Dauphine: Chris Froome wins second title|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHe was again selected for the [[2015 Tour de France]], this time alongside his brother Adam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/jun/27/tour-de-france-2015-yates-twins-orica|title=Tour de France 2015: Yates twins ready for coming of age with Orica|first=William|last=Fotheringham|date=27 June 2015|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref> Simon placed eighth on Stage 3, which finished on the [[Mur de Huy]], and eleventh on Stage 20, the queen stage of the race finishing on [[Alpe d'Huez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.velon.cc/teamnews/yates-brothers-show-strength-on-alpe-dhuez/|title=Velon - Team Hub|website=www.velon.cc}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n[[File:Simon Yates Madone d'Utelle 2016.JPG|upright|thumb|Yates at the [[2016 Paris-Nice]]]]\nIn March 2016, Yates finished seventh overall at [[2016 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]], however, in April it emerged that Yates had tested positive for the banned substance [[terbutaline]] in an in-competition test during the race.<ref name=\"doping2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/36166128|title=Simon Yates: British cyclist fails drug test 'due to asthma inhaler'|date=29 April 2016|website=[[bbc.co.uk]]|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref> Yates was disqualified from the race and served a four-month doping ban during 2016; his team took full responsibility for this blaming an \"administrative error\". The ban meant Yates missed the [[2016 Tour de France]], where his brother Adam finished fourth overall and won the [[Young rider classification in the Tour de France|Young rider classification]].\n\nFollowing the expiry of his doping suspension, he was named in the startlist for the [[2016 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]].<ref name=\"Vuelta2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Vuelta_a_Espana_2016_Startlist|title=71st Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|work=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref> In stage 6 Yates, seeing an opportunity, escaped from a breakaway group to win a solo stage victory - the first of the Yates brothers to take a Grand Tour stage victory.\n\n====2017====\n[[File:Meilleur Jeune \u00e0 l'arriv\u00e9e du Tour de France 2017 \u00e0 Chamb\u00e9ry.JPG|left|thumb|Yates wearing the White Jersey at the [[2017 Tour de France]]]]\n2017 saw Yates collect stage wins at two prestigious stage races, [[2017 Paris-Nice|Paris-Nice]] and the [[2017 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandie]]. He placed second at the latter, his highest finish in a [[UCI World Tour]] stage-race at the time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour de Romandie: Britain's Simon Yates second as Richie Porte wins on final stage|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/39763157|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> He finished 7th overall at the [[2017 Tour de France|Tour de France]] and won the young rider classification, matching the feat achieved by his twin brother a year prior.\n\n====2018: Grand Tour success====\nYates confirmed his and the team's plans for him participating in the [[2018 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]] and the [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/tour-de-france/adam-yates-will-lead-mitchelton-scott-team-tour-de-france-simon-yates-giro-vuelta-363464|title=Adam Yates will lead Mitchelton-Scott team at 2018 Tour de France; Simon Yates to Giro and Vuelta - Cycling Weekly|date=2017-12-15|work=Cycling Weekly|access-date=2018-03-02|language=en-US}}</ref> In March, Yates won Stage 7 of the [[2018 Paris\u2013Nice]], a mountain top finish to [[Valdeblore|Valdeblore La Colmiane]], to take the overall race lead going into the final stage. However, on Stage 8 [[Marc Soler]] of the {{ct|MOV|2018}}, who started the final stage 37 seconds down on Yates in sixth place overall, attacked around halfway into the stage along with compatriot [[David de la Cruz]] ({{ct|SKY|2018}}); the duo joined [[Omar Fraile]] ({{ct|AST|2018}}) at the head of the race, and the trio managed to stay clear of the rest of the field by the time they reached [[Nice]]. As de la Cruz and Fraile contested stage honours, Soler finished third \u2013 acquiring four bonus seconds on the finish in addition to three gained at an earlier intermediate sprint \u2013 and with a 35-second gap to Yates and the remaining general classification contenders, it was enough to give Soler victory over Yates by four seconds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/marc-soler-grabs-paris-nice-title-four-seconds-simon-yates-final-stage-372464|title=Marc Soler grabs Paris-Nice title by four seconds from Simon Yates on final stage|first=Richard|last=Windsor|work=[[Cycling Weekly]]|publisher=[[TI Media]]|date=11 March 2018|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> Later that month, Yates won stage 7 of the [[2017 Volta a Catalunya|Volta a Catalunya]] after attacking multiple times on the {{convert|6.6|km|abbr=off|adj=on}} laps of the hilly final circuit through the [[Montju\u00efc]] Park. By doing so he finished fourth overall in the race.<ref>http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/volta-ciclista-a-catalunya-2018/stage-7/results/</ref>\n\n[[File:GIR40263 simon yates.jpg|thumb|Yates wearing the [[Maglia rosa]] at the [[2018 Giro d'Italia]]]]\nYates entered the Giro d'Italia as joint leader of {{ct|MTS men|2018}} with [[Esteban Chaves]], supported by a strong climbing focused team including [[Roman Kreuziger]], [[Mikel Nieve]] and [[Jack Haig (cyclist)|Jack Haig]].<ref>https://www.eurosport.com/cycling/giro-d-italia/2018/yates-ready-to-lead-team-at-debut-giro-d-italia_sto6730182/story.shtml</ref> Yates placed seventh in the opening {{convert|9.7|km|abbr=off|adj=on}} individual time trial in [[Jerusalem]], 20 seconds down on the defending champion and world time trial champion [[Tom Dumoulin]] ({{ct|SUN|2018}}).<ref>http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/giro-ditalia/tom-dumoulin-stamps-authority-giro-ditalia-stage-one-time-trial-victory-378738</ref> On Stage 6 to [[Mount Etna]], Yates took the race lead after finishing second behind teammate Chaves. Yates attacked from the group of favourites {{convert|1.5|km|abbr=off}} from the summit and caught Chaves, who had been part of the day's breakaway, in sight of the line, but waved Chaves through to claim the stage honours.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} The result meant Yates held the [[Maglia rosa]] over Dumoulin in second, and over Chaves in third place. Yates won stage 9 after accelerating away with {{convert|100|m|abbr=off}} to go on the summit finish to [[Gran Sasso d'Italia]], extending his lead over Chaves, and Dumoulin.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/44101703</ref> Yates extended his lead further on Stage 10, but teammate Chaves dropped out of contention after finishing 25 minutes down after being dropped on the first climb.<ref>http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-im-very-disappointed-for-esteban/</ref> Yates claimed his second stage victory on Stage 11, attacking with {{convert|1.5|km|abbr=off}} to go and holding off the pursuit of Dumoulin to win on hill top finish in [[Osimo]]. Yates increased his lead over Dumoulin.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/44145175</ref>\n\nOn Stage 14, Yates finished second behind [[Chris Froome]] ({{ct|SKY|2018}}) on [[Monte Zoncolan]]. With six bonus seconds for finishing second, Yates extended his overall advantage over Dumoulin, whilst his gap over Froome was 3 minutes 10 seconds.<ref>http://www.skysports.com/cycling/news/15264/11378651/chris-froome-wins-giro-ditalia-stage-14-as-simon-yates-extends-overall-lead</ref> Yates pedaled to a solo win on stage 15 to [[Sappada]], attacking with {{convert|18|km|abbr=off}} remaining, increasing his lead over Dumoulin.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/44190618</ref> On Stage 17, a {{convert|34.2|km|abbr=off|adj=on}} individual time trial from [[Trento]] to [[Rovereto]], Yates held on to his overall lead over Dumoulin.<ref>http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/giro-ditalia/simon-yates-holds-onto-pink-rohan-dennis-wins-giro-ditalia-stage-16-time-trial-380857#4wKbq8I7I1Ph4pTm.99</ref> On stage 18 to [[Prato Nevoso]] Yates cracked on the final slopes of the summit finish and lost 28 seconds to all of his other general classification rivals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/giro-d-italia/2018/stage-18-gc|title=Giro d'Italia 2018 - Stage 18|website=www.procyclingstats.com}}</ref> Stage 19 of the race had been classified as the '[[queen stage]]' of the race, with three focussed climbs in the latter half of the stage. These included the half paved-half gravel climb of the [[Colle delle Finestre]], followed by the climb to [[Sestriere]] and the final uphill finish too [[Bardonecchia]]. Yates cracked on the lower slopes of the Finestre, before Froome launched a solo attack with {{convert|80|km|abbr=off}} left of the stage. Froome's advantage grew throughout the second half of the stage, culminating in him taking a stage victory of more than three minutes and thereby also taking the overall race lead, 40 seconds ahead of Dumoulin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/giro-d-italia/2018/stage-19|title=Giro d'Italia 2018 - Stage 19|website=www.procyclingstats.com}}</ref> Yates lost over 38 minutes to Froome and dropped to 17th overall.<ref>http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-i-was-just-really-tired-and-exhausted/</ref> He eventually finished the race 21st overall, 1 hour and 15 minutes behind the winner Froome.<ref>https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/giro-d-italia/2018/gc</ref>\n[[File:Carmena entrega los premios a dos de los triunfadores de La Vuelta 02.jpg|left|thumb|Yates (centre) on the podium at the [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]].]]\nAfter the Giro, Yates made his return to racing at the [[Prueba Villafranca de Ordizia]], where he finished second behind team-mate [[Robert Power (Australian cyclist)|Robert Power]]. He subsequently returned to WorldTour competition at the [[2018 Tour de Pologne|Tour de Pologne]] in August, where he won the race's closing stage with a solo attack and finished second overall behind [[Micha\u0142 Kwiatkowski]].<ref name=af>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-on-track-for-vuelta-a-espana-in-final-countdown/ |title=Simon Yates on track for Vuelta a Espana in final countdown |last=Fotheringham |first=Alasdair |author-link=Alasdair Fotheringham |date=23 August 2018|website=[[cyclingnews.com]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nYates was {{ct|MTS men|2018|nolink=yes}}'s team leader for the [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]], with support from his brother.<ref name=af /> Yates moved into third place on the general classification after stage 4, the first mountain stage, ten seconds behind leader Kwiatkowski. On the ninth stage, Yates took the leader's red jersey from [[Rudy Molard]] going into the first rest day.<ref name=ee>{{cite web |url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/how-simon-yates-set-his-winning-course-at-la-vuelta-2/ |title=How Simon Yates set his winning course at La Vuelta|date=16 September 2018 |website=[[eveningexpress.co.uk]] |access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> However he lost the lead on stage 12, when {{ct|MTS men|2018|nolink=yes}} elected not to close down a large breakaway, with the red jersey being taken by [[Jes\u00fas Herrada]] with Yates in second and Valverde in third.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/45437610 |title=Vuelta a Espana: Jesus Herrada takes leader's jersey from Simon Yates|date=6 September 2018 |website=[[bbc.co.uk]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> However the following day Yates cut nearly two minutes from Herrada's lead,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/sep/07/oscar-rodriguez-snatches-vuelta-victory-jesus-herrada-lead-cut-simon-yates-cycling |title=Oscar Rodriguez snatches Vuelta win while Simon Yates mounts attack|date=7 September 2018 |website= [[theguardian.com]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> and he then took victory on the fourteenth stage, reclaiming the overall lead. He extended his lead during stage 16 (an individual time trial) and stage 19.<ref name=ee /> On the last mountain stage the following day, Yates attacked his rivals on the penultimate climb, joining [[Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez (cyclist)|Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez]] and [[Nairo Quintana]] alongside [[Enric Mas]] at the head of the race, and eventually finishing third on the stage behind Mas and L\u00f3pez, who moved up into second and third overall after Valverde and [[Steven Kruijswijk]] lost significant time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/vuelta-a-espana/simon-yates-sets-vuelta-espana-2018-overall-victory-enric-mas-wins-gruelling-stage-20-394472 |title=Simon Yates sets up Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a 2018 overall victory as Enric Mas wins gruelling stage 20 |last=Windsor |first=Richard |date=15 September 2018 |website=[[Cycling Weekly]] |access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> He went on to safely cross the finish line on the last stage in Madrid to secure his overall victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/45540766 |title=Simon Yates: British cyclist wins first Grand Tour at Vuelta a Espana|date=16 September 2018 |website=[[bbc.co.uk]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2019====\nSimon previously considered time-trialling to be a weakness,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/tour-de-france/simon-yates-admits-time-trialling-may-always-weakness-heads-tour-de-france-337454|title=Simon Yates admits his time trialling may always be a weakness as he heads to the Tour de France|last=Pitt|first=Vern|date=2017-06-27|website=Cycling Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> and his slowly improved since his junior years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/simon-yates-my-advantage-could-be-wiped-out-in-time-trial-mb2cp8v2m|title=Simon Yates: my advantage could be wiped out in time-trial|last=Burrows|first=Josh|date=2018-05-22|work=The Times|access-date=2019-07-30|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> He had improved in 2019, with his first win in the discipline, in a hilly course at [[2019 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris-Nice]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/simon-yates-wasnt-expecting-time-trial-win-410630|title=Simon Yates: 'I wasn't expecting time trial win'|last=Cossins|first=Peter|date=2019-03-14|website=Cycling Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref> This course may have suited him and other climbers, rather than TT specialists, due to the lumpy profile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/simon-yates-takes-first-ever-time-trial-victory-paris-nice-2019-stage-five-410559|title=Simon Yates takes first career time trial victory on Paris-Nice 2019 stage five|last=Ballinger|first=Alex|date=2019-03-14|website=Cycling Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\nYates returned to the [[2019 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]] aiming for the general classification. He entered the race, publicly stating that he considered himself as \"the number one favourite\" for the [[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|general classification]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-im-the-number-one-favourite-for-the-giro-ditalia/|website=www.cyclingnews.com|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> He started, showing superb{{according to whom|date=August 2019}} form on the opening stage, an individual time-trial in [[Bologna]], where he finished second behind [[Primo\u017e Rogli\u010d]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/48241353|title=Giro d'Italia: Simon Yates makes strong start behind winner Primoz Roglic in opening time trial|date=2019-05-11|access-date=2019-07-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> Yates's hopes of the overall win looked all but over after a disastrous{{according to whom|date=August 2019}} stage 9 time-trial that saw him lose over 3 minutes, dropping to 24th overall. He lost further time on stage 13 up to [[Serr\u00f9 Lake|Lago Seru]]. Despite a second-place finish on stage 19, he finished 8th on GC, and described it as heartbreaking.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-vows-to-come-back-to-try-again-after-heartbreaking-giro-ditalia/|website=www.cyclingnews.com|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n\nHe rode Le Tour de France, in support of his brother's GC ambition, but Simon was allowed a day off [[domestique]] duty{{failed verification|date=July 2019}}, and won stage 12 into [[Bagn\u00e8res-de-Bigorre|Bagnerres-de-Bigorre]] in a 3 up sprint against [[Pello Bilbao|Bilbao]] and [[Gregor M\u00fchlberger|Muhlberger]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/tour-de-france/simon-yates-wasnt-confident-winning-final-sprint-tour-de-france-stage-12-431759|title=Simon Yates 'wasn't confident' of winning final sprint of Tour de France stage 12|last=Brown|first=Gregor|date=2019-07-18|website=Cycling Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref> Unfortunately for Adam, his GC hopes faded after losing time on the individual time-trial and the climb to [[Col du Tourmalet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/tour-de-france-dream-over-for-adam-yates-after-tourmalet-stage/|website=www.cyclingnews.com|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref> These GC losses freed up Simon as the team refocused on stage wins,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenedgecycling.com/news/adam-yates-drops-out-of-contention-after-tough-stage-14|title=Mitchelton-SCOTT to change focus after dropping out of GC contention of stage 14 of the TdF|website=Mitchelton-SCOTT GreenEDGE Cycling|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> and he added another mountain stage win after a ferocious{{according to whom|date=July 2019}} solo attack on stage 15,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/49064307|title=Tour de France 2019: Simon Yates wins stage 15 as Geraint Thomas gains time|date=2019-07-21|access-date=2019-07-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> taking [[Mitchelton\u2013Scott (men's team)|Mitchelton-Scott]]'s tally to 3 before the second rest day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenedgecycling.com/news/a-second-stage-victory-for-simon-yates-to-make-it-a-hat-trick-of-wins-for-mitchelton-scott-at-the-tour-de-france|title=A second stage victory for Simon Yates makes it a hat-trick of wins for MTS at the Tour de France {{!}} Mitchelton-SCOTT GreenEDGE Cycling|website=www.greenedgecycling.com|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n\n==Doping ban==\nIn April 2016 it emerged that Yates had tested positive for the banned substance [[terbutaline]] in an in-competition test during [[2016 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]] the previous month,<ref name=\"doping2\"/> where he finished seventh overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cycling/2016/03/13/geraint-thomas-wins-paris-nice-to-claim-biggest-title-of-career/|title=Geraint Thomas wins Paris-Nice to claim biggest title of career|last1=Cary|first1=Tom|date=13 March 2016|website=[[telegraph.co.uk]]|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref> {{ct|ORS|2016a}}'s owner [[Gerry Ryan (businessman)|Gerry Ryan]] accused [[British Cycling]] of leaking the news of Yates' failed drug test to the press, and criticised the organisation for doing so.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/apr/29/orica-greenedge-british-cycling-leak-simon-yates</ref> In a statement, {{ct|ORS|2016a|nolink=yes}} claimed full responsibility for the test result, saying that the team's doctor had failed to apply for a therapeutic use exemption for an asthma inhaler used by Yates which triggered the positive test.<ref name=\"doping2\" /> Subsequently, the international governing body [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] issued a statement indicating that Yates would not be provisionally suspended from competition due to the substance he had tested positive for.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/36169275|title=Simon Yates: UCI not suspending cyclist despite failed drugs test|website=[[bbc.co.uk]]|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June, the UCI decided to issue a four-month ban for the \"presence and use of the specified prohibited substance terbutaline\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uci.ch/pressreleases/uci-statement-simon-yates/|title=UCI statement on Simon Yates|website=www.uci.ch|access-date=2018-05-25}}</ref> backdated from 12 March (the date the positive sample was collected), preventing Yates from competing at the [[2016 Tour de France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-handed-four-month-non-intentional-doping-ban/|title=Simon Yates handed four-month 'non-intentional' doping ban|date=17 June 2016|work=Cycling News|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career achievements==\n===Major results===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;2010\n: [[UCI Juniors Track World Championships|UCI Junior Track World Championships]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey rainbow.svg|20px]] Madison (with [[Daniel McLay|Dan McLay]])\n::2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] Team pursuit\n: [[British National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n::2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] Points race\n::2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] Scratch race\n: 1st [[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] [[British National Madison Championships|Madison]] (with [[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]]), [[British National Track Championships|National Junior Track Championships]]\n;2011\n: 1st Stage 6 [[Tour de l'Avenir]]\n: 1st [[Six Days of Ghent]] Future Stars (with [[Owain Doull]])\n: 1st Pro-Am Classic\n: 2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] Omnium, [[British National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n: 3rd [[File:Bronze medal blank.svg|15px]] [[2010\u201311 UCI Track Cycling World Cup Classics|Team pursuit]] \u2013 Beijing, [[UCI Track Cycling World Cup Classics|UCI Track World Cup]]\n: 9th Overall [[Th\u00fcringen Rundfahrt der U23]]\n;2012\n: [[British National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n::1st [[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] [[British National Madison Championships|Madison]] (with [[Mark Christian]])\n::1st [[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] [[British National Team Pursuit Championships|Team pursuit]]\n;2013\n: 1st [[File:Jersey rainbow.svg|20px]] [[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships \u2013 Men's points race|Points race]], [[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships|UCI Track World Championships]]\n: 1st [[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] [[British National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Under\u201323 Road Championships\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall Arden Challenge\n::1st Stage 4\n: 3rd Overall [[2013 Tour of Britain|Tour of Britain]]\n::1st Stage 6\n: 3rd [[La C\u00f4te Picarde]]\n: 9th Overall [[R\u00e1s Tailteann|An Post R\u00e1s]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Young rider classification\n: 10th Overall [[Tour de l'Avenir]]\n::1st Stages 5 & 6\n: 10th Overall [[Fl\u00e8che du Sud]]\n: 10th Overall [[Th\u00fcringen Rundfahrt der U23]]\n: 10th Overall [[Czech Cycling Tour]]\n;2014\n: 1st [[File:Jersey polkadot.svg|20px]] Mountains classification [[2014 Tour of Alberta|Tour of Alberta]]\n: 3rd [[British National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Road Championships\n: 7th Overall [[2014 Tour of Slovenia|Tour of Slovenia]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Young rider classification\n;2015\n: 5th Overall [[2015 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Young rider classification\n: 5th Overall [[2015 Tour of the Basque Country|Tour of the Basque Country]]\n: 6th Overall [[2015 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandie]]\n;2016\n: 1st [[2016 Prueba Villafranca de Ordizia|Prueba Villafranca de Ordizia]]\n: 2nd [[Circuito de Getxo]]\n: 4th Overall [[2016 Vuelta a Burgos|Vuelta a Burgos]]\n: 6th Overall [[2016 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n::1st Stage 6\n: 7th [[2016 Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n|Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n]]\n;2017\n: 1st [[2017 GP Miguel Indurain|GP Miguel Indurain]]\n: 2nd Overall [[2017 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandie]]\n::1st Stage 4\n: 7th Overall [[2017 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] [[Young rider classification in the Tour de France|Young rider classification]]\n: 9th Overall [[2017 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]]\n::1st Stage 6\n;2018\n: 1st [[2018 UCI World Tour|UCI World Tour]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey red.svg|20px]] [[General classification in the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Overall]] [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] [[Combination classification in the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Combination classification]]\n::1st Stage 14\n: [[2018 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n::1st Stages 9, 11 & 15\n::Held [[File:Jersey pink.svg|20px]] after Stages 6\u201318\n::Held [[File:Jersey blue.svg|20px]] after Stages 9\u201318\n: 2nd Overall [[2018 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]]\n::1st Stage 7\n: 2nd Overall [[2018 Tour de Pologne|Tour de Pologne]]\n::1st Stage 7\n: 2nd [[Prueba Villafranca de Ordizia]]\n: 4th Overall [[2018 Volta a Catalunya|Volta a Catalunya]]\n::1st Stage 7\n;2019\n: [[2019 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st Stages 12 & 15\n: [[2019 Vuelta a Andaluc\u00eda|Vuelta a Andaluc\u00eda]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey orange.svg|20px]] Mountains classification\n::1st Stage 4\n: 1st Stage 5 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) [[2019 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]]\n: 8th Overall [[2019 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n;2020\n: 7th Overall [[2020 Tour Down Under|Tour Down Under]]\n: 10th [[2020 Cadel Evans Great Ocean Road Race|Cadel Evans Great Ocean Road Race]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===General classification results timeline===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|colspan=7 align=\"center\"|'''Grand Tour general classification results'''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Grand Tour\n! scope=\"col\" | 2014\n! scope=\"col\" | 2015\n! scope=\"col\" | 2016\n! scope=\"col\" | 2017\n! scope=\"col\" | 2018\n! scope=\"col\" | 2019\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|pink}} [[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| [[2018 Giro d'Italia|21]]\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2019 Giro d'Italia|8]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|yellow}} [[General classification in the Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n| [[2014 Tour de France|DNF]]\n| [[2015 Tour de France|89]]\n| \u2014\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2017 Tour de France|7]]\n| \u2014\n| [[2019 Tour de France|49]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|red}} [[List of Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a general classification winners|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2016 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|6]]\n| [[2017 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|44]]\n| style=\"background:red\"   |{{font colour|white|'''1'''|link=2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a}}\n| \u2014\n|-\n|colspan=7 align=\"center\"|'''Major stage race general classification results'''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Race\n! scope=\"col\" | 2014\n! scope=\"col\" | 2015\n! scope=\"col\" | 2016\n! scope=\"col\" | 2017\n! scope=\"col\" | 2018\n! scope=\"col\" | 2019\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|yellow}} [[Paris\u2013Nice]]\n| [[2014 Paris\u2013Nice|44]]\n| [[2015 Paris\u2013Nice|29]]\n| [[2016 Paris\u2013Nice|DSQ]]\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2017 Paris\u2013Nice|9]]\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2018 Paris\u2013Nice|'''2''']]\n| [[2019 Paris\u2013Nice|25]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|blue}} [[Tirreno\u2013Adriatico]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|Volta a Catalunya}} [[Volta a Catalunya]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2018 Volta a Catalunya|4]]\n| [[2019 Volta a Catalunya|13]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|yellow}} [[Tour of the Basque Country]]\n| [[2014 Tour of the Basque Country|11]]\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2015 Tour of the Basque Country|5]]\n| [[2016 Tour of the Basque Country|DNF]]\n| [[2017 Tour of the Basque Country|22]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|yellow}} [[Tour de Romandie]]\n| \u2014\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2015 Tour de Romandie|6]]\n| \u2014\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2017 Tour de Romandie|'''2''']]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|Dauphine}} [[Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9]]\n| \u2014\n| style=\"background:#ddf;\" |[[2015 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|5]]\n| \u2014\n| [[2017 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|13]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{cjersey|yellow}} [[Tour de Suisse]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n===Classics results timeline===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Monument\n! scope=\"col\" | 2014\n! scope=\"col\" | 2015\n! scope=\"col\" | 2016\n! scope=\"col\" | 2017\n! scope=\"col\" | 2018\n! scope=\"col\" | 2019\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[Milan\u2013San Remo]]\n| \u2014\n| [[2015 Milan\u2013San Remo|37]]\n| [[2016 Milan\u2013San Remo|95]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[Tour of Flanders]]\n|colspan=7 rowspan=2 {{n/a|Has not yet contested during career}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[Paris\u2013Roubaix]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]]\n| \u2014\n| [[2015 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|39]]\n| \u2014\n| [[2017 Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge|153]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[Giro di Lombardia]]\n| [[2014 Giro di Lombardia|DNF]]\n| [[2015 Giro di Lombardia|18]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n! Classic\n! scope=\"col\" | 2014\n! scope=\"col\" | 2015\n! scope=\"col\" | 2016\n! scope=\"col\" | 2017\n! scope=\"col\" | 2018\n! scope=\"col\" | 2019\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[Amstel Gold Race]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]]\n| [[2014 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne|78]]\n| [[2015 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne|62]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n]]\n| [[2014 Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n|DNF]]\n| [[2015 Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n|14]]\n| style=\"background:#ddddff;\"|[[2016 Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n|7]]\n| [[2017 Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n|18]]\n| \u2014\n| [[2019 Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n|DNF]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[Grand Prix Cycliste de Qu\u00e9bec]]\n| [[2014 Grand Prix Cycliste de Qu\u00e9bec|22]]\n| [[2015 Grand Prix Cycliste de Qu\u00e9bec|82]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#efefef;\"|[[Grand Prix Cycliste de Montr\u00e9al]]\n| [[2014 Grand Prix Cycliste de Montr\u00e9al|36]]\n| [[2015 Grand Prix Cycliste de Montr\u00e9al|16]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Legend\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \u2014\n| Did not compete\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Did Not Finish|DNF]]\n| Did not finish\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | DSQ\n| Disqualified\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Sports}}\n* [[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]]\n* [[List of doping cases in cycling]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Simon Yates}}\n* {{Cycling archives|65130|Simon Yates}}\n\n{{Mitchelton\u2013Scott (men's team) riders}}\n{{UCI Track Cycling World Champions \u2013 Men's points race}}\n{{Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a winners}}\n{{Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a combination classification winners}}\n{{Tour de France young rider classification winners}}\n{{UCI World Tour Winners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yates, Simon}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bury, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:English male cyclists]]\n[[Category:UCI Track Cycling World Champions (men)]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 2010 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Twin sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Twin people from England]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in cycling]]\n[[Category:English sportspeople in doping cases]]\n[[Category:Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a cyclists]]\n[[Category:British Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:British Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a stage winners]]\n[[Category:British Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:English track cyclists]]\n[[Category:Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a winners]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British road and track racing cyclist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Simon Yates\n| image         = 20140907-SimonYates.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Yates in the [[King of the Mountains]] jersey of the [[2014 Tour of Alberta]]\n| fullname      = Simon Philip Yates\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|08|07}}<ref name=\"eurosport\">{{cite web|title=Simon Yates|url=http://au.eurosport.com/cycling/simon-yates_prs330797/person.shtml|publisher=Eurosport Australia|accessdate=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_place   = [[Bury, Greater Manchester]], England\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        = {{height|m=1.72}}<ref name=\"eurosport\"/>\n| weight        = {{convert|59|kg|lb stlb|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"eurosport\"/>\n| currentteam   = {{ct|OBE}}\n| discipline    = Track and road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = Climber<br />All-rounder (road)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/simon-yatess-scott-addict-186349 |title=Simon Yates's Scott Addict |last1=Bridgewood |first1=Oliver |date=6 August 2015 |website=[[Cycling Weekly]]|access-date=9 September 2015}}</ref><br />Endurance (track)\n| amateuryears1 = 2013\n| amateurteam1  = 100% me<ref>https://www.ukad.org.uk/education/athletes/100percentme/</ref>\n| amateuryears2 = \n| amateurteam2  = \n| proyears1     = 2014\u2013\n| proteam1      = {{ct|OBE|2014}}<ref name=\"Orica\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/yates-brothers-confirm-move-to-orica-greenedge|title=Yates Brothers Confirm Move To Mitchelton-Scott|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=3 October 2013|accessdate=3 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/mitchelton-scott-finalise-25-rider-roster-for-2019/|title=Mitchelton-Scott finalise 25-rider roster for 2019|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|date=15 November 2018|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n| proyears2     = \n| proteam2      = \n| majorwins     = '''[[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]]'''\n:'''[[Tour de France]]'''\n::[[Young rider classification in the Tour de France|Young rider classification]] ([[2017 Tour de France|2017]])\n::2 individual stages ([[2019 Tour de France|2019]])\n:'''[[Giro d'Italia]]'''\n::3 individual stages ([[2018 Giro d'Italia|2018]])\n:'''[[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]'''\n::'''[[General classification in the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|General classification]]''' ([[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2018]])\n::[[Combination classification in the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Combination classification]] ([[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2018]])\n::2 individual stages ([[2016 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2016]], [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2018]])\n'''Other'''\n:[[UCI World Tour]] ([[2018 UCI World Tour|2018]])\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[track cycling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{GBR2}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Track Cycling World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships|2013 Minsk]]|[[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships&nbsp;\u2013 Men's points race|Points race]]}}\n| show-medals   = \n}}\n\n'''Simon Philip Yates''' (born 7 August 1992) is a British [[Road bicycle racing|road]] and [[track cycling|track]] racing cyclist, who currently rides for [[UCI WorldTeam]] {{ct|MTS men}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.greenedgecycling.com/news/wins-from-january-to-october-mitchelton-scott-men-confirm-roster-and-goals-for-2020|title=Wins from January to October: Mitchelton-Scott men confirm roster and goals for 2020|work={{ct|MTS men|2020}}|publisher=New Global Cycling Services|date=11 December 2019|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> His twin brother is [[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]], who is also a cyclist for the same team. He won the gold medal in the [[points race]] at the [[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships \u2013 Men's points race|2013 Track Cycling World Championships]]. Following a [[doping in sport|doping ban]] in 2016, he won the [[young rider classification]] in the [[2017 Tour de France]] and the [[general classification]] in the [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]. Yates has also won multiple stages at each of cycling's three [[Grand Tour (cycling)|grand tours]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\n[[File:Simon Yates.jpg|upright|thumbnail|left|Yates in 2012]]\nThe brothers took up cycling after their father John was injured in a collision with a car while riding. During John's recovery he took the twins to [[Manchester Velodrome]] to track sessions run by his cycling club, Bury Clarion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buryclarion.co.uk/|title=Home - Bury Clarion Cycling Club|work=Bury Clarion Cycling Club}}</ref> to keep in touch with the other members. Both brothers soon started riding on the road for Bury Clarion and on the track for Eastlands Velo.\n\nAt the age of 18, Simon was selected by [[British Cycling]] for its Olympic Academy programme. He was also selected for the England team for the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Delhi]], where his room-mate was [[Chris Froome]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/29391092 |title=Simon and Adam Yates: Bury boys on a twin track to the top |last1=Slater |first1=Matt|date=27 September 2014 |website=[[bbc.co.uk]] |accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe won the gold medal in the [[points race]] at the [[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships|2013 Track World Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bevan|first=Chris|title=Jason Kenny and Simon Yates win World cycling golds for Britain|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/21546329|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=22 February 2013|location=Minsk, Belarus|date=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nSimon made his breakthrough on the road in 2013 riding for the British national team. Along with brother Adam, he competed at the 2013 [[Tour de l'Avenir]] for the Great Britain national team, where Simon won the race's fifth stage, ahead of Adam.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/cycling/news/15264/8895597/simon-yates-and-brother-adam-finish-first-and-second-on-stage-five-of-tour-de-lavenir|title=Simon Yates and brother Adam finish first and second on stage five of Tour de l'Avenir|work=[[Sky Sports]]|publisher=[[BSkyB]]|date=29 August 2013|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> Simon added another stage victory the following day,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/cycling/news/15264/8897673/|title=Simon Yates claims second successive Tour de l'Avenir win with victory on stage six|work=[[Sky Sports]]|publisher=[[BSkyB]]|date=30 August 2013|accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref> and finished the race tenth overall.\n\nHe was then selected as part of the British national team to take part in the [[2013 Tour of Britain|Tour of Britain]]. He competed well throughout the race and on stage six he took his biggest win to that point, on the summit finish at [[Haytor]], sprinting clear of a nine-man group, which included [[Bradley Wiggins]] and [[Nairo Quintana]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour of Britain \u2013 Yates wins stage six, Wiggins maintains overall lead|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/tour-britain-yates-wins-stage-six-wiggins-maintains-134817871--spt.html|publisher=Yahoo Eurosport|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tour of Britain: Simon Yates wins stage six, Bradley Wiggins leads|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/24178704|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref>\nYates finished third overall in the Tour of Britain, and was the best rider in the under-23 classification.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour of Britain 2013, stage eight: Sir Bradley Wiggins triumphs after Mark Cavendish sprints to London victory|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/cycling/10326934/Tour-of-Britain-2013-stage-eight-Sir-Bradley-Wiggins-triumphs-after-Mark-Cavendish-sprints-to-London-victory.html|publisher=Telegraph Online|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Orica\u2013GreenEDGE/Mitchelton SCOTT (2014\u2013present)===\n====2014====\n[[File:Simon Yates-Croix des Moinats (cropped).JPG|upright|thumb|left|Yates at the [[2014 Tour de France]]]]\nYates along with his brother joined the Australian [[UCI World Tour]] team {{ct|OBE|2014}} in 2014.<ref name=\"Orica\"/> He finished 12th Overall in one of his first World Tour races, the [[2014 Tour of the Basque Country|Tour of the Basque Country]]. Yates suffered a broken collarbone on Stage 3 of the [[2014 Tour of Turkey|Tour of Turkey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-crashes-out-of-the-tour-of-turkey|title=Simon Yates crashes out of the Tour of Turkey|author=Cycling News|work=Cyclingnews.com}}</ref> He recovered to take seventh overall and the Young Riders Classification in the [[2014 Tour of Slovenia|Tour of Slovenia]] in June. He was a surprise selection for the {{ct|OBE|2014|nolink=yes}} team for the [[2014 Tour de France]], with only 5 days' notice, and was one of only 4 British riders to take to the Grand Depart startline in [[Leeds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/28111981|title=BBC Sport - Tour de France: Britain's Simon Yates handed unexpected berth|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> Yates featured in two breakaways during his Grand Tour debut, before being withdrawn by his team on the second rest day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/racing/tour-de-france/simon-yates-withdraws-tour-de-france-130712|title=Simon Yates withdraws from Tour de France|date=21 July 2014|work=Cycling Weekly}}</ref>\n\n====2015====\nIn April 2015 Yates finished fifth overall in the [[2015 Tour of the Basque Country|Tour of the Basque Country]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.bt.com/more-sport-hub/more-sport/yates-clinches-fifth-placed-finish-S11363975112013|title=Yates clinches fifth-placed finish|work=BT.com}}</ref> Later that month he rode the [[2015 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandie]] and placed sixth overall. In June 2015 Yates finished fifth overall in the [[2015 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9]] after finishing second behind [[Chris Froome]] on the final stage, a summit finish at [[Modane]]. By doing so Yates also won the White Jersey as best young rider.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/33127651|title=Criterium du Dauphine: Chris Froome wins second title|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHe was again selected for the [[2015 Tour de France]], this time alongside his brother Adam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/jun/27/tour-de-france-2015-yates-twins-orica|title=Tour de France 2015: Yates twins ready for coming of age with Orica|first=William|last=Fotheringham|date=27 June 2015|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref> Simon placed eighth on Stage 3, which finished on the [[Mur de Huy]], and eleventh on Stage 20, the queen stage of the race finishing on [[Alpe d'Huez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.velon.cc/teamnews/yates-brothers-show-strength-on-alpe-dhuez/|title=Velon - Team Hub|website=www.velon.cc}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n[[File:Simon Yates Madone d'Utelle 2016.JPG|upright|thumb|Yates at the [[2016 Paris-Nice]]]]\nIn March 2016, Yates finished seventh overall at [[2016 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]], however, in April it emerged that Yates had tested positive for the banned substance [[terbutaline]] in an in-competition test during the race.<ref name=\"doping2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/36166128|title=Simon Yates: British cyclist fails drug test 'due to asthma inhaler'|date=29 April 2016|website=[[bbc.co.uk]]|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref> Yates was disqualified from the race and served a four-month doping ban during 2016; his team took full responsibility for this blaming an \"administrative error\". The ban meant Yates missed the [[2016 Tour de France]], where his brother Adam finished fourth overall and won the [[Young rider classification in the Tour de France|Young rider classification]].\n\nFollowing the expiry of his doping suspension, he was named in the startlist for the [[2016 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]].<ref name=\"Vuelta2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Vuelta_a_Espana_2016_Startlist|title=71st Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|work=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref> In stage 6 Yates, seeing an opportunity, escaped from a breakaway group to win a solo stage victory - the first of the Yates brothers to take a Grand Tour stage victory.\n\n====2017====\n[[File:Meilleur Jeune \u00e0 l'arriv\u00e9e du Tour de France 2017 \u00e0 Chamb\u00e9ry.JPG|left|thumb|Yates wearing the White Jersey at the [[2017 Tour de France]]]]\n2017 saw Yates collect stage wins at two prestigious stage races, [[2017 Paris-Nice|Paris-Nice]] and the [[2017 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandie]]. He placed second at the latter, his highest finish in a [[UCI World Tour]] stage-race at the time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour de Romandie: Britain's Simon Yates second as Richie Porte wins on final stage|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/39763157|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> He finished 7th overall at the [[2017 Tour de France|Tour de France]] and won the young rider classification, matching the feat achieved by his twin brother a year prior.\n\n====2018: Grand Tour success====\nYates confirmed his and the team's plans for him participating in the [[2018 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]] and the [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/tour-de-france/adam-yates-will-lead-mitchelton-scott-team-tour-de-france-simon-yates-giro-vuelta-363464|title=Adam Yates will lead Mitchelton-Scott team at 2018 Tour de France; Simon Yates to Giro and Vuelta - Cycling Weekly|date=2017-12-15|work=Cycling Weekly|access-date=2018-03-02|language=en-US}}</ref> In March, Yates won Stage 7 of the [[2018 Paris\u2013Nice]], a mountain top finish to [[Valdeblore|Valdeblore La Colmiane]], to take the overall race lead going into the final stage. However, on Stage 8 [[Marc Soler]] of the {{ct|MOV|2018}}, who started the final stage 37 seconds down on Yates in sixth place overall, attacked around halfway into the stage along with compatriot [[David de la Cruz]] ({{ct|SKY|2018}}); the duo joined [[Omar Fraile]] ({{ct|AST|2018}}) at the head of the race, and the trio managed to stay clear of the rest of the field by the time they reached [[Nice]]. As de la Cruz and Fraile contested stage honours, Soler finished third \u2013 acquiring four bonus seconds on the finish in addition to three gained at an earlier intermediate sprint \u2013 and with a 35-second gap to Yates and the remaining general classification contenders, it was enough to give Soler victory over Yates by four seconds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/marc-soler-grabs-paris-nice-title-four-seconds-simon-yates-final-stage-372464|title=Marc Soler grabs Paris-Nice title by four seconds from Simon Yates on final stage|first=Richard|last=Windsor|work=[[Cycling Weekly]]|publisher=[[TI Media]]|date=11 March 2018|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> Later that month, Yates won stage 7 of the [[2017 Volta a Catalunya|Volta a Catalunya]] after attacking multiple times on the {{convert|6.6|km|abbr=off|adj=on}} laps of the hilly final circuit through the [[Montju\u00efc]] Park. By doing so he finished fourth overall in the race.<ref>http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/volta-ciclista-a-catalunya-2018/stage-7/results/</ref>\n\n[[File:GIR40263 simon yates.jpg|thumb|Yates wearing the [[Maglia rosa]] at the [[2018 Giro d'Italia]]]]\nYates entered the Giro d'Italia as joint leader of {{ct|MTS men|2018}} with [[Esteban Chaves]], supported by a strong climbing focused team including [[Roman Kreuziger]], [[Mikel Nieve]] and [[Jack Haig (cyclist)|Jack Haig]].<ref>https://www.eurosport.com/cycling/giro-d-italia/2018/yates-ready-to-lead-team-at-debut-giro-d-italia_sto6730182/story.shtml</ref> Yates placed seventh in the opening {{convert|9.7|km|abbr=off|adj=on}} individual time trial in [[Jerusalem]], 20 seconds down on the defending champion and world time trial champion [[Tom Dumoulin]] ({{ct|SUN|2018}}).<ref>http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/giro-ditalia/tom-dumoulin-stamps-authority-giro-ditalia-stage-one-time-trial-victory-378738</ref> On Stage 6 to [[Mount Etna]], Yates took the race lead after finishing second behind teammate Chaves. Yates attacked from the group of favourites {{convert|1.5|km|abbr=off}} from the summit and caught Chaves, who had been part of the day's breakaway, in sight of the line, but waved Chaves through to claim the stage honours.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} The result meant Yates held the [[Maglia rosa]] over Dumoulin in second, and over Chaves in third place. Yates won stage 9 after accelerating away with {{convert|100|m|abbr=off}} to go on the summit finish to [[Gran Sasso d'Italia]], extending his lead over Chaves, and Dumoulin.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/44101703</ref> Yates extended his lead further on Stage 10, but teammate Chaves dropped out of contention after finishing 25 minutes down after being dropped on the first climb.<ref>http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-im-very-disappointed-for-esteban/</ref> Yates claimed his second stage victory on Stage 11, attacking with {{convert|1.5|km|abbr=off}} to go and holding off the pursuit of Dumoulin to win on hill top finish in [[Osimo]]. Yates increased his lead over Dumoulin.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/44145175</ref>\n\nOn Stage 14, Yates finished second behind [[Chris Froome]] ({{ct|SKY|2018}}) on [[Monte Zoncolan]]. With six bonus seconds for finishing second, Yates extended his overall advantage over Dumoulin, whilst his gap over Froome was 3 minutes 10 seconds.<ref>http://www.skysports.com/cycling/news/15264/11378651/chris-froome-wins-giro-ditalia-stage-14-as-simon-yates-extends-overall-lead</ref> Yates pedaled to a solo win on stage 15 to [[Sappada]], attacking with {{convert|18|km|abbr=off}} remaining, increasing his lead over Dumoulin.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/44190618</ref> On Stage 17, a {{convert|34.2|km|abbr=off|adj=on}} individual time trial from [[Trento]] to [[Rovereto]], Yates held on to his overall lead over Dumoulin.<ref>http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/giro-ditalia/simon-yates-holds-onto-pink-rohan-dennis-wins-giro-ditalia-stage-16-time-trial-380857#4wKbq8I7I1Ph4pTm.99</ref> On stage 18 to [[Prato Nevoso]] Yates cracked on the final slopes of the summit finish and lost 28 seconds to all of his other general classification rivals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/giro-d-italia/2018/stage-18-gc|title=Giro d'Italia 2018 - Stage 18|website=www.procyclingstats.com}}</ref> Stage 19 of the race had been classified as the '[[queen stage]]' of the race, with three focussed climbs in the latter half of the stage. These included the half paved-half gravel climb of the [[Colle delle Finestre]], followed by the climb to [[Sestriere]] and the final uphill finish too [[Bardonecchia]]. Yates cracked on the lower slopes of the Finestre, before Froome launched a solo attack with {{convert|80|km|abbr=off}} left of the stage. Froome's advantage grew throughout the second half of the stage, culminating in him taking a stage victory of more than three minutes and thereby also taking the overall race lead, 40 seconds ahead of Dumoulin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/giro-d-italia/2018/stage-19|title=Giro d'Italia 2018 - Stage 19|website=www.procyclingstats.com}}</ref> Yates lost over 38 minutes to Froome and dropped to 17th overall.<ref>http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-i-was-just-really-tired-and-exhausted/</ref> He eventually finished the race 21st overall, 1 hour and 15 minutes behind the winner Froome.<ref>https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/giro-d-italia/2018/gc</ref>\n[[File:Carmena entrega los premios a dos de los triunfadores de La Vuelta 02.jpg|left|thumb|Yates (centre) on the podium at the [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]].]]\nAfter the Giro, Yates made his return to racing at the [[Prueba Villafranca de Ordizia]], where he finished second behind team-mate [[Robert Power (Australian cyclist)|Robert Power]]. He subsequently returned to WorldTour competition at the [[2018 Tour de Pologne|Tour de Pologne]] in August, where he won the race's closing stage with a solo attack and finished second overall behind [[Micha\u0142 Kwiatkowski]].<ref name=af>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-on-track-for-vuelta-a-espana-in-final-countdown/ |title=Simon Yates on track for Vuelta a Espana in final countdown |last=Fotheringham |first=Alasdair |author-link=Alasdair Fotheringham |date=23 August 2018|website=[[cyclingnews.com]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nYates was {{ct|MTS men|2018|nolink=yes}}'s team leader for the [[2018 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]], with support from his brother.<ref name=af /> Yates moved into third place on the general classification after stage 4, the first mountain stage, ten seconds behind leader Kwiatkowski. On the ninth stage, Yates took the leader's red jersey from [[Rudy Molard]] going into the first rest day.<ref name=ee>{{cite web |url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/how-simon-yates-set-his-winning-course-at-la-vuelta-2/ |title=How Simon Yates set his winning course at La Vuelta|date=16 September 2018 |website=[[eveningexpress.co.uk]] |access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> However he lost the lead on stage 12, when {{ct|MTS men|2018|nolink=yes}} elected not to close down a large breakaway, with the red jersey being taken by [[Jes\u00fas Herrada]] with Yates in second and Valverde in third.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/45437610 |title=Vuelta a Espana: Jesus Herrada takes leader's jersey from Simon Yates|date=6 September 2018 |website=[[bbc.co.uk]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> However the following day Yates cut nearly two minutes from Herrada's lead,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/sep/07/oscar-rodriguez-snatches-vuelta-victory-jesus-herrada-lead-cut-simon-yates-cycling |title=Oscar Rodriguez snatches Vuelta win while Simon Yates mounts attack|date=7 September 2018 |website= [[theguardian.com]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> and he then took victory on the fourteenth stage, reclaiming the overall lead. He extended his lead during stage 16 (an individual time trial) and stage 19.<ref name=ee /> On the last mountain stage the following day, Yates attacked his rivals on the penultimate climb, joining [[Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez (cyclist)|Miguel \u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez]] and [[Nairo Quintana]] alongside [[Enric Mas]] at the head of the race, and eventually finishing third on the stage behind Mas and L\u00f3pez, who moved up into second and third overall after Valverde and [[Steven Kruijswijk]] lost significant time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/vuelta-a-espana/simon-yates-sets-vuelta-espana-2018-overall-victory-enric-mas-wins-gruelling-stage-20-394472 |title=Simon Yates sets up Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a 2018 overall victory as Enric Mas wins gruelling stage 20 |last=Windsor |first=Richard |date=15 September 2018 |website=[[Cycling Weekly]] |access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> He went on to safely cross the finish line on the last stage in Madrid to secure his overall victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/45540766 |title=Simon Yates: British cyclist wins first Grand Tour at Vuelta a Espana|date=16 September 2018 |website=[[bbc.co.uk]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2019====\nSimon previously considered time-trialling to be a weakness,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/tour-de-france/simon-yates-admits-time-trialling-may-always-weakness-heads-tour-de-france-337454|title=Simon Yates admits his time trialling may always be a weakness as he heads to the Tour de France|last=Pitt|first=Vern|date=2017-06-27|website=Cycling Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> and his slowly improved since his junior years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/simon-yates-my-advantage-could-be-wiped-out-in-time-trial-mb2cp8v2m|title=Simon Yates: my advantage could be wiped out in time-trial|last=Burrows|first=Josh|date=2018-05-22|work=The Times|access-date=2019-07-30|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> He had improved in 2019, with his first win in the discipline, in a hilly course at [[2019 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris-Nice]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/simon-yates-wasnt-expecting-time-trial-win-410630|title=Simon Yates: 'I wasn't expecting time trial win'|last=Cossins|first=Peter|date=2019-03-14|website=Cycling Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref> This course may have suited him and other climbers, rather than TT specialists, due to the lumpy profile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/simon-yates-takes-first-ever-time-trial-victory-paris-nice-2019-stage-five-410559|title=Simon Yates takes first career time trial victory on Paris-Nice 2019 stage five|last=Ballinger|first=Alex|date=2019-03-14|website=Cycling Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\nYates returned to the [[2019 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]] aiming for the general classification. He entered the race, publicly stating that he considered himself as \"the number one favourite\" for the [[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|general classification]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-im-the-number-one-favourite-for-the-giro-ditalia/|website=www.cyclingnews.com|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> He started, showing superb{{according to whom|date=August 2019}} form on the opening stage, an individual time-trial in [[Bologna]], where he finished second behind [[Primo\u017e Rogli\u010d]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/48241353|title=Giro d'Italia: Simon Yates makes strong start behind winner Primoz Roglic in opening time trial|date=2019-05-11|access-date=2019-07-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> Yates's hopes of the overall win looked all but over after a disastrous{{according to whom|date=August 2019}} stage 9 time-trial that saw him lose over 3 minutes, dropping to 24th overall. He lost further time on stage 13 up to [[Serr\u00f9 Lake|Lago Seru]]. Despite a second-place finish on stage 19, he finished 8th on GC, and described it as heartbreaking.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-vows-to-come-back-to-try-again-after-heartbreaking-giro-ditalia/|website=www.cyclingnews.com|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n\nHe rode Le Tour de France, in support of his brother's GC ambition, but Simon was allowed a day off [[domestique]] duty{{failed verification|date=July 2019}}, and won stage 12 into [[Bagn\u00e8res-de-Bigorre|Bagnerres-de-Bigorre]] in a 3 up sprint against [[Pello Bilbao|Bilbao]] and [[Gregor M\u00fchlberger|Muhlberger]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/tour-de-france/simon-yates-wasnt-confident-winning-final-sprint-tour-de-france-stage-12-431759|title=Simon Yates 'wasn't confident' of winning final sprint of Tour de France stage 12|last=Brown|first=Gregor|date=2019-07-18|website=Cycling Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref> Unfortunately for Adam, his GC hopes faded after losing time on the individual time-trial and the climb to [[Col du Tourmalet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/tour-de-france-dream-over-for-adam-yates-after-tourmalet-stage/|website=www.cyclingnews.com|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref> These GC losses freed up Simon as the team refocused on stage wins,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenedgecycling.com/news/adam-yates-drops-out-of-contention-after-tough-stage-14|title=Mitchelton-SCOTT to change focus after dropping out of GC contention of stage 14 of the TdF|website=Mitchelton-SCOTT GreenEDGE Cycling|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> and he added another mountain stage win after a ferocious{{according to whom|date=July 2019}} solo attack on stage 15,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/49064307|title=Tour de France 2019: Simon Yates wins stage 15 as Geraint Thomas gains time|date=2019-07-21|access-date=2019-07-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> taking [[Mitchelton\u2013Scott (men's team)|Mitchelton-Scott]]'s tally to 3 before the second rest day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenedgecycling.com/news/a-second-stage-victory-for-simon-yates-to-make-it-a-hat-trick-of-wins-for-mitchelton-scott-at-the-tour-de-france|title=A second stage victory for Simon Yates makes it a hat-trick of wins for MTS at the Tour de France {{!}} Mitchelton-SCOTT GreenEDGE Cycling|website=www.greenedgecycling.com|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n\n==Doping ban==\nIn April 2016 it emerged that Yates had tested positive for the banned substance [[terbutaline]] in an in-competition test during [[2016 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]] the previous month,<ref name=\"doping2\"/> where he finished seventh overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cycling/2016/03/13/geraint-thomas-wins-paris-nice-to-claim-biggest-title-of-career/|title=Geraint Thomas wins Paris-Nice to claim biggest title of career|last1=Cary|first1=Tom|date=13 March 2016|website=[[telegraph.co.uk]]|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref> {{ct|ORS|2016a}}'s owner [[Gerry Ryan (businessman)|Gerry Ryan]] accused [[British Cycling]] of leaking the news of Yates' failed drug test to the press, and criticised the organisation for doing so.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/apr/29/orica-greenedge-british-cycling-leak-simon-yates</ref> In a statement, {{ct|ORS|2016a|nolink=yes}} claimed full responsibility for the test result, saying that the team's doctor had failed to apply for a therapeutic use exemption for an asthma inhaler used by Yates which triggered the positive test.<ref name=\"doping2\" /> Subsequently, the international governing body [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] issued a statement indicating that Yates would not be provisionally suspended from competition due to the substance he had tested positive for.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cycling/36169275|title=Simon Yates: UCI not suspending cyclist despite failed drugs test|website=[[bbc.co.uk]]|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June, the UCI decided to issue a four-month ban for the \"presence and use of the specified prohibited substance terbutaline\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uci.ch/pressreleases/uci-statement-simon-yates/|title=UCI statement on Simon Yates|website=www.uci.ch|access-date=2018-05-25}}</ref> backdated from 12 March (the date the positive sample was collected), preventing Yates from competing at the [[2016 Tour de France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/simon-yates-handed-four-month-non-intentional-doping-ban/|title=Simon Yates handed four-month 'non-intentional' doping ban|date=17 June 2016|work=Cycling News|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career achievements==\n===Major results===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;2010\n: [[UCI Juniors Track World Championships|UCI Junior Track World Championships]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey rainbow.svg|20px]] Madison (with [[Daniel McLay|Dan McLay]])\n::2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] Team pursuit\n: [[British National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n::2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] Points race\n::2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] Scratch race\n: 1st [[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] [[British National Madison Championships|Madison]] (with [[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]]), [[British National Track Championships|National Junior Track Championships]]\n;2011\n: 1st Stage 6 [[Tour de l'Avenir]]\n: 1st [[Six Days of Ghent]] Future Stars (with [[Owain Doull]])\n: 1st Pro-Am Classic\n: 2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] Omnium, [[British National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n: 3rd [[File:Bronze medal blank.svg|15px]] [[2010\u201311 UCI Track Cycling World Cup Classics|Team pursuit]] \u2013 Beijing, [[UCI Track Cycling World Cup Classics|UCI Track World Cup]]\n: 9th Overall [[Th\u00fcringen Rundfahrt der U23]]\n;2012\n: [[British National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n::1st [[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] [[British National Madison Championships|Madison]] (with [[Mark Christian]])\n::1st [[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] [[British National Team Pursuit Championships|Team pursuit]]\n;2013\n: 1st [[File:Jersey rainbow.svg|20px]] [[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships \u2013 Men's points race|Points race]], [[2013 UCI Track Cycling World Championships|UCI Track World Championships]]\n: 1st [[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] [[British National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Under\u201323 Road Championships\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall Arden Challenge\n::1st Stage 4\n: 3rd Overall [[2013 Tour of Britain|Tour of Britain]]\n::1st Stage 6\n: 3rd [[La C\u00f4te Picarde]]\n: 9th Overall [[R\u00e1s Tailteann|An Post R\u00e1s]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Young rider classification\n: 10th Overall [[Tour de l'Avenir]]\n::1st Stages 5 & 6\n: 10th Overall [[Fl\u00e8che du Sud]]\n: 10th Overall [[Th\u00fcringen Rundfahrt der U23]]\n: 10th Overall [[Czech Cycling Tour]]\n;2014\n: 1st [[File:Jersey polkadot.svg|20px]] Mountains classification [[2014 Tour of Alberta|Tour of Alberta]]\n: 3rd [[British National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Road Championships\n: 7th Overall [[2014 Tour of Slovenia|Tour of Slovenia]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Young rider classification\n;2015\n: 5th Overall [[2015 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Young rider classification\n: 5th Overall [[2015 Tour of the Basque Country|Tour of the Basque Country]]\n: 6th Overall [[2015 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandi